B001C032V023	1	32	23	He took them, and sent them over the stream, and sent over that which he had.
B001C032V024	1	32	24	Jacob was left alone, and wrestled with a man there until the breaking of the day.
B001C032V025	1	32	25	When he saw that he did not prevail against him, he touched the hollow of his thigh, and the hollow of Jacob's thigh was strained, as he wrestled.
B001C032V026	1	32	26	The man said, "Let me go, for the day breaks."
B001C032V027	1	32	27	He said to him, "What is your name?"He said, "Jacob."
B001C032V028	1	32	28	He said, "Your name will no longer be called Jacob, but Israel; for you have fought with God and with men, and have prevailed."
B001C032V029	1	32	29	Jacob asked him, "Please tell me your name."
B001C032V030	1	32	30	Jacob called the name of the place Peniel: for, he said, "I have seen God face to face, and my life is preserved."
B001C032V031	1	32	31	The sun rose on him as he passed over Peniel, and he limped because of his thigh.
B001C032V032	1	32	32	Therefore the children of Israel do not eat the sinew of the hip, which is on the hollow of the thigh, to this day, because he touched the hollow of Jacob's thigh in the sinew of the hip.
B001C033V001	1	33	1	Jacob lifted up his eyes, and looked, and, behold, Esau was coming, and with him four hundred men. He divided the children between Leah, Rachel, and the two handmaids.
B001C033V002	1	33	2	He put the handmaids and their children in front, Leah and her children after, and Rachel and Joseph at the rear.
B001C033V003	1	33	3	He himself passed over in front of them, and bowed himself to the ground seven times, until he came near to his brother.
B001C033V004	1	33	4	Esau ran to meet him, embraced him, fell on his neck, kissed him, and they wept.
B001C033V005	1	33	5	He lifted up his eyes, and saw the women and the children; and said, "Who are these with you?"He said, "The children whom God has graciously given your servant."
B001C033V006	1	33	6	Then the handmaids came near with their children, and they bowed themselves.
B001C033V007	1	33	7	Leah also and her children came near, and bowed themselves. After them, Joseph came near with Rachel, and they bowed themselves.
B001C033V008	1	33	8	Esau said, "What do you mean by all this company which I met?"
B001C033V009	1	33	9	Esau said, "I have enough, my brother; let that which you have be yours."
B001C033V010	1	33	10	Jacob said, "Please, no, if I have now found favor in your sight, then receive my present at my hand, because I have seen your face, as one sees the face of God, and you were pleased with me.
B001C033V011	1	33	11	Please take the gift that I brought to you, because God has dealt graciously with me, and because I have enough." He urged him, and he took it.
B001C033V012	1	33	12	Esau said, "Let us take our journey, and let us go, and I will go before you."
B001C033V013	1	33	13	Jacob said to him, "My lord knows that the children are tender, and that the flocks and herds with me have their young, and if they overdrive them one day, all the flocks will die.
B001C033V014	1	33	14	Please let my lord pass over before his servant, and I will lead on gently, according to the pace of the livestock that are before me and according to the pace of the children, until I come to my lord to Seir."
B001C033V015	1	33	15	Esau said, "Let me now leave with you some of the folk who are with me."
B001C033V016	1	33	16	So Esau returned that day on his way to Seir.
B001C033V017	1	33	17	Jacob traveled to Succoth, built himself a house, and made shelters for his livestock. Therefore the name of the place is called Succoth.
B001C033V018	1	33	18	Jacob came in peace to the city of Shechem, which is in the land of Canaan, when he came from Paddan Aram; and encamped before the city.
B001C033V019	1	33	19	He bought the parcel of ground where he had spread his tent, at the hand of the children of Hamor, Shechem's father, for one hundred pieces of money.
B001C033V020	1	33	20	He erected an altar there, and called it El Elohe Israel.
B001C034V001	1	34	1	Dinah, the daughter of Leah, whom she bore to Jacob, went out to see the daughters of the land.
B001C034V002	1	34	2	Shechem the son of Hamor the Hivite, the prince of the land, saw her. He took her, lay with her, and humbled her.
B001C034V003	1	34	3	His soul joined to Dinah, the daughter of Jacob, and he loved the young lady, and spoke kindly to the young lady.
B001C034V004	1	34	4	Shechem spoke to his father, Hamor, saying, "Get me this young lady as a wife."
B001C034V005	1	34	5	Now Jacob heard that he had defiled Dinah, his daughter; and his sons were with his livestock in the field. Jacob held his peace until they came.
B001C034V006	1	34	6	Hamor the father of Shechem went out to Jacob to talk with him.
B001C034V007	1	34	7	The sons of Jacob came in from the field when they heard it. The men were grieved, and they were very angry, because he had done folly in Israel in lying with Jacob's daughter; a which thing ought not to be done.
B001C034V008	1	34	8	Hamor talked with them, saying, "The soul of my son, Shechem, longs for your daughter. Please give her to him as a wife.
B001C034V009	1	34	9	Make marriages with us. Give your daughters to us, and take our daughters for yourselves.
B001C034V010	1	34	10	You shall dwell with us, and the land will be before you. Live and trade in it, and get possessions in it."
B001C034V011	1	34	11	Shechem said to her father and to her brothers, "Let me find favor in your eyes, and whatever you will tell me I will give.
B001C034V012	1	34	12	Ask me a great amount for a dowry, and I will give whatever you ask of me, but give me the young lady as a wife."
B001C034V013	1	34	13	The sons of Jacob answered Shechem and Hamor his father with deceit, and spoke, because he had defiled Dinah their sister,
B001C034V014	1	34	14	and said to them, "We can't do this thing, to give our sister to one who is uncircumcised; for that is a reproach to us.
B001C034V015	1	34	15	Only on this condition will we consent to you. If you will be as we are, that every male of you be circumcised;
B001C034V016	1	34	16	then will we give our daughters to you, and we will take your daughters to us, and we will dwell with you, and we will become one people.
B001C034V017	1	34	17	But if you will not listen to us, to be circumcised, then we will take our sister, and we will be gone."
B001C034V018	1	34	18	Their words pleased Hamor and Shechem, Hamor's son.
B001C034V019	1	34	19	The young man did not wait to do this thing, because he had delight in Jacob's daughter, and he was honored above all the house of his father.
B001C034V020	1	34	20	Hamor and Shechem, his son, came to the gate of their city, and talked with the men of their city, saying,
B001C034V021	1	34	21	"These men are peaceful with us. Therefore let them live in the land and trade in it. For behold, the land is large enough for them. Let us take their daughters to us for wives, and let us give them our daughters.
B001C034V022	1	34	22	Only on this condition will the men consent to us to live with us, to become one people, if every male among us is circumcised, as they are circumcised.
B001C034V023	1	34	23	Won't their livestock and their possessions and all their animals be ours? Only let us give our consent to them, and they will dwell with us."
B001C034V024	1	34	24	All who went out of the gate of his city listened to Hamor, and to Shechem his son; and every male was circumcised, all who went out of the gate of his city.
B001C034V025	1	34	25	It happened on the third day, when they were sore, that two of Jacob's sons, Simeon and Levi, Dinah's brothers, each took his sword, came upon the unsuspecting city, and killed all the males.
B001C034V026	1	34	26	They killed Hamor and Shechem, his son, with the edge of the sword, and took Dinah out of Shechem's house, and went away.
B001C034V027	1	34	27	Jacob's sons came on the dead, and plundered the city, because they had defiled their sister.
B001C034V028	1	34	28	They took their flocks, their herds, their donkeys, that which was in the city, that which was in the field,
B001C034V029	1	34	29	and all their wealth. They took captive all their little ones and their wives, and took as plunder everything that was in the house.
B001C034V030	1	34	30	Jacob said to Simeon and Levi, "You have troubled me, to make me odious to the inhabitants of the land, among the Canaanites and the Perizzites. I am few in number. They will gather themselves together against me and strike me, and I will be destroyed, I and my house."
B001C034V031	1	34	31	They said, "Should he deal with our sister as with a prostitute?"
B001C035V001	1	35	1	God said to Jacob, "Arise, go up to Bethel, and live there. Make there an altar to God, who appeared to you when you fled from the face of Esau your brother."
B001C035V002	1	35	2	Then Jacob said to his household, and to all who were with him, "Put away the foreign gods that are among you, purify yourselves, change your garments.
B001C035V003	1	35	3	Let us arise, and go up to Bethel. I will make there an altar to God, who answered me in the day of my distress, and was with me in the way which I went."
B001C035V004	1	35	4	They gave to Jacob all the foreign gods which were in their hands, and the rings which were in their ears; and Jacob hid them under the oak which was by Shechem.
B001C035V005	1	35	5	They traveled, and a terror of God was on the cities that were around them, and they did not pursue the sons of Jacob.
B001C035V006	1	35	6	So Jacob came to Luz (that is, Bethel), which is in the land of Canaan, he and all the people who were with him.
B001C035V007	1	35	7	He built an altar there, and called the place El Beth El; because there God was revealed to him, when he fled from the face of his brother.
B001C035V008	1	35	8	Deborah, Rebekah's nurse, died, and she was buried below Bethel under the oak; and its name was called Allon Bacuth.
B001C035V009	1	35	9	God appeared to Jacob again, when he came from Paddan Aram, and blessed him.
B001C035V010	1	35	10	God said to him, "Your name is Jacob. Your name shall not be Jacob any more, but your name will be Israel." He named him Israel.
B001C035V011	1	35	11	God said to him, "I am God Almighty. Be fruitful and multiply. A nation and a company of nations will be from you, and kings will come out of your body.
B001C035V012	1	35	12	The land which I gave to Abraham and Isaac, I will give it to you, and to your seed after you will I give the land."
B001C035V013	1	35	13	God went up from him in the place where he spoke with him.
B001C035V014	1	35	14	Jacob set up a pillar in the place where he spoke with him, a pillar of stone. He poured out a drink offering on it, and poured oil on it.
B001C035V015	1	35	15	Jacob called the name of the place where God spoke with him "Bethel."
B001C035V016	1	35	16	They traveled from Bethel. There was still some distance to come to Ephrath, and Rachel travailed. She had hard labor.
B001C035V017	1	35	17	When she was in hard labor, the midwife said to her, "Do not be afraid, for now you will have another son."
B001C035V018	1	35	18	It happened, as her soul was departing (for she died), that she named him Benoni, but his father named him Benjamin.
B001C035V019	1	35	19	Rachel died, and was buried in the way to Ephrath (the same is Bethlehem).
B001C035V020	1	35	20	Jacob set up a pillar on her grave. The same is the Pillar of Rachel's grave to this day.
B001C035V021	1	35	21	Israel traveled, and spread his tent beyond the tower of Eder.
B001C035V022	1	35	22	It happened, while Israel lived in that land, that Reuben went and lay with Bilhah, his father's concubine, and Israel heard of it.Now the sons of Jacob were twelve.
B001C035V023	1	35	23	The sons of Leah: Reuben (Jacob's firstborn), Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, and Zebulun.
B001C035V024	1	35	24	The sons of Rachel: Joseph and Benjamin.
B001C035V025	1	35	25	The sons of Bilhah (Rachel's handmaid): Dan and Naphtali.
B001C035V026	1	35	26	The sons of Zilpah (Leah's handmaid): Gad and Asher. These are the sons of Jacob, who were born to him in Paddan Aram.
B001C035V027	1	35	27	Jacob came to Isaac his father, to Mamre, to Kiriath Arba (which is Hebron), where Abraham and Isaac lived as foreigners.
B001C035V028	1	35	28	The days of Isaac were one hundred eighty years.
B001C035V029	1	35	29	Isaac gave up the spirit, and died, and was gathered to his people, old and full of days. Esau and Jacob, his sons, buried him.
B001C036V001	1	36	1	Now this is the history of the generations of Esau (that is, Edom).
B001C036V002	1	36	2	Esau took his wives from the daughters of Canaan: Adah the daughter of Elon, the Hittite; and Oholibamah the daughter of Anah, the daughter of Zibeon, the Hivite;
B001C036V003	1	36	3	and Basemath, Ishmael's daughter, sister of Nebaioth.
B001C036V004	1	36	4	Adah bore to Esau Eliphaz. Basemath bore Reuel.
B001C036V005	1	36	5	Oholibamah bore Jeush, Jalam, and Korah. These are the sons of Esau, who were born to him in the land of Canaan.
B001C036V006	1	36	6	Esau took his wives, his sons, his daughters, and all the members of his household, with his livestock, all his animals, and all his possessions, which he had gathered in the land of Canaan, and went into a land away from his brother Jacob.
B001C036V007	1	36	7	For their substance was too great for them to dwell together, and the land of their travels couldn't bear them because of their livestock.
B001C036V008	1	36	8	Esau lived in the hill country of Seir. Esau is Edom.
B001C036V009	1	36	9	This is the history of the generations of Esau the father of the Edomites in the hill country of Seir:
B001C036V010	1	36	10	these are the names of Esau's sons: Eliphaz, the son of Adah, the wife of Esau; and Reuel, the son of Basemath, the wife of Esau.
B001C036V011	1	36	11	The sons of Eliphaz were Teman, Omar, Zepho, and Gatam, and Kenaz.
B001C036V012	1	36	12	Timna was concubine to Eliphaz, Esau's son; and she bore to Eliphaz Amalek. These are the sons of Adah, Esau's wife.
B001C036V013	1	36	13	These are the sons of Reuel: Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah. These were the sons of Basemath, Esau's wife.
B001C036V014	1	36	14	These were the sons of Oholibamah, the daughter of Anah, the daughter of Zibeon, Esau's wife: she bore to Esau Jeush, Jalam, and Korah.
B001C036V015	1	36	15	These are the chiefs of the sons of Esau: the sons of Eliphaz the firstborn of Esau: chief Teman, chief Omar, chief Zepho, chief Kenaz,
B001C036V016	1	36	16	chief Korah, chief Gatam, chief Amalek: these are the chiefs who came of Eliphaz in the land of Edom; these are the sons of Adah.
B001C036V017	1	36	17	These are the sons of Reuel, Esau's son: chief Nahath, chief Zerah, chief Shammah, chief Mizzah: these are the chiefs who came of Reuel in the land of Edom; these are the sons of Basemath, Esau's wife.
B001C036V018	1	36	18	These are the sons of Oholibamah, Esau's wife: chief Jeush, chief Jalam, chief Korah: these are the chiefs who came of Oholibamah the daughter of Anah, Esau's wife.
B001C036V019	1	36	19	These are the sons of Esau (that is, Edom), and these are their chiefs.
B001C036V020	1	36	20	These are the sons of Seir the Horite, the inhabitants of the land: Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah,
B001C036V021	1	36	21	Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan. These are the chiefs who came of the Horites, the children of Seir in the land of Edom.
B001C036V022	1	36	22	The children of Lotan were Hori and Heman. Lotan's sister was Timna.
B001C036V023	1	36	23	These are the children of Shobal: Alvan, Manahath, Ebal, Shepho, and Onam.
B001C036V024	1	36	24	These are the children of Zibeon: Aiah and Anah. This is Anah who found the hot springs in the wilderness, as he fed the donkeys of Zibeon his father.
B001C036V025	1	36	25	These are the children of Anah: Dishon and Oholibamah, the daughter of Anah.
B001C036V026	1	36	26	These are the children of Dishon: Hemdan, Eshban, Ithran, and Cheran.
B001C036V027	1	36	27	These are the children of Ezer: Bilhan, Zaavan, and Akan.
B001C036V028	1	36	28	These are the children of Dishan: Uz and Aran.
B001C036V029	1	36	29	These are the chiefs who came of the Horites: chief Lotan, chief Shobal, chief Zibeon, chief Anah,
B001C036V030	1	36	30	chief Dishon, chief Ezer, and chief Dishan: these are the chiefs who came of the Horites, according to their chiefs in the land of Seir.
B001C036V031	1	36	31	These are the kings who reigned in the land of Edom, before any king reigned over the children of Israel.
B001C036V032	1	36	32	Bela, the son of Beor, reigned in Edom. The name of his city was Dinhabah.
B001C036V033	1	36	33	Bela died, and Jobab, the son of Zerah of Bozrah, reigned in his place.
B001C036V034	1	36	34	Jobab died, and Husham of the land of the Temanites reigned in his place.
B001C036V035	1	36	35	Husham died, and Hadad, the son of Bedad, who struck Midian in the field of Moab, reigned in his place. The name of his city was Avith.
B001C036V036	1	36	36	Hadad died, and Samlah of Masrekah reigned in his place.
B001C036V037	1	36	37	Samlah died, and Shaul of Rehoboth by the river, reigned in his place.
B001C036V038	1	36	38	Shaul died, and Baal Hanan, the son of Achbor reigned in his place.
B001C036V039	1	36	39	Baal Hanan the son of Achbor died, and Hadar reigned in his place. The name of his city was Pau. His wife's name was Mehetabel, the daughter of Matred, the daughter of Mezahab.
B001C036V040	1	36	40	These are the names of the chiefs who came from Esau, according to their families, after their places, and by their names: chief Timna, chief Alvah, chief Jetheth,
B001C036V041	1	36	41	chief Oholibamah, chief Elah, chief Pinon,
B001C036V042	1	36	42	chief Kenaz, chief Teman, chief Mibzar,
B001C036V043	1	36	43	chief Magdiel, and chief Iram. These are the chiefs of Edom, according to their habitations in the land of their possession. This is Esau, the father of the Edomites.
B001C037V001	1	37	1	Jacob lived in the land of his father's travels, in the land of Canaan.
B001C037V002	1	37	2	This is the history of the generations of Jacob. Joseph, being seventeen years old, was feeding the flock with his brothers. He was a boy with the sons of Bilhah and Zilpah, his father's wives. Joseph brought an evil report of them to their father.
B001C037V003	1	37	3	Now Israel loved Joseph more than all his children, because he was the son of his old age, and he made him a coat of many colors.
B001C037V004	1	37	4	His brothers saw that their father loved him more than all his brothers, and they hated him, and couldn't speak peaceably to him.
B001C037V005	1	37	5	Joseph dreamed a dream, and he told it to his brothers, and they hated him all the more.
B001C037V006	1	37	6	He said to them, "Please hear this dream which I have dreamed:
B001C037V007	1	37	7	for behold, we were binding sheaves in the field, and behold, my sheaf arose and also stood upright; and behold, your sheaves came around, and bowed down to my sheaf."
B001C037V008	1	37	8	His brothers said to him, "Will you indeed reign over us? Or will you indeed have dominion over us?" They hated him all the more for his dreams and for his words.
B001C037V009	1	37	9	He dreamed yet another dream, and told it to his brothers, and said, "Behold, I have dreamed yet another dream: and behold, the sun and the moon and eleven stars bowed down to me."
B001C037V010	1	37	10	He told it to his father and to his brothers. His father rebuked him, and said to him, "What is this dream that you have dreamed? Will I and your mother and your brothers indeed come to bow ourselves down to you to the earth?"
B001C037V011	1	37	11	His brothers envied him, but his father kept this saying in mind.
B001C037V012	1	37	12	His brothers went to feed their father's flock in Shechem.
B001C037V013	1	37	13	Israel said to Joseph, "Aren't your brothers feeding the flock in Shechem? Come, and I will send you to them." He said to him, "Here I am."
B001C037V014	1	37	14	He said to him, "Go now, see whether it is well with your brothers, and well with the flock; and bring me word again." So he sent him out of the valley of Hebron, and he came to Shechem.
B001C037V015	1	37	15	A certain man found him, and behold, he was wandering in the field. The man asked him, "What are you looking for?"
B001C037V016	1	37	16	He said, "I am looking for my brothers. Tell me, please, where they are feeding the flock."
B001C037V017	1	37	17	The man said, "They have left here, for I heard them say, 'Let us go to Dothan.'"Joseph went after his brothers, and found them in Dothan.
B001C037V018	1	37	18	They saw him afar off, and before he came near to them, they conspired against him to kill him.
B001C037V019	1	37	19	They said one to another, "Behold, this dreamer comes.
B001C037V020	1	37	20	Come now therefore, and let's kill him, and cast him into one of the pits, and we will say, 'An evil animal has devoured him.' We will see what will become of his dreams."
B001C037V021	1	37	21	Reuben heard it, and delivered him out of their hand, and said, "Let's not take his life."
B001C037V022	1	37	22	Reuben said to them, "Shed no blood. Throw him into this pit that is in the wilderness, but lay no hand on him"-that he might deliver him out of their hand, to restore him to his father.
B001C037V023	1	37	23	It happened, when Joseph came to his brothers, that they stripped Joseph of his coat, the coat of many colors that was on him;
B001C037V024	1	37	24	and they took him, and threw him into the pit. The pit was empty. There was no water in it.
B001C037V025	1	37	25	They sat down to eat bread, and they lifted up their eyes and looked, and saw a caravan of Ishmaelites was coming from Gilead, with their camels bearing spices and balm and myrrh, going to carry it down to Egypt.
B001C037V026	1	37	26	Judah said to his brothers, "What profit is it if we kill our brother and conceal his blood?
B001C037V027	1	37	27	Come, and let's sell him to the Ishmaelites, and not let our hand be on him; for he is our brother, our flesh." His brothers listened to him.
B001C037V028	1	37	28	Midianites who were merchants passed by, and they drew and lifted up Joseph out of the pit, and sold Joseph to the Ishmaelites for twenty pieces of silver. They brought Joseph into Egypt.
B001C037V029	1	37	29	Reuben returned to the pit; and saw that Joseph wasn't in the pit; and he tore his clothes.
B001C037V030	1	37	30	He returned to his brothers, and said, "The child is no more; and I, where will I go?"
B001C037V031	1	37	31	They took Joseph's coat, and killed a male goat, and dipped the coat in the blood.
B001C037V032	1	37	32	They took the coat of many colors, and they brought it to their father, and said, "We have found this. Examine it, now, whether it is your son's coat or not."
B001C037V033	1	37	33	He recognized it, and said, "It is my son's coat. An evil animal has devoured him. Joseph is without doubt torn in pieces."
B001C037V034	1	37	34	Jacob tore his clothes, and put sackcloth on his waist, and mourned for his son many days.
B001C037V035	1	37	35	All his sons and all his daughters rose up to comfort him, but he refused to be comforted. He said, "For I will go down to Sheol to my son mourning." His father wept for him.
B001C037V036	1	37	36	The Midianites sold him into Egypt to Potiphar, an officer of Pharaoh's, the captain of the guard.
B001C038V001	1	38	1	It happened at that time, that Judah went down from his brothers, and visited a certain Adullamite, whose name was Hirah.
B001C038V002	1	38	2	Judah saw there a daughter of a certain Canaanite whose name was Shua. He took her, and went in to her.
B001C038V003	1	38	3	She conceived, and bore a son; and he named him Er.
B001C038V004	1	38	4	She conceived again, and bore a son; and she named him Onan.
B001C038V005	1	38	5	She yet again bore a son, and named him Shelah: and he was at Chezib, when she bore him.
B001C038V006	1	38	6	Judah took a wife for Er, his firstborn, and her name was Tamar.
B001C038V007	1	38	7	Er, Judah's firstborn, was wicked in the sight of 
B001C038V008	1	38	8	Judah said to Onan, "Go in to your brother's wife, and perform the duty of a husband's brother to her, and raise up seed to your brother."
B001C038V009	1	38	9	Onan knew that the seed wouldn't be his; and it happened, when he went in to his brother's wife, that he spilled it on the ground, lest he should give seed to his brother.
B001C038V010	1	38	10	The thing which he did was evil in the sight of 
B001C038V011	1	38	11	Then Judah said to Tamar, his daughter-in-law, "Remain a widow in your father's house, until Shelah, my son, is grown up;" for he said, "Lest he also die, like his brothers." Tamar went and lived in her father's house.
