B018C005V027	18	5	27	Look this, we have searched it, so it is.Hear it, and know it for your good."
B018C006V001	18	6	1	Then Job answered,
B018C006V002	18	6	2	"Oh that my anguish were weighed,and all my calamity laid in the balances!
B018C006V003	18	6	3	For now it would be heavier than the sand of the seas,therefore have my words been rash.
B018C006V004	18	6	4	For the arrows of the Almighty are within me.My spirit drinks up their poison.The terrors of God set themselves in array against me.
B018C006V005	18	6	5	Does the wild donkey bray when he has grass?Or does the ox low over his fodder?
B018C006V006	18	6	6	Can that which has no flavor be eaten without salt?Or is there any taste in the white of an egg?
B018C006V007	18	6	7	My soul refuses to touch them.They are as loathsome food to me.
B018C006V008	18	6	8	"Oh that I might have my request,that God would grant the thing that I long for,
B018C006V009	18	6	9	even that it would please God to crush me;that he would let loose his hand, and cut me off!
B018C006V010	18	6	10	Be it still my consolation,yes, let me exult in pain that doesn't spare,that I have not denied the words of the Holy One.
B018C006V011	18	6	11	What is my strength, that I should wait?What is my end, that I should be patient?
B018C006V012	18	6	12	Is my strength the strength of stones?Or is my flesh of brass?
B018C006V013	18	6	13	Isn't it that I have no help in me,That wisdom is driven quite from me?
B018C006V014	18	6	14	"To him who is ready to faint, kindness should be shown from his friend;even to him who forsakes the fear of the Almighty.
B018C006V015	18	6	15	My brothers have dealt deceitfully as a brook,as the channel of brooks that pass away;
B018C006V016	18	6	16	Which are black by reason of the ice,in which the snow hides itself.
B018C006V017	18	6	17	In the dry season, they vanish.When it is hot, they are consumed out of their place.
B018C006V018	18	6	18	The caravans that travel beside them turn aside.They go up into the waste, and perish.
B018C006V019	18	6	19	The caravans of Tema looked.The companies of Sheba waited for them.
B018C006V020	18	6	20	They were distressed because they were confident.They came there, and were confounded.
B018C006V021	18	6	21	For now you are nothing.You see a terror, and are afraid.
B018C006V022	18	6	22	Did I say, 'Give to me?'or, 'Offer a present for me from your substance?'
B018C006V023	18	6	23	or, 'Deliver me from the adversary's hand?'or, 'Redeem me from the hand of the oppressors?'
B018C006V024	18	6	24	"Teach me, and I will hold my peace.Cause me to understand wherein I have erred.
B018C006V025	18	6	25	How forcible are words of uprightness!But your reproof, what does it reprove?
B018C006V026	18	6	26	Do you intend to reprove words,seeing that the speeches of one who is desperate are as wind?
B018C006V027	18	6	27	Yes, you would even cast lots for the fatherless,and make merchandise of your friend.
B018C006V028	18	6	28	Now therefore be pleased to look at me,for surely I shall not lie to your face.
B018C006V029	18	6	29	Please return.Let there be no injustice.Yes, return again.My cause is righteous.
B018C006V030	18	6	30	Is there injustice on my tongue?Can't my taste discern mischievous things?
B018C007V001	18	7	1	"Isn't a man forced to labor on earth? Aren't his days like the days of a hired hand?
B018C007V002	18	7	2	As a servant who earnestly desires the shadow,as a hireling who looks for his wages,
B018C007V003	18	7	3	so am I made to possess months of misery,wearisome nights are appointed to me.
B018C007V004	18	7	4	When I lie down, I say,'When shall I arise, and the night be gone?'I toss and turn until the dawning of the day.
B018C007V005	18	7	5	My flesh is clothed with worms and clods of dust.My skin closes up, and breaks out afresh.
B018C007V006	18	7	6	My days are swifter than a weaver's shuttle,and are spent without hope.
B018C007V007	18	7	7	Oh remember that my life is a breath.My eye shall no more see good.
B018C007V008	18	7	8	The eye of him who sees me shall see me no more.Your eyes shall be on me, but I shall not be.
B018C007V009	18	7	9	As the cloud is consumed and vanishes away,so he who goes down to Sheol shall come up no more.
B018C007V010	18	7	10	He shall return no more to his house,neither shall his place know him any more.
B018C007V011	18	7	11	"Therefore I will not keep silent.I will speak in the anguish of my spirit.I will complain in the bitterness of my soul.
B018C007V012	18	7	12	Am I a sea, or a sea monster,that you put a guard over me?
B018C007V013	18	7	13	When I say, 'My bed shall comfort me.My couch shall ease my complaint;'
B018C007V014	18	7	14	then you scare me with dreams,and terrify me through visions:
B018C007V015	18	7	15	so that my soul chooses strangling,death rather than my bones.
B018C007V016	18	7	16	I loathe my life.I do not want to live forever.Leave me alone, for my days are but a breath.
B018C007V017	18	7	17	What is man, that you should magnify him,that you should set your mind on him,
B018C007V018	18	7	18	that you should visit him every morning,and test him every moment?
B018C007V019	18	7	19	How long will you not look away from me,nor leave me alone until I swallow down my spittle?
B018C007V020	18	7	20	If I have sinned, what do I do to you, you watcher of men?Why have you set me as a mark for you,so that I am a burden to myself?
B018C007V021	18	7	21	Why do you not pardon my disobedience, and take away my iniquity?For now shall I lie down in the dust.You will seek me diligently, but I shall not be."
B018C008V001	18	8	1	Then Bildad the Shuhite answered,
B018C008V002	18	8	2	"How long will you speak these things?Shall the words of your mouth be a mighty wind?
B018C008V003	18	8	3	Does God pervert justice?Or does the Almighty pervert righteousness?
B018C008V004	18	8	4	If your children have sinned against him,He has delivered them into the hand of their disobedience.
B018C008V005	18	8	5	If you want to seek God diligently,make your supplication to the Almighty.
B018C008V006	18	8	6	If you were pure and upright,surely now he would awaken for you,and make the habitation of your righteousness prosperous.
B018C008V007	18	8	7	Though your beginning was small,yet your latter end would greatly increase.
B018C008V008	18	8	8	"Please inquire of past generations.Find out about the learning of their fathers.
B018C008V009	18	8	9	(For we are but of yesterday, and know nothing,because our days on earth are a shadow.)
B018C008V010	18	8	10	Shall they not teach you, tell you,and utter words out of their heart?
B018C008V011	18	8	11	"Can the papyrus grow up without mire?Can the rushes grow without water?
B018C008V012	18	8	12	While it is yet in its greenness, not cut down,it withers before any other reed.
B018C008V013	18	8	13	So are the paths of all who forget God.The hope of the godless man shall perish,
B018C008V014	18	8	14	Whose confidence shall break apart,Whose trust is a spider's web.
B018C008V015	18	8	15	He shall lean on his house, but it shall not stand.He shall cling to it, but it shall not endure.
B018C008V016	18	8	16	He is green before the sun.His shoots go forth over his garden.
B018C008V017	18	8	17	His roots are wrapped around the rock pile.He sees the place of stones.
B018C008V018	18	8	18	If he is destroyed from his place,then it shall deny him, saying, 'I have not seen you.'
B018C008V019	18	8	19	Behold, this is the joy of his way:out of the earth, others shall spring.
B018C008V020	18	8	20	"Behold, God will not cast away a blameless man,neither will he uphold the evildoers.
B018C008V021	18	8	21	He will still fill your mouth with laughter,your lips with shouting.
B018C008V022	18	8	22	Those who hate you shall be clothed with shame.The tent of the wicked shall be no more."
B018C009V001	18	9	1	Then Job answered,
B018C009V002	18	9	2	"Truly I know that it is so,but how can man be just with God?
B018C009V003	18	9	3	If he is pleased to contend with him,he can't answer him one time in a thousand.
B018C009V004	18	9	4	God who is wise in heart, and mighty in strength:who has hardened himself against him, and prospered?
B018C009V005	18	9	5	He removes the mountains, and they do not know it,when he overturns them in his anger.
B018C009V006	18	9	6	He shakes the earth out of its place.Its pillars tremble.
B018C009V007	18	9	7	He commands the sun, and it doesn't rise,and seals up the stars.
B018C009V008	18	9	8	He alone stretches out the heavens,and treads on the waves of the sea.
B018C009V009	18	9	9	He makes the Bear, Orion, and the Pleiades,and the chambers of the south.
B018C009V010	18	9	10	He does great things past finding out;yes, marvelous things without number.
B018C009V011	18	9	11	Behold, he goes by me, and I do not see him.He passes on also, but I do not perceive him.
B018C009V012	18	9	12	Behold, he snatches away.Who can hinder him?Who will ask him, 'What are you doing?'
B018C009V013	18	9	13	"God will not withdraw his anger.The helpers of Rahab stoop under him.
B018C009V014	18	9	14	How much less shall I answer him,And choose my words to argue with him?
B018C009V015	18	9	15	Though I were righteous, yet I wouldn't answer him.I would make supplication to my judge.
B018C009V016	18	9	16	If I had called, and he had answered me,yet I wouldn't believe that he listened to my voice.
B018C009V017	18	9	17	For he breaks me with a storm,and multiplies my wounds without cause.
B018C009V018	18	9	18	He will not allow me to catch my breath,but fills me with bitterness.
B018C009V019	18	9	19	If it is a matter of strength, behold, he is mighty!If of justice, 'Who,' says he, 'will summon me?'
B018C009V020	18	9	20	Though I am righteous, my own mouth shall condemn me.Though I am blameless, it shall prove me perverse.
B018C009V021	18	9	21	I am blameless.I do not regard myself.I despise my life.
B018C009V022	18	9	22	"It is all the same.Therefore I say he destroys the blameless and the wicked.
B018C009V023	18	9	23	If the scourge kills suddenly,he will mock at the trial of the innocent.
B018C009V024	18	9	24	The earth is given into the hand of the wicked.He covers the faces of its judges.If not he, then who is it?
B018C009V025	18	9	25	"Now my days are swifter than a runner.They flee away, they see no good,
B018C009V026	18	9	26	They have passed away as the swift ships,as the eagle that swoops on the prey.
B018C009V027	18	9	27	If I say, 'I will forget my complaint,I will put off my sad face, and cheer up;'
B018C009V028	18	9	28	I am afraid of all my sorrows,I know that you will not hold me innocent.
B018C009V029	18	9	29	I shall be condemned.Why then do I labor in vain?
B018C009V030	18	9	30	If I wash myself with snow,and cleanse my hands with lye,
B018C009V031	18	9	31	yet you will plunge me in the ditch.My own clothes shall abhor me.
B018C009V032	18	9	32	For he is not a man, as I am, that I should answer him,that we should come together in judgment.
B018C009V033	18	9	33	There is no umpire between us,that might lay his hand on us both.
B018C009V034	18	9	34	Let him take his rod away from me.Let his terror not make me afraid;
B018C009V035	18	9	35	then I would speak, and not fear him,for I am not so in myself.
B018C010V001	18	10	1	"My soul is weary of my life. I will give free course to my complaint.I will speak in the bitterness of my soul.
B018C010V002	18	10	2	I will tell God, 'Do not condemn me.Show me why you contend with me.
B018C010V003	18	10	3	Is it good to you that you should oppress,that you should despise the work of your hands,and smile on the counsel of the wicked?
B018C010V004	18	10	4	Do you have eyes of flesh?Or do you see as man sees?
B018C010V005	18	10	5	Are your days as the days of mortals,or your years as man's years,
B018C010V006	18	10	6	that you inquire after my iniquity,and search after my sin?
B018C010V007	18	10	7	Although you know that I am not wicked,there is no one who can deliver out of your hand.
B018C010V008	18	10	8	"'Your hands have framed me and fashioned me altogether,yet you destroy me.
B018C010V009	18	10	9	Remember, I beg you, that you have fashioned me as clay.Will you bring me into dust again?
B018C010V010	18	10	10	Haven't you poured me out like milk,and curdled me like cheese?
B018C010V011	18	10	11	You have clothed me with skin and flesh,and knit me together with bones and sinews.
B018C010V012	18	10	12	You have granted me life and loving kindness.Your visitation has preserved my spirit.
B018C010V013	18	10	13	Yet you hid these things in your heart.I know that this is with you:
B018C010V014	18	10	14	if I sin, then you mark me.You will not acquit me from my iniquity.
B018C010V015	18	10	15	If I am wicked, woe to me.If I am righteous, I still shall not lift up my head,being filled with disgrace,and conscious of my affliction.
B018C010V016	18	10	16	If my head is held high, you hunt me like a lion.Again you show yourself powerful to me.
B018C010V017	18	10	17	You renew your witnesses against me,and increase your indignation on me.Changes and warfare are with me.
B018C010V018	18	10	18	"'Why, then, have you brought me forth out of the womb?I wish I had given up the spirit, and no eye had seen me.
B018C010V019	18	10	19	I should have been as though I had not been.I should have been carried from the womb to the grave.
B018C010V020	18	10	20	Aren't my days few?Cease then.Leave me alone, that I may find a little comfort,
B018C010V021	18	10	21	before I go where I shall not return from,to the land of darkness and of the shadow of death;
B018C010V022	18	10	22	the land dark as midnight,of the shadow of death,without any order,where the light is as midnight.'"
B018C011V001	18	11	1	Then Zophar, the Naamathite, answered,
B018C011V002	18	11	2	"Shouldn't the multitude of words be answered?Should a man full of talk be justified?
B018C011V003	18	11	3	Should your boastings make men hold their peace?When you mock, shall no man make you ashamed?
B018C011V004	18	11	4	For you say, 'My doctrine is pure.I am clean in your eyes.'
B018C011V005	18	11	5	But oh that God would speak,and open his lips against you,
B018C011V006	18	11	6	that he would show you the secrets of wisdom!For true wisdom has two sides.Know therefore that God exacts of you less than your iniquity deserves.
B018C011V007	18	11	7	"Can you fathom the mystery of God?Or can you probe the limits of the Almighty?
B018C011V008	18	11	8	They are high as heaven. What can you do?They are deeper than Sheol. What can you know?
B018C011V009	18	11	9	Its measure is longer than the earth,and broader than the sea.
B018C011V010	18	11	10	If he passes by, or confines,or convenes a court, then who can oppose him?
B018C011V011	18	11	11	For he knows false men.He sees iniquity also, even though he doesn't consider it.
B018C011V012	18	11	12	An empty-headed man becomes wisewhen a man is born as a wild donkey's colt.
B018C011V013	18	11	13	"If you set your heart aright,stretch out your hands toward him.
B018C011V014	18	11	14	If iniquity is in your hand, put it far away.Do not let unrighteousness dwell in your tents.
B018C011V015	18	11	15	Surely then you shall lift up your face without spot;Yes, you shall be steadfast, and shall not fear:
B018C011V016	18	11	16	for you shall forget your misery.You shall remember it as waters that are passed away.
B018C011V017	18	11	17	Life shall be clearer than the noonday.Though there is darkness, it shall be as the morning.
B018C011V018	18	11	18	You shall be secure, because there is hope.Yes, you shall search, and shall take your rest in safety.
B018C011V019	18	11	19	Also you shall lie down, and none shall make you afraid.Yes, many shall court your favor.
B018C011V020	18	11	20	But the eyes of the wicked shall fail.They shall have no way to flee.Their hope shall be the giving up of the spirit."
B018C012V001	18	12	1	Then Job answered,
B018C012V002	18	12	2	"No doubt, but you are the people,and wisdom shall die with you.
B018C012V003	18	12	3	But I have understanding as well as you;I am not inferior to you.Yes, who doesn't know such things as these?
B018C012V004	18	12	4	I am like one who is a joke to his neighbor,I, who called on God, and he answered.The just, the blameless man is a joke.
B018C012V005	18	12	5	In the thought of him who is at ease there is contempt for misfortune.It is ready for them whose foot slips.
B018C012V006	18	12	6	The tents of robbers prosper.Those who provoke God are secure,who carry their God in their hands.
B018C012V007	18	12	7	"But ask the animals, now, and they shall teach you;the birds of the sky, and they shall tell you.
B018C012V008	18	12	8	Or speak to the earth, and it shall teach you.The fish of the sea shall declare to you.
B018C012V009	18	12	9	Who doesn't know that in all these,the hand of 
B018C012V010	18	12	10	in whose hand is the life of every living thing,and the breath of all mankind?
B018C012V011	18	12	11	Doesn't the ear try words,even as the palate tastes its food?
B018C012V012	18	12	12	With aged men is wisdom,in length of days understanding.
B018C012V013	18	12	13	"With God is wisdom and might.He has counsel and understanding.
B018C012V014	18	12	14	Behold, he breaks down, and it can't be built again.He imprisons a man, and there can be no release.
B018C012V015	18	12	15	Behold, he withholds the waters, and they dry up.Again, he sends them out, and they overturn the earth.
B018C012V016	18	12	16	With him is strength and wisdom.The deceived and the deceiver are his.
B018C012V017	18	12	17	He leads counselors away stripped.He makes judges fools.
B018C012V018	18	12	18	He loosens the bond of kings.He binds their waist with a belt.
B018C012V019	18	12	19	He leads priests away stripped,and overthrows the mighty.
B018C012V020	18	12	20	He removes the speech of those who are trusted,and takes away the understanding of the elders.
B018C012V021	18	12	21	He pours contempt on princes,and loosens the belt of the strong.
B018C012V022	18	12	22	He uncovers deep things out of darkness,and brings out to light the shadow of death.
B018C012V023	18	12	23	He increases the nations, and he destroys them.He enlarges the nations, and he leads them captive.
B018C012V024	18	12	24	He takes away understanding from the chiefs of the people of the earth,and causes them to wander in a wilderness where there is no way.
B018C012V025	18	12	25	They grope in the dark without light.He makes them stagger like a drunken man.
B018C013V001	18	13	1	"Behold, my eye has seen all this. My ear has heard and understood it.
B018C013V002	18	13	2	What you know, I know also.I am not inferior to you.
B018C013V003	18	13	3	"Surely I would speak to the Almighty.I desire to reason with God.
B018C013V004	18	13	4	But you are forgers of lies.You are all physicians of no value.
B018C013V005	18	13	5	Oh that you would be completely silent!Then you would be wise.
B018C013V006	18	13	6	Hear now my reasoning.Listen to the pleadings of my lips.
B018C013V007	18	13	7	Will you speak unrighteously for God,and talk deceitfully for him?
B018C013V008	18	13	8	Will you show partiality to him?Will you contend for God?
B018C013V009	18	13	9	Is it good that he should search you out?Or as one deceives a man, will you deceive him?
B018C013V010	18	13	10	He will surely reprove youif you secretly show partiality.
B018C013V011	18	13	11	Shall not his majesty make you afraid,And his dread fall on you?
B018C013V012	18	13	12	Your memorable sayings are proverbs of ashes,Your defenses are defenses of clay.
B018C013V013	18	13	13	"Be silent, leave me alone, that I may speak.Let come on me what will.
B018C013V014	18	13	14	Why should I take my flesh in my teeth,and put my life in my hand?
B018C013V015	18	13	15	Behold, he will kill me.I have no hope.Nevertheless, I will maintain my ways before him.
B018C013V016	18	13	16	This also shall be my salvation,that a godless man shall not come before him.
B018C013V017	18	13	17	Hear diligently my speech.Let my declaration be in your ears.
B018C013V018	18	13	18	See now, I have set my cause in order.I know that I am righteous.
B018C013V019	18	13	19	Who is he who will contend with me?For then would I hold my peace and give up the spirit.
B018C013V020	18	13	20	"Only do not do two things to me;then I will not hide myself from your face:
B018C013V021	18	13	21	withdraw your hand far from me;and do not let your terror make me afraid.
B018C013V022	18	13	22	Then call, and I will answer;or let me speak, and you answer me.
B018C013V023	18	13	23	How many are my iniquities and sins?Make me know my disobedience and my sin.
B018C013V024	18	13	24	Why hide you your face,and hold me for your enemy?
B018C013V025	18	13	25	Will you harass a driven leaf?Will you pursue the dry stubble?
B018C013V026	18	13	26	For you write bitter things against me,and make me inherit the iniquities of my youth:
B018C013V027	18	13	27	You also put my feet in the stocks,and mark all my paths.You set a bound to the soles of my feet,
B018C013V028	18	13	28	though I am decaying like a rotten thing,like a garment that is moth-eaten.
B018C014V001	18	14	1	"Man, who is born of a woman, is of few days, and full of trouble.
B018C014V002	18	14	2	He comes forth like a flower, and is cut down.He also flees like a shadow, and doesn't continue.
B018C014V003	18	14	3	Do you open your eyes on such a one,and bring me into judgment with you?
B018C014V004	18	14	4	Who can bring a clean thing out of an unclean?Not one.
B018C014V005	18	14	5	Seeing his days are determined,the number of his months is with you,and you have appointed his bounds that he can't pass;
B018C014V006	18	14	6	Look away from him, that he may rest,until he shall accomplish, as a hireling, his day.
B018C014V007	18	14	7	"For there is hope for a tree,If it is cut down, that it will sprout again,that the tender branch of it will not cease.
B018C014V008	18	14	8	Though its root grows old in the earth,and its stock dies in the ground,
B018C014V009	18	14	9	yet through the scent of water it will bud,and put forth boughs like a plant.
B018C014V010	18	14	10	But man dies, and is laid low.Yes, man gives up the spirit, and where is he?
B018C014V011	18	14	11	As the waters fail from the sea,and the river wastes and dries up,
B018C014V012	18	14	12	so man lies down and doesn't rise.Until the heavens are no more, they shall not awake,nor be roused out of their sleep.
B018C014V013	18	14	13	"Oh that you would hide me in Sheol,that you would keep me secret, until your wrath is past,that you would appoint me a set time, and remember me!
B018C014V014	18	14	14	If a man dies, shall he live again?All the days of my warfare would I wait,until my release should come.
B018C014V015	18	14	15	You would call, and I would answer you.You would have a desire to the work of your hands.
B018C014V016	18	14	16	But now you number my steps.Do you not watch over my sin?
B018C014V017	18	14	17	My disobedience is sealed up in a bag.You fasten up my iniquity.
B018C014V018	18	14	18	"But the mountain falling comes to nothing.The rock is removed out of its place;
B018C014V019	18	14	19	The waters wear the stones.The torrents of it wash away the dust of the earth.So you destroy the hope of man.
B018C014V020	18	14	20	You forever prevail against him, and he departs.You change his face, and send him away.
B018C014V021	18	14	21	His sons come to honor, and he doesn't know it.They are brought low, but he doesn't perceive it of them.
B018C014V022	18	14	22	But his flesh on him has pain,and his soul within him mourns."
B018C015V001	18	15	1	Then Eliphaz the Temanite answered,
B018C015V002	18	15	2	"Should a wise man answer with vain knowledge,and fill himself with the east wind?
B018C015V003	18	15	3	Should he reason with unprofitable talk,or with speeches with which he can do no good?
B018C015V004	18	15	4	Yes, you do away with fear,and hinder devotion before God.
B018C015V005	18	15	5	For your iniquity teaches your mouth,and you choose the language of the crafty.
B018C015V006	18	15	6	Your own mouth condemns you, and not I.Yes, your own lips testify against you.
B018C015V007	18	15	7	"Are you the first man who was born?Or were you brought forth before the hills?
B018C015V008	18	15	8	Have you heard the secret counsel of God?Do you limit wisdom to yourself?
B018C015V009	18	15	9	What do you know, that we do not know?What do you understand, which is not in us?
B018C015V010	18	15	10	With us are both the gray-headed and the very aged men,much elder than your father.
B018C015V011	18	15	11	Are the consolations of God too small for you,even the word that is gentle toward you?
B018C015V012	18	15	12	Why does your heart carry you away?Why do your eyes flash,
B018C015V013	18	15	13	That you turn your spirit against God,and let such words go out of your mouth?
B018C015V014	18	15	14	What is man, that he should be clean?What is he who is born of a woman, that he should be righteous?
B018C015V015	18	15	15	Behold, he puts no trust in his holy ones.Yes, the heavens are not clean in his sight;
B018C015V016	18	15	16	how much less one who is abominable and corrupt,a man who drinks iniquity like water!
B018C015V017	18	15	17	"I will show you, listen to me;that which I have seen I will declare:
B018C015V018	18	15	18	(Which wise men have told by their fathers,and have not hidden it;
B018C015V019	18	15	19	to whom alone the land was given,and no stranger passed among them):
B018C015V020	18	15	20	the wicked man writhes in pain all his days,even the number of years that are laid up for the oppressor.
B018C015V021	18	15	21	A sound of terrors is in his ears.In prosperity the destroyer shall come on him.
B018C015V022	18	15	22	He doesn't believe that he shall return out of darkness.He is waited for by the sword.
B018C015V023	18	15	23	He wanders abroad for bread, saying, 'Where is it?'He knows that the day of darkness is ready at his hand.
B018C015V024	18	15	24	Distress and anguish make him afraid.They prevail against him, as a king ready to the battle.
B018C015V025	18	15	25	Because he has stretched out his hand against God,and behaves himself proudly against the Almighty;
B018C015V026	18	15	26	he runs at him with a stiff neck,with the thick shields of his bucklers;
B018C015V027	18	15	27	because he has covered his face with his fatness,and gathered fat on his thighs.
B018C015V028	18	15	28	He has lived in desolate cities,in houses which no one inhabited,which were ready to become heaps.
B018C015V029	18	15	29	He shall not be rich, neither shall his substance continue,neither shall their possessions be extended on the earth.
B018C015V030	18	15	30	He shall not depart out of darkness.The flame shall dry up his branches.By the breath of God's mouth shall he go away.
B018C015V031	18	15	31	Let him not trust in emptiness, deceiving himself;for emptiness shall be his reward.
B018C015V032	18	15	32	It shall be accomplished before his time.His branch shall not be green.
B018C015V033	18	15	33	He shall shake off his unripe grape as the vine,and shall cast off his flower as the olive tree.
B018C015V034	18	15	34	For the company of the godless shall be barren,and fire shall consume the tents of bribery.
B018C015V035	18	15	35	They conceive mischief, and bring forth iniquity.Their heart prepares deceit."
B018C016V001	18	16	1	Then Job answered,
B018C016V002	18	16	2	"I have heard many such things.You are all miserable comforters!
B018C016V003	18	16	3	Shall vain words have an end?Or what provokes you that you answer?
B018C016V004	18	16	4	I also could speak as you do.If your soul were in my soul's place,I could join words together against you,and shake my head at you,
B018C016V005	18	16	5	but I would strengthen you with my mouth.The solace of my lips would relieve you.
B018C016V006	18	16	6	"Though I speak, my grief is not subsided.Though I forbear, what am I eased?
B018C016V007	18	16	7	But now, God, you have surely worn me out.You have made desolate all my company.
B018C016V008	18	16	8	You have shriveled me up. This is a witness against me.My leanness rises up against me.It testifies to my face.
B018C016V009	18	16	9	He has torn me in his wrath, and persecuted me.He has gnashed on me with his teeth.My adversary sharpens his eyes on me.
B018C016V010	18	16	10	They have gaped on me with their mouth.They have struck me on the cheek reproachfully.They gather themselves together against me.
B018C016V011	18	16	11	God delivers me to the ungodly,and casts me into the hands of the wicked.
B018C016V012	18	16	12	I was at ease, and he broke me apart.Yes, he has taken me by the neck, and dashed me to pieces.He has also set me up for his target.
B018C016V013	18	16	13	His archers surround me.He splits my kidneys apart, and does not spare.He pours out my gall on the ground.
B018C016V014	18	16	14	He breaks me with breach on breach.He runs on me like a giant.
B018C016V015	18	16	15	I have sewed sackcloth on my skin,and have thrust my horn in the dust.
B018C016V016	18	16	16	My face is red with weeping.Deep darkness is on my eyelids.
B018C016V017	18	16	17	Although there is no violence in my hands,and my prayer is pure.
B018C016V018	18	16	18	"Earth, do not cover my blood.Let my cry have no place to rest.
B018C016V019	18	16	19	Even now, behold, my witness is in heaven.He who vouches for me is on high.
B018C016V020	18	16	20	My friends scoff at me.My eyes pour out tears to God,
B018C016V021	18	16	21	that he would maintain the right of a man with God,of a son of man with his neighbor!
B018C016V022	18	16	22	For when a few years are come,I shall go the way from whence I shall not return.
B018C017V001	18	17	1	"My spirit is consumed. My days are extinct,And the grave is ready for me.
B018C017V002	18	17	2	Surely there are mockers with me.My eye dwells on their provocation.
B018C017V003	18	17	3	"Now give a pledge, be collateral for me with yourself.Who is there who will strike hands with me?
B018C017V004	18	17	4	For you have hidden their heart from understanding,Therefore you shall not exalt them.
B018C017V005	18	17	5	He who denounces his friends for a prey,Even the eyes of his children shall fail.
B018C017V006	18	17	6	"But he has made me a byword of the people.They spit in my face.
B018C017V007	18	17	7	My eye also is dim by reason of sorrow.All my members are as a shadow.
B018C017V008	18	17	8	Upright men shall be astonished at this.The innocent shall stir up himself against the godless.
B018C017V009	18	17	9	Yet shall the righteous hold on his way.He who has clean hands shall grow stronger and stronger.
B018C017V010	18	17	10	But as for you all, come on now again;I shall not find a wise man among you.
B018C017V011	18	17	11	My days are past, my plans are broken off,as are the thoughts of my heart.
B018C017V012	18	17	12	They change the night into day,saying 'The light is near' in the presence of darkness.
B018C017V013	18	17	13	If I look for Sheol as my house,if I have spread my couch in the darkness,
B018C017V014	18	17	14	If I have said to corruption, 'You are my father;'to the worm, 'My mother,' and 'my sister;'
B018C017V015	18	17	15	where then is my hope?As for my hope, who shall see it?
B018C017V016	18	17	16	Shall it go down with me to the gates of Sheol,or descend together into the dust?"
B018C018V001	18	18	1	Then Bildad the Shuhite answered,
B018C018V002	18	18	2	"How long will you hunt for words?Consider, and afterwards we will speak.
B018C018V003	18	18	3	Why are we counted as animals,which have become unclean in your sight?
B018C018V004	18	18	4	You who tear yourself in your anger,shall the earth be forsaken for you?Or shall the rock be removed out of its place?
B018C018V005	18	18	5	"Yes, the light of the wicked shall be put out,The spark of his fire shall not shine.
B018C018V006	18	18	6	The light shall be dark in his tent.His lamp above him shall be put out.
B018C018V007	18	18	7	The steps of his strength shall be shortened.His own counsel shall cast him down.
B018C018V008	18	18	8	For he is cast into a net by his own feet,and he wanders into its mesh.
B018C018V009	18	18	9	A snare will take him by the heel.A trap will catch him.
B018C018V010	18	18	10	A noose is hidden for him in the ground,a trap for him in the way.
B018C018V011	18	18	11	Terrors shall make him afraid on every side,and shall chase him at his heels.
B018C018V012	18	18	12	His strength shall be famished.Calamity shall be ready at his side.
B018C018V013	18	18	13	The members of his body shall be devoured.The firstborn of death shall devour his members.
B018C018V014	18	18	14	He shall be rooted out of his tent where he trusts.He shall be brought to the king of terrors.
B018C018V015	18	18	15	There shall dwell in his tent that which is none of his.Sulfur shall be scattered on his habitation.
B018C018V016	18	18	16	His roots shall be dried up beneath.Above shall his branch be cut off.
B018C018V017	18	18	17	His memory shall perish from the earth.He shall have no name in the street.
B018C018V018	18	18	18	He shall be driven from light into darkness,and chased out of the world.
B018C018V019	18	18	19	He shall have neither son nor grandson among his people,nor any remaining where he sojourned.
B018C018V020	18	18	20	Those who come after shall be astonished at his day,as those who went before were frightened.
B018C018V021	18	18	21	Surely such are the dwellings of the unrighteous.This is the place of him who doesn't know God."
B018C019V001	18	19	1	Then Job answered,
B018C019V002	18	19	2	"How long will you torment me,and crush me with words?
B018C019V003	18	19	3	You have reproached me ten times.You aren't ashamed that you attack me.
B018C019V004	18	19	4	If it is true that I have erred,my error remains with myself.
B018C019V005	18	19	5	If indeed you will magnify yourselves against me,and plead against me my reproach;
B018C019V006	18	19	6	know now that God has subverted me,and has surrounded me with his net.
B018C019V007	18	19	7	"Behold, I cry out 'Injustice!' but there is no justice.
B018C019V008	18	19	8	He has walled up my way so that I can't pass,and has set darkness in my paths.
B018C019V009	18	19	9	He has stripped me of my glory,and taken the crown from my head.
B018C019V010	18	19	10	He has broken me down on every side, and I am gone.My hope he has plucked up like a tree.
B018C019V011	18	19	11	He has also kindled his wrath against me.He counts me among his adversaries.
B018C019V012	18	19	12	His troops come on together,build a siege ramp against me,and encamp around my tent.
B018C019V013	18	19	13	"He has put my brothers far from me.My acquaintances are wholly estranged from me.
B018C019V014	18	19	14	My relatives have gone away.My familiar friends have forgotten me.
B018C019V015	18	19	15	Those who dwell in my house, and my maids, count me for a stranger.I am a foreigner in their sight.
B018C019V016	18	19	16	I call to my servant, and he gives me no answer.I beg him with my mouth.
B018C019V017	18	19	17	My breath is offensive to my wife.I am loathsome to the children of my own mother.
B018C019V018	18	19	18	Even young children despise me.If I arise, they speak against me.
B018C019V019	18	19	19	All my familiar friends abhor me.They whom I loved have turned against me.
B018C019V020	18	19	20	My bones stick to my skin and to my flesh.I have escaped by the skin of my teeth.
B018C019V021	18	19	21	"Have pity on me, have pity on me, you my friends;for the hand of God has touched me.
B018C019V022	18	19	22	Why do you persecute me as God,and are not satisfied with my flesh?
B018C019V023	18	19	23	"Oh that my words were now written!Oh that they were inscribed in a book!
B018C019V024	18	19	24	That with an iron pen and leadthey were engraved in the rock forever!
B018C019V025	18	19	25	But as for me, I know that my Redeemer lives.In the end, he will stand upon the earth.
B018C019V026	18	19	26	After my skin is destroyed,then in my flesh shall I see God,
B018C019V027	18	19	27	Whom I, even I, shall see on my side.My eyes shall see, and not as a stranger."My heart is consumed within me.
B018C019V028	18	19	28	If you say, 'How we will persecute him!'because the root of the matter is found in me,
B018C019V029	18	19	29	be afraid of the sword,for wrath brings the punishments of the sword,that you may know there is a judgment."
B018C020V001	18	20	1	Then Zophar the Naamathite answered,
B018C020V002	18	20	2	"Therefore do my thoughts give answer to me,even by reason of my haste that is in me.
B018C020V003	18	20	3	I have heard the reproof which puts me to shame.The spirit of my understanding answers me.
B018C020V004	18	20	4	Do you not know this from old time,since man was placed on earth,
B018C020V005	18	20	5	that the triumphing of the wicked is short,the joy of the godless but for a moment?
B018C020V006	18	20	6	Though his height mount up to the heavens,and his head reach to the clouds,
B018C020V007	18	20	7	yet he shall perish forever like his own dung.Those who have seen him shall say, 'Where is he?'
B018C020V008	18	20	8	He shall fly away as a dream, and shall not be found.Yes, he shall be chased away like a vision of the night.
B018C020V009	18	20	9	The eye which saw him shall see him no more,neither shall his place any more see him.
B018C020V010	18	20	10	His children shall seek the favor of the poor.His hands shall give back his wealth.
B018C020V011	18	20	11	His bones are full of his youth,but youth shall lie down with him in the dust.
B018C020V012	18	20	12	"Though wickedness is sweet in his mouth,though he hide it under his tongue,
B018C020V013	18	20	13	though he spare it, and will not let it go,but keep it still within his mouth;
B018C020V014	18	20	14	yet his food in his bowels is turned.It is cobra venom within him.
B018C020V015	18	20	15	He has swallowed down riches, and he shall vomit them up again.God will cast them out of his belly.
B018C020V016	18	20	16	He shall suck cobra venom.The viper's tongue shall kill him.
B018C020V017	18	20	17	He shall not look at the rivers,the flowing streams of honey and butter.
B018C020V018	18	20	18	That for which he labored he shall restore, and shall not swallow it down.According to the substance that he has gotten, he shall not rejoice.
B018C020V019	18	20	19	For he has oppressed and forsaken the poor.He has violently taken away a house, and he shall not build it up.
B018C020V020	18	20	20	"Because he knew no quietness within him,he shall not save anything of that in which he delights.
B018C020V021	18	20	21	There was nothing left that he did not devour,therefore his prosperity shall not endure.
B018C020V022	18	20	22	In the fullness of his sufficiency, distress shall overtake him.The hand of everyone who is in misery shall come on him.
B018C020V023	18	20	23	When he is about to fill his belly, God will cast the fierceness of his wrath on him.It will rain on him while he is eating.
B018C020V024	18	20	24	He shall flee from the iron weapon.The bronze arrow shall strike him through.
B018C020V025	18	20	25	He draws it forth, and it comes out of his body.Yes, the glittering point comes out of his liver.Terrors are on him.
B018C020V026	18	20	26	All darkness is laid up for his treasures.An unfanned fire shall devour him.It shall consume that which is left in his tent.
B018C020V027	18	20	27	The heavens shall reveal his iniquity.The earth shall rise up against him.
B018C020V028	18	20	28	The increase of his house shall depart.They shall rush away in the day of his wrath.
B018C020V029	18	20	29	This is the portion of a wicked man from God,the heritage appointed to him by God."
B018C021V001	18	21	1	Then Job answered,
B018C021V002	18	21	2	"Listen diligently to my speech.Let this be your consolation.
B018C021V003	18	21	3	Allow me, and I also will speak;After I have spoken, mock on.
B018C021V004	18	21	4	As for me, is my complaint to man?Why shouldn't I be impatient?
B018C021V005	18	21	5	Look at me, and be astonished.Lay your hand on your mouth.
B018C021V006	18	21	6	When I remember, I am troubled.Horror takes hold of my flesh.
B018C021V007	18	21	7	"Why do the wicked live,become old, yes, and grow mighty in power?
B018C021V008	18	21	8	Their child is established with them in their sight,their offspring before their eyes.
B018C021V009	18	21	9	Their houses are safe from fear,neither is the rod of God upon them.
B018C021V010	18	21	10	Their bulls breed without fail.Their cows calve, and do not miscarry.
B018C021V011	18	21	11	They send forth their little ones like a flock.Their children dance.
B018C021V012	18	21	12	They sing to the tambourine and harp,and rejoice at the sound of the pipe.
B018C021V013	18	21	13	They spend their days in prosperity.In an instant they go down to Sheol.
B018C021V014	18	21	14	They tell God, 'Depart from us,for we do not want to know about your ways.
B018C021V015	18	21	15	What is the Almighty, that we should serve him?What profit should we have, if we pray to him?'
B018C021V016	18	21	16	Behold, their prosperity is not in their hand.The counsel of the wicked is far from me.
B018C021V017	18	21	17	"How often is it that the lamp of the wicked is put out,that their calamity comes on them,that God distributes sorrows in his anger?
B018C021V018	18	21	18	How often is it that they are as stubble before the wind,as chaff that the storm carries away?
B018C021V019	18	21	19	You say, 'God lays up his iniquity for his children.'Let him recompense it to himself, that he may know it.
B018C021V020	18	21	20	Let his own eyes see his destruction.Let him drink of the wrath of the Almighty.
B018C021V021	18	21	21	For what does he care for his house after him,when the number of his months is cut off?
B018C021V022	18	21	22	"Shall any teach God knowledge,seeing he judges those who are high?
B018C021V023	18	21	23	One dies in his full strength,being wholly at ease and quiet.
B018C021V024	18	21	24	His pails are full of milk.The marrow of his bones is moistened.
B018C021V025	18	21	25	Another dies in bitterness of soul,and never tastes of good.
B018C021V026	18	21	26	They lie down alike in the dust.The worm covers them.
B018C021V027	18	21	27	"Behold, I know your thoughts,the devices with which you would wrong me.
B018C021V028	18	21	28	For you say, 'Where is the house of the prince?Where is the tent in which the wicked lived?'
B018C021V029	18	21	29	Haven't you asked wayfaring men?Do you not know their evidences,
B018C021V030	18	21	30	that the evil man is reserved to the day of calamity,That they are led forth to the day of wrath?
B018C021V031	18	21	31	Who shall declare his way to his face?Who shall repay him what he has done?
B018C021V032	18	21	32	Yet he will be borne to the grave.Men shall keep watch over the tomb.
B018C021V033	18	21	33	The clods of the valley shall be sweet to him.All men shall draw after him,as there were innumerable before him.
B018C021V034	18	21	34	So how can you comfort me with nonsense,seeing that in your answers there remains only falsehood?"
B018C022V001	18	22	1	Then Eliphaz the Temanite answered,
B018C022V002	18	22	2	"Can a man be profitable to God?Surely he who is wise is profitable to himself.
B018C022V003	18	22	3	Is it any pleasure to the Almighty, that you are righteous?Or does it benefit him, that you make your ways perfect?
B018C022V004	18	22	4	Is it for your piety that he reproves you,that he enters with you into judgment?
B018C022V005	18	22	5	Isn't your wickedness great?Neither is there any end to your iniquities.
B018C022V006	18	22	6	For you have taken pledges from your brother for nothing,and stripped the naked of their clothing.
B018C022V007	18	22	7	You haven't given water to the weary to drink,and you have withheld bread from the hungry.
B018C022V008	18	22	8	But as for the mighty man, he had the earth.The honorable man, he lived in it.
B018C022V009	18	22	9	You have sent widows away empty,and the arms of the fatherless have been broken.
B018C022V010	18	22	10	Therefore snares are around you.Sudden fear troubles you,
B018C022V011	18	22	11	or darkness, so that you can not see,and floods of waters cover you.
B018C022V012	18	22	12	"Isn't God in the heights of heaven?See the height of the stars, how high they are!
B018C022V013	18	22	13	You say, 'What does God know?Can he judge through the thick darkness?
B018C022V014	18	22	14	Thick clouds are a covering to him, so that he doesn't see.He walks on the vault of the sky.'
B018C022V015	18	22	15	Will you keep the old way,which wicked men have trodden,
B018C022V016	18	22	16	who were snatched away before their time,whose foundation was poured out as a stream,
B018C022V017	18	22	17	who said to God, 'Depart from us;'and, 'What can the Almighty do for us?'
B018C022V018	18	22	18	Yet he filled their houses with good things,but the counsel of the wicked is far from me.
B018C022V019	18	22	19	The righteous see it, and are glad.The innocent ridicule them,
B018C022V020	18	22	20	saying, 'Surely those who rose up against us are cut off.The fire has consumed the remnant of them.'
B018C022V021	18	22	21	"Acquaint yourself with him, now, and be at peace.Thereby good shall come to you.
B018C022V022	18	22	22	Please receive instruction from his mouth,and lay up his words in your heart.
B018C022V023	18	22	23	If you return to the Almighty, you shall be built up,if you put away unrighteousness far from your tents.
B018C022V024	18	22	24	Lay your treasure in the dust,the gold of Ophir among the stones of the brooks.
B018C022V025	18	22	25	The Almighty will be your treasure,and precious silver to you.
B018C022V026	18	22	26	For then you will delight yourself in the Almighty,and shall lift up your face to God.
B018C022V027	18	22	27	You shall make your prayer to him, and he will hear you.You shall pay your vows.
B018C022V028	18	22	28	You shall also decree a thing, and it shall be established to you.Light shall shine on your ways.
B018C022V029	18	22	29	When they cast down, you shall say, 'be lifted up.'He will save the humble person.
B018C022V030	18	22	30	He will even deliver him who is not innocent.Yes, he shall be delivered through the cleanness of your hands."
B018C023V001	18	23	1	Then Job answered,
B018C023V002	18	23	2	"Even today my complaint is rebellious.His hand is heavy in spite of my groaning.
B018C023V003	18	23	3	Oh that I knew where I might find him!That I might come even to his seat!
B018C023V004	18	23	4	I would set my cause in order before him,and fill my mouth with arguments.
B018C023V005	18	23	5	I would know the words which he would answer me,and understand what he would tell me.
B018C023V006	18	23	6	Would he contend with me in the greatness of his power?No, but he would listen to me.
B018C023V007	18	23	7	There the upright might reason with him,so I should be delivered forever from my judge.
B018C023V008	18	23	8	"If I go east, he is not there;if west, I can't find him;
B018C023V009	18	23	9	He works to the north, but I can't see him.He turns south, but I can't catch a glimpse of him.
B018C023V010	18	23	10	But he knows the way that I take.When he has tried me, I shall come forth like gold.
B018C023V011	18	23	11	My foot has held fast to his steps.I have kept his way, and not turned aside.
B018C023V012	18	23	12	I haven't gone back from the commandment of his lips.I have treasured up the words of his mouth more than my necessary food.
B018C023V013	18	23	13	But he stands alone, and who can oppose him?What his soul desires, even that he does.
B018C023V014	18	23	14	For he performs that which is appointed for me.Many such things are with him.
B018C023V015	18	23	15	Therefore I am terrified at his presence.When I consider, I am afraid of him.
B018C023V016	18	23	16	For God has made my heart faint.The Almighty has terrified me.
B018C023V017	18	23	17	Because I was not cut off before the darkness,neither did he cover the thick darkness from my face.
B018C024V001	18	24	1	"Why aren't times laid up by the Almighty? Why do not those who know him see his days?
B018C024V002	18	24	2	There are people who remove the landmarks.They violently take away flocks, and feed them.
B018C024V003	18	24	3	They drive away the donkey of the fatherless,and they take the widow's ox for a pledge.
B018C024V004	18	24	4	They turn the needy out of the way.The poor of the earth all hide themselves.
B018C024V005	18	24	5	Behold, as wild donkeys in the desert,they go forth to their work, seeking diligently for food.The wilderness yields them bread for their children.
B018C024V006	18	24	6	They cut their provender in the field.They glean the vineyard of the wicked.
B018C024V007	18	24	7	They lie all night naked without clothing,and have no covering in the cold.
B018C024V008	18	24	8	They are wet with the showers of the mountains,and embrace the rock for lack of a shelter.
B018C024V009	18	24	9	There are those who pluck the fatherless from the breast,and take a pledge of the poor,
B018C024V010	18	24	10	So that they go around naked without clothing.Being hungry, they carry the sheaves.
B018C024V011	18	24	11	They make oil within the walls of these men.They tread wine presses, and suffer thirst.
B018C024V012	18	24	12	From out of the populous city, men groan.The soul of the wounded cries out,yet God doesn't regard the folly.
B018C024V013	18	24	13	"These are of those who rebel against the light.They do not know its ways,nor abide in its paths.
B018C024V014	18	24	14	The murderer rises with the light.He kills the poor and needy.In the night he is like a thief.
B018C024V015	18	24	15	The eye also of the adulterer waits for the twilight,saying, 'No eye shall see me.'He disguises his face.
B018C024V016	18	24	16	In the dark they dig through houses.They shut themselves up in the daytime.They do not know the light.
B018C024V017	18	24	17	For the morning is to all of them like thick darkness,for they know the terrors of the thick darkness.
B018C024V018	18	24	18	"They are foam on the surface of the waters.Their portion is cursed in the earth.They do not turn into the way of the vineyards.
B018C024V019	18	24	19	Drought and heat consume the snow waters,so does Sheol those who have sinned.
B018C024V020	18	24	20	The womb shall forget him.The worm shall feed sweetly on him.He shall be no more remembered.Unrighteousness shall be broken as a tree.
B018C024V021	18	24	21	He devours the barren who do not bear.He shows no kindness to the widow.
B018C024V022	18	24	22	Yet God preserves the mighty by his power.He rises up who has no assurance of life.
B018C024V023	18	24	23	God gives them security, and they rest in it.His eyes are on their ways.
B018C024V024	18	24	24	They are exalted; yet a little while, and they are gone.Yes, they are brought low, they are taken out of the way as all others,and are cut off as the tops of the ears of grain.
B018C024V025	18	24	25	If it isn't so now, who will prove me a liar,and make my speech worth nothing?"
B018C025V001	18	25	1	Then Bildad the Shuhite answered,
B018C025V002	18	25	2	"Dominion and fear are with him.He makes peace in his high places.
B018C025V003	18	25	3	Can his armies be counted?On whom does his light not arise?
B018C025V004	18	25	4	How then can man be just with God?Or how can he who is born of a woman be clean?
B018C025V005	18	25	5	Behold, even the moon has no brightness,and the stars are not pure in his sight;
B018C025V006	18	25	6	How much less man, who is a worm,the son of man, who is a worm!"
B018C026V001	18	26	1	Then Job answered,
B018C026V002	18	26	2	"How have you helped him who is without power!How have you saved the arm that has no strength!
B018C026V003	18	26	3	How have you counseled him who has no wisdom,and plentifully declared sound knowledge!
B018C026V004	18	26	4	To whom have you uttered words?Whose spirit came forth from you?
B018C026V005	18	26	5	"Those who are deceased tremble,those beneath the waters and all that live in them.
B018C026V006	18	26	6	Sheol is naked before God,and Abaddon has no covering.
B018C026V007	18	26	7	He stretches out the north over empty space,and hangs the earth on nothing.
B018C026V008	18	26	8	He binds up the waters in his thick clouds,and the cloud is not burst under them.
B018C026V009	18	26	9	He encloses the face of his throne,and spreads his cloud on it.
B018C026V010	18	26	10	He has described a boundary on the surface of the waters,and to the confines of light and darkness.
B018C026V011	18	26	11	The pillars of heaven trembleand are astonished at his rebuke.
B018C026V012	18	26	12	He stirs up the sea with his power,and by his understanding he strikes through Rahab.
B018C026V013	18	26	13	By his Spirit the heavens are garnished.His hand has pierced the swift serpent.
B018C026V014	18	26	14	Behold, these are but the outskirts of his ways.How small a whisper do we hear of him!But the thunder of his power who can understand?"
B018C027V001	18	27	1	Job again took up his parable, and said,
B018C027V002	18	27	2	"As God lives, who has taken away my right,the Almighty, who has made my soul bitter.
B018C027V003	18	27	3	(For the length of my life is still in me,and the spirit of God is in my nostrils);
B018C027V004	18	27	4	surely my lips shall not speak unrighteousness,neither shall my tongue utter deceit.
B018C027V005	18	27	5	Far be it from me that I should justify you.Until I die I will not put away my integrity from me.
B018C027V006	18	27	6	I hold fast to my righteousness, and will not let it go.My heart shall not reproach me so long as I live.
B018C027V007	18	27	7	"Let my enemy be as the wicked.Let him who rises up against me be as the unrighteous.
B018C027V008	18	27	8	For what is the hope of the godless, when he is cut off, when God takes away his life?
B018C027V009	18	27	9	Will God hear his cry when trouble comes on him?
B018C027V010	18	27	10	Will he delight himself in the Almighty,and call on God at all times?
B018C027V011	18	27	11	I will teach you about the hand of God.That which is with the Almighty will I not conceal.
B018C027V012	18	27	12	Behold, all of you have seen it yourselves;why then have you become altogether vain?
B018C027V013	18	27	13	"This is the portion of a wicked man with God,the heritage of oppressors, which they receive from the Almighty.
B018C027V014	18	27	14	If his children are multiplied, it is for the sword.His offspring shall not be satisfied with bread.
B018C027V015	18	27	15	Those who remain of him shall be buried in death.His widows shall make no lamentation.
B018C027V016	18	27	16	Though he heap up silver as the dust,and prepare clothing as the clay;
B018C027V017	18	27	17	he may prepare it, but the just shall put it on,and the innocent shall divide the silver.
B018C027V018	18	27	18	He builds his house as the moth,as a booth which the watchman makes.
B018C027V019	18	27	19	He lies down rich, but he shall not do so again.He opens his eyes, and he is not.
B018C027V020	18	27	20	Terrors overtake him like waters.A storm steals him away in the night.
B018C027V021	18	27	21	The east wind carries him away, and he departs.It sweeps him out of his place.
B018C027V022	18	27	22	For it hurls at him, and does not spare,as he flees away from his hand.
B018C027V023	18	27	23	Men shall clap their hands at him,and shall hiss him out of his place.
B018C028V001	18	28	1	"Surely there is a mine for silver, and a place for gold which they refine.
B018C028V002	18	28	2	Iron is taken out of the earth,and copper is smelted out of the ore.
B018C028V003	18	28	3	Man sets an end to darkness,and searches out, to the furthest bound,the stones of obscurity and of thick darkness.
B018C028V004	18	28	4	He breaks open a shaft away from where people live.They are forgotten by the foot.They hang far from men, they swing back and forth.
B018C028V005	18	28	5	As for the earth, out of it comes bread;Underneath it is turned up as it were by fire.
B018C028V006	18	28	6	Sapphires come from its rocks.It has dust of gold.
B018C028V007	18	28	7	That path no bird of prey knows,neither has the falcon's eye seen it.
B018C028V008	18	28	8	The proud animals have not trodden it,nor has the fierce lion passed by there.
B018C028V009	18	28	9	He puts forth his hand on the flinty rock,and he overturns the mountains by the roots.
B018C028V010	18	28	10	He cuts out channels among the rocks.His eye sees every precious thing.
B018C028V011	18	28	11	He binds the streams that they do not trickle.The thing that is hidden he brings forth to light.
B018C028V012	18	28	12	"But where shall wisdom be found?Where is the place of understanding?
B018C028V013	18	28	13	Man doesn't know its price;Neither is it found in the land of the living.
B018C028V014	18	28	14	The deep says, 'It isn't in me.'The sea says, 'It isn't with me.'
B018C028V015	18	28	15	It can't be gotten for gold,neither shall silver be weighed for its price.
B018C028V016	18	28	16	It can't be valued with the gold of Ophir,with the precious onyx, or the sapphire.
B018C028V017	18	28	17	Gold and glass can't equal it,neither shall it be exchanged for jewels of fine gold.
B018C028V018	18	28	18	No mention shall be made of coral or of crystal.Yes, the price of wisdom is above rubies.
B018C028V019	18	28	19	The topaz of Ethiopia shall not equal it,Neither shall it be valued with pure gold.
B018C028V020	18	28	20	Whence then comes wisdom?Where is the place of understanding?
B018C028V021	18	28	21	Seeing it is hidden from the eyes of all living,and kept close from the birds of the sky.
B018C028V022	18	28	22	Destruction and Death say,'We have heard a rumor of it with our ears.'
B018C028V023	18	28	23	"God understands its way,and he knows its place.
B018C028V024	18	28	24	For he looks to the ends of the earth,and sees under the whole sky.
B018C028V025	18	28	25	He establishes the force of the wind.Yes, he measures out the waters by measure.
B018C028V026	18	28	26	When he made a decree for the rain,and a way for the lightning of the thunder;
B018C028V027	18	28	27	then he saw it, and declared it.He established it, yes, and searched it out.
B018C028V028	18	28	28	To man he said,'Behold, the fear of the Lord, that is wisdom.To depart from evil is understanding.'"
B018C029V001	18	29	1	Job again took up his parable, and said,
B018C029V002	18	29	2	"Oh that I were as in the months of old,as in the days when God watched over me;
B018C029V003	18	29	3	when his lamp shone on my head,and by his light I walked through darkness,
B018C029V004	18	29	4	as I was in the ripeness of my days,when the friendship of God was in my tent,
B018C029V005	18	29	5	when the Almighty was yet with me,and my children were around me,
B018C029V006	18	29	6	when my steps were washed with butter,and the rock poured out streams of oil for me,
B018C029V007	18	29	7	when I went forth to the city gate,when I prepared my seat in the street.
B018C029V008	18	29	8	The young men saw me and hid themselves.The aged rose up and stood.
B018C029V009	18	29	9	The princes refrained from talking,and laid their hand on their mouth.
B018C029V010	18	29	10	The voice of the nobles was hushed,and their tongue stuck to the roof of their mouth.
B018C029V011	18	29	11	For when the ear heard me, then it blessed me;and when the eye saw me, it commended me:
B018C029V012	18	29	12	Because I delivered the poor who cried,and the fatherless also, who had none to help him,
B018C029V013	18	29	13	the blessing of him who was ready to perish came on me,and I caused the widow's heart to sing for joy.
B018C029V014	18	29	14	I put on righteousness, and it clothed me.My justice was as a robe and a diadem.
B018C029V015	18	29	15	I was eyes to the blind,and feet to the lame.
B018C029V016	18	29	16	I was a father to the needy.The cause of him who I did not know, I searched out.
B018C029V017	18	29	17	I broke the jaws of the unrighteous,and plucked the prey out of his teeth.
B018C029V018	18	29	18	Then I said, 'I shall die in my own house,I shall number my days as the sand.
B018C029V019	18	29	19	My root is spread out to the waters.The dew lies all night on my branch.
B018C029V020	18	29	20	My glory is fresh in me.My bow is renewed in my hand.'
B018C029V021	18	29	21	"Men listened to me, waited,and kept silence for my counsel.
B018C029V022	18	29	22	After my words they did not speak again.My speech fell on them.
B018C029V023	18	29	23	They waited for me as for the rain.Their mouths drank as with the spring rain.
B018C029V024	18	29	24	I smiled on them when they had no confidence.They did not reject the light of my face.
B018C029V025	18	29	25	I chose out their way, and sat as chief.I lived as a king in the army,as one who comforts the mourners.
B018C030V001	18	30	1	"But now those who are younger than I have me in derision, whose fathers I would have disdained to put with my sheep dogs.
B018C030V002	18	30	2	Of what use is the strength of their hands to me,men in whom ripe age has perished?
B018C030V003	18	30	3	They are gaunt from lack and famine.They gnaw the dry ground, in the gloom of waste and desolation.
B018C030V004	18	30	4	They pluck salt herbs by the bushes.The roots of the broom are their food.
B018C030V005	18	30	5	They are driven out from the midst of men.They cry after them as after a thief;
B018C030V006	18	30	6	So that they dwell in frightful valleys,and in holes of the earth and of the rocks.
B018C030V007	18	30	7	Among the bushes they bray;and under the nettles they are gathered together.
B018C030V008	18	30	8	They are children of fools, yes, children of base men.They were flogged out of the land.
B018C030V009	18	30	9	"Now I have become their song.Yes, I am a byword to them.
B018C030V010	18	30	10	They abhor me, they stand aloof from me,and do not hesitate to spit in my face.
B018C030V011	18	30	11	For he has untied his cord, and afflicted me;and they have thrown off restraint before me.
B018C030V012	18	30	12	On my right hand rise the rabble.They thrust aside my feet,They cast up against me their ways of destruction.
B018C030V013	18	30	13	They mar my path,They set forward my calamity,without anyone's help.
B018C030V014	18	30	14	As through a wide breach they come,in the midst of the ruin they roll themselves in.
B018C030V015	18	30	15	Terrors have turned on me.They chase my honor as the wind.My welfare has passed away as a cloud.
B018C030V016	18	30	16	"Now my soul is poured out within me.Days of affliction have taken hold on me.
B018C030V017	18	30	17	In the night season my bones are pierced in me,and the pains that gnaw me take no rest.
B018C030V018	18	30	18	By great force is my garment disfigured.It binds me about as the collar of my coat.
B018C030V019	18	30	19	He has cast me into the mire.I have become like dust and ashes.
B018C030V020	18	30	20	I cry to you, and you do not answer me.I stand up, and you gaze at me.
B018C030V021	18	30	21	You have turned to be cruel to me.With the might of your hand you persecute me.
B018C030V022	18	30	22	You lift me up to the wind, and drive me with it.You dissolve me in the storm.
B018C030V023	18	30	23	For I know that you will bring me to death,To the house appointed for all living.
B018C030V024	18	30	24	"However doesn't one stretch out a hand in his fall?Or in his calamity therefore cry for help?
B018C030V025	18	30	25	Did I not weep for him who was in trouble?Wasn't my soul grieved for the needy?
B018C030V026	18	30	26	When I looked for good, then evil came;When I waited for light, there came darkness.
B018C030V027	18	30	27	My heart is troubled, and doesn't rest.Days of affliction have come on me.
B018C030V028	18	30	28	I go mourning without the sun.I stand up in the assembly, and cry for help.
B018C030V029	18	30	29	I am a brother to jackals,and a companion to ostriches.
B018C030V030	18	30	30	My skin grows black and peels from me.My bones are burned with heat.
B018C030V031	18	30	31	Therefore my harp has turned to mourning,and my pipe into the voice of those who weep.
B018C031V001	18	31	1	"I made a covenant with my eyes, how then should I look lustfully at a young woman?
B018C031V002	18	31	2	For what is the portion from God above,and the heritage from the Almighty on high?
B018C031V003	18	31	3	Is it not calamity for the unrighteous,and disaster for the workers of iniquity?
B018C031V004	18	31	4	Doesn't he see my ways,and number all my steps?
B018C031V005	18	31	5	"If I have walked with falsehood,and my foot has hurried to deceit
B018C031V006	18	31	6	(let me be weighed in an even balance,that God may know my integrity);
B018C031V007	18	31	7	if my step has turned out of the way,if my heart walked after my eyes,if any defilement has stuck to my hands,
B018C031V008	18	31	8	then let me sow, and let another eat.Yes, let the produce of my field be rooted out.
B018C031V009	18	31	9	"If my heart has been enticed to a woman,and I have lain in wait at my neighbor's door,
B018C031V010	18	31	10	then let my wife grind for another,and let others sleep with her.
B018C031V011	18	31	11	For that would be a heinous crime.Yes, it would be an iniquity to be punished by the judges:
B018C031V012	18	31	12	For it is a fire that consumes to destruction,and would root out all my increase.
B018C031V013	18	31	13	"If I have despised the cause of my male servantor of my female servant,when they contended with me;
B018C031V014	18	31	14	What then shall I do when God rises up?When he visits, what shall I answer him?
B018C031V015	18	31	15	Did not he who made me in the womb make him?Did not the same one fashion us in the womb?
B018C031V016	18	31	16	"If I have withheld the poor from their desire,or have caused the eyes of the widow to fail,
B018C031V017	18	31	17	or have eaten my morsel alone,and the fatherless has not eaten of it
B018C031V018	18	31	18	(no, from my youth he grew up with me as with a father,her have I guided from my mother's womb);
B018C031V019	18	31	19	if I have seen any perish for want of clothing,or that the needy had no covering;
B018C031V020	18	31	20	if his heart hasn't blessed me,if he hasn't been warmed with my sheep's fleece;
B018C031V021	18	31	21	if I have lifted up my hand against the fatherless,because I saw my help in the gate,
B018C031V022	18	31	22	then let my shoulder fall from the shoulder blade,and my arm be broken from the bone.
B018C031V023	18	31	23	For calamity from God is a terror to me.Because his majesty, I can do nothing.
B018C031V024	18	31	24	"If I have made gold my hope,and have said to the fine gold, 'You are my confidence;'
B018C031V025	18	31	25	If I have rejoiced because my wealth was great,and because my hand had gotten much;
B018C031V026	18	31	26	if I have seen the sun when it shined,or the moon moving in splendor,
B018C031V027	18	31	27	and my heart has been secretly enticed,and my hand threw a kiss from my mouth,
B018C031V028	18	31	28	this also would be an iniquity to be punished by the judges;for I should have denied the God who is above.
B018C031V029	18	31	29	"If I have rejoiced at the destruction of him who hated me,or lifted up myself when evil found him;
B018C031V030	18	31	30	(yes, I have not allowed my mouth to sinby asking his life with a curse);
B018C031V031	18	31	31	if the men of my tent have not said,'Who can find one who has not been filled with his meat?'
B018C031V032	18	31	32	(the foreigner has not lodged in the street,but I have opened my doors to the traveler);
B018C031V033	18	31	33	if like Adam I have covered my transgressions,by hiding my iniquity in my heart,
B018C031V034	18	31	34	because I feared the great multitude,and the contempt of families terrified me,so that I kept silence, and did not go out of the door-
B018C031V035	18	31	35	oh that I had one to hear me!(behold, here is my signature, let the Almighty answer me);let the accuser write my indictment!
B018C031V036	18	31	36	Surely I would carry it on my shoulder;and I would bind it to me as a crown.
B018C031V037	18	31	37	I would declare to him the number of my steps;as a prince would I go near to him.
B018C031V038	18	31	38	If my land cries out against me,and its furrows weep together;
B018C031V039	18	31	39	if I have eaten its fruits without money,or have caused its owners to lose their life,
B018C031V040	18	31	40	let briars grow instead of wheat,and stinkweed instead of barley." 
B018C032V001	18	32	1	So these three men ceased to answer Job, because he was righteous in his own eyes.
B018C032V002	18	32	2	Then the wrath of Elihu the son of Barachel, the Buzite, of the family of Ram, was kindled against Job. His wrath was kindled because he justified himself rather than God.
B018C032V003	18	32	3	Also his wrath was kindled against his three friends, because they had found no answer, and yet had condemned Job.
B018C032V004	18	32	4	Now Elihu had waited to speak to Job, because they were elder than he.
B018C032V005	18	32	5	When Elihu saw that there was no answer in the mouth of these three men, his wrath was kindled.
B018C032V006	18	32	6	Elihu the son of Barachel the Buzite answered, "I am young, and you are very old;Therefore I held back, and did not dare show you my opinion.
B018C032V007	18	32	7	I said, 'Days should speak,and multitude of years should teach wisdom.'
B018C032V008	18	32	8	But there is a spirit in man,and the breath of the Almighty gives them understanding.
B018C032V009	18	32	9	It is not the great who are wise,nor the aged who understand justice.
B018C032V010	18	32	10	Therefore I said, 'Listen to me;I also will show my opinion.'
B018C032V011	18	32	11	"Behold, I waited for your words,and I listened for your reasoning,while you searched out what to say.
B018C032V012	18	32	12	Yes, I gave you my full attention,but there was no one who convinced Job,or who answered his words, among you.
B018C032V013	18	32	13	Beware lest you say, 'We have found wisdom,God may refute him, not man;'
B018C032V014	18	32	14	for he has not directed his words against me;neither will I answer him with your speeches.
B018C032V015	18	32	15	"They are amazed. They answer no more.They do not have a word to say.
B018C032V016	18	32	16	Shall I wait, because they do not speak,because they stand still, and answer no more?
B018C032V017	18	32	17	I also will answer my part,and I also will show my opinion.
B018C032V018	18	32	18	For I am full of words.The spirit within me constrains me.
B018C032V019	18	32	19	Behold, my breast is as wine which has no vent;like new wineskins it is ready to burst.
B018C032V020	18	32	20	I will speak, that I may be refreshed.I will open my lips and answer.
B018C032V021	18	32	21	Please do not let me respect any man's person,neither will I give flattering titles to any man.
B018C032V022	18	32	22	For I do not know how to give flattering titles;or else my Maker would soon take me away.
B018C033V001	18	33	1	"However, Job, Please hear my speech, and listen to all my words.
B018C033V002	18	33	2	See now, I have opened my mouth.My tongue has spoken in my mouth.
B018C033V003	18	33	3	My words shall utter the uprightness of my heart.That which my lips know they shall speak sincerely.
B018C033V004	18	33	4	The Spirit of God has made me,and the breath of the Almighty gives me life.
B018C033V005	18	33	5	If you can, answer me.Set your words in order before me, and stand forth.
B018C033V006	18	33	6	Behold, I am toward God even as you are.I am also formed out of the clay.
B018C033V007	18	33	7	Behold, my terror shall not make you afraid,neither shall my pressure be heavy on you.
B018C033V008	18	33	8	"Surely you have spoken in my hearing,I have heard the voice of your words, saying,
B018C033V009	18	33	9	'I am clean, without disobedience.I am innocent, neither is there iniquity in me.
B018C033V010	18	33	10	Behold, he finds occasions against me.He counts me for his enemy.
B018C033V011	18	33	11	He puts my feet in the stocks.He marks all my paths.'
B018C033V012	18	33	12	"Behold, I will answer you. In this you are not just,for God is greater than man.
B018C033V013	18	33	13	Why do you strive against him,because he doesn't give account of any of his matters?
B018C033V014	18	33	14	For God speaks once,yes twice, though man pays no attention.
B018C033V015	18	33	15	In a dream, in a vision of the night,when deep sleep falls on men,in slumbering on the bed;
B018C033V016	18	33	16	Then he opens the ears of men,and seals their instruction,
B018C033V017	18	33	17	That he may withdraw man from his purpose,and hide pride from man.
B018C033V018	18	33	18	He keeps back his soul from the pit,and his life from perishing by the sword.
B018C033V019	18	33	19	He is chastened also with pain on his bed,with continual strife in his bones;
B018C033V020	18	33	20	So that his life abhors bread,and his soul dainty food.
B018C033V021	18	33	21	His flesh is so consumed away, that it can't be seen.His bones that were not seen stick out.
B018C033V022	18	33	22	Yes, his soul draws near to the pit,and his life to the destroyers.
B018C033V023	18	33	23	"If there is beside him an angel,an interpreter, one among a thousand,to show to man what is right for him;
B018C033V024	18	33	24	then God is gracious to him, and says,'Deliver him from going down to the pit,I have found a ransom.'
B018C033V025	18	33	25	His flesh shall be fresher than a child's.He returns to the days of his youth.
B018C033V026	18	33	26	He prays to God, and he is favorable to him,so that he sees his face with joy.He restores to man his righteousness.
B018C033V027	18	33	27	He sings before men, and says,'I have sinned, and perverted that which was right,and it did not profit me.
B018C033V028	18	33	28	He has redeemed my soul from going into the pit.My life shall see the light.'
B018C033V029	18	33	29	"Behold, God works all these things,twice, yes three times, with a man,
B018C033V030	18	33	30	to bring back his soul from the pit,that he may be enlightened with the light of the living.
B018C033V031	18	33	31	Mark well, Job, and listen to me.Hold your peace, and I will speak.
B018C033V032	18	33	32	If you have anything to say, answer me.Speak, for I desire to justify you.
B018C033V033	18	33	33	If not, listen to me.Hold your peace, and I will teach you wisdom."
B018C034V001	18	34	1	Moreover Elihu answered,
B018C034V002	18	34	2	"Hear my words, you wise men.Give ear to me, you who have knowledge.
B018C034V003	18	34	3	For the ear tries words,as the palate tastes food.
B018C034V004	18	34	4	Let us choose for us that which is right.Let us know among ourselves what is good.
B018C034V005	18	34	5	For Job has said, 'I am righteous,God has taken away my right:
B018C034V006	18	34	6	Notwithstanding my right I am considered a liar.My wound is incurable, though I am without disobedience.'
B018C034V007	18	34	7	What man is like Job,who drinks scorn like water,
B018C034V008	18	34	8	Who goes in company with the workers of iniquity,and walks with wicked men?
B018C034V009	18	34	9	For he has said, 'It profits a man nothingthat he should delight himself with God.'
B018C034V010	18	34	10	"Therefore listen to me, you men of understanding:far be it from God, that he should do wickedness,from the Almighty, that he should commit iniquity.
B018C034V011	18	34	11	For the work of a man he will render to him,and cause every man to find according to his ways.
B018C034V012	18	34	12	Yes surely, God will not do wickedly,neither will the Almighty pervert justice.
B018C034V013	18	34	13	Who put him in charge of the earth?or who has appointed him over the whole world?
B018C034V014	18	34	14	If he set his heart on himself,If he gathered to himself his spirit and his breath,
B018C034V015	18	34	15	all flesh would perish together,and man would turn again to dust.
B018C034V016	18	34	16	"If now you have understanding, hear this.Listen to the voice of my words.
B018C034V017	18	34	17	Shall even one who hates justice govern?Will you condemn him who is righteous and mighty?-
B018C034V018	18	34	18	Who says to a king, 'Vile!'or to nobles, 'Wicked!'?
B018C034V019	18	34	19	Who doesn't respect the persons of princes,nor regards the rich more than the poor;for they all are the work of his hands.
B018C034V020	18	34	20	In a moment they die, even at midnight.The people are shaken and pass away.The mighty are taken away without a hand.
B018C034V021	18	34	21	"For his eyes are on the ways of a man.He sees all his goings.
B018C034V022	18	34	22	There is no darkness, nor thick gloom,where the workers of iniquity may hide themselves.
B018C034V023	18	34	23	For he doesn't need to consider a man further,that he should go before God in judgment.
B018C034V024	18	34	24	He breaks in pieces mighty men in ways past finding out,and sets others in their place.
B018C034V025	18	34	25	Therefore he takes knowledge of their works.He overturns them in the night, so that they are destroyed.
B018C034V026	18	34	26	He strikes them as wicked menin the open sight of others;
B018C034V027	18	34	27	because they turned aside from following him,and wouldn't pay attention to any of his ways,
B018C034V028	18	34	28	so that they caused the cry of the poor to come to him.He heard the cry of the afflicted.
B018C034V029	18	34	29	When he gives quietness, who then can condemn?When he hides his face, who then can see him?Alike whether to a nation, or to a man,
B018C034V030	18	34	30	that the godless man may not reign,that there be no one to ensnare the people.
B018C034V031	18	34	31	"For has any said to God,'I am guilty, but I will not offend any more.
B018C034V032	18	34	32	Teach me that which I do not see.If I have done iniquity, I will do it no more'?
B018C034V033	18	34	33	Shall his recompense be as you desire, that you refuse it?For you must choose, and not I.Therefore speak what you know.
B018C034V034	18	34	34	Men of understanding will tell me,yes, every wise man who hears me:
B018C034V035	18	34	35	'Job speaks without knowledge.His words are without wisdom.'
B018C034V036	18	34	36	I wish that Job were tried to the end,because of his answering like wicked men.
B018C034V037	18	34	37	For he adds rebellion to his sin.He claps his hands among us,and multiplies his words against God."
B018C035V001	18	35	1	Moreover Elihu answered,
B018C035V002	18	35	2	"Do you think this to be your right,or do you say, 'My righteousness is more than God's,'
B018C035V003	18	35	3	That you ask, 'What advantage will it be to you?What profit shall I have, more than if I had sinned?'
B018C035V004	18	35	4	I will answer you,and your companions with you.
B018C035V005	18	35	5	Look to the heavens, and see.See the skies, which are higher than you.
B018C035V006	18	35	6	If you have sinned, what effect do you have against him?If your transgressions are multiplied, what do you do to him?
B018C035V007	18	35	7	If you are righteous, what do you give him?Or what does he receive from your hand?
B018C035V008	18	35	8	Your wickedness may hurt a man as you are,and your righteousness may profit a son of man.
B018C035V009	18	35	9	"By reason of the multitude of oppressions they cry out.They cry for help by reason of the arm of the mighty.
B018C035V010	18	35	10	But none says, 'Where is God my Maker,who gives songs in the night,
B018C035V011	18	35	11	who teaches us more than the animals of the earth,and makes us wiser than the birds of the sky?'
B018C035V012	18	35	12	There they cry, but none gives answer,because of the pride of evil men.
B018C035V013	18	35	13	Surely God will not hear an empty cry,neither will the Almighty regard it.
B018C035V014	18	35	14	How much less when you say you do not see him.The cause is before him, and you wait for him!
B018C035V015	18	35	15	But now, because he has not visited in his anger,neither does he greatly regard arrogance.
B018C035V016	18	35	16	Therefore Job opens his mouth with empty talk,and he multiplies words without knowledge."
B018C036V001	18	36	1	Elihu also continued, and said,
B018C036V002	18	36	2	"Bear with me a little, and I will show you;for I still have something to say on God's behalf.
B018C036V003	18	36	3	I will get my knowledge from afar,and will ascribe righteousness to my Maker.
B018C036V004	18	36	4	For truly my words are not false.One who is perfect in knowledge is with you.
B018C036V005	18	36	5	"Behold, God is mighty, and doesn't despise anyone.He is mighty in strength of understanding.
B018C036V006	18	36	6	He doesn't preserve the life of the wicked,but gives to the afflicted their right.
B018C036V007	18	36	7	He doesn't withdraw his eyes from the righteous,but with kings on the throne,he sets them forever, and they are exalted.
B018C036V008	18	36	8	If they are bound in fetters,and are taken in the cords of afflictions,
B018C036V009	18	36	9	then he shows them their work,and their transgressions, that they have behaved themselves proudly.
B018C036V010	18	36	10	He also opens their ears to instruction,and commands that they return from iniquity.
B018C036V011	18	36	11	If they listen and serve him,they shall spend their days in prosperity,and their years in pleasures.
B018C036V012	18	36	12	But if they do not listen, they shall perish by the sword;they shall die without knowledge.
B018C036V013	18	36	13	"But those who are godless in heart lay up anger.They do not cry for help when he binds them.
B018C036V014	18	36	14	They die in youth.Their life perishes among the unclean.
B018C036V015	18	36	15	He delivers the afflicted by their affliction,and opens their ear in oppression.
B018C036V016	18	36	16	Yes, he would have allured you out of distress,into a broad place, where there is no restriction.That which is set on your table would be full of fatness.
B018C036V017	18	36	17	"But you are full of the judgment of the wicked.Judgment and justice take hold of you.
B018C036V018	18	36	18	Do not let riches entice you to wrath,neither let the great size of a bribe turn you aside.
B018C036V019	18	36	19	Would your wealth sustain you in distress,or all the might of your strength?
B018C036V020	18	36	20	Do not desire the night,when people are cut off in their place.
B018C036V021	18	36	21	Take heed, do not regard iniquity;for you have chosen this rather than affliction.
B018C036V022	18	36	22	Behold, God is exalted in his power.Who is a teacher like him?
B018C036V023	18	36	23	Who has prescribed his way for him?Or who can say, 'You have committed unrighteousness?'
B018C036V024	18	36	24	"Remember that you magnify his work,whereof men have sung.
B018C036V025	18	36	25	All men have looked thereon.Man sees it afar off.
B018C036V026	18	36	26	Behold, God is great, and we do not know him.The number of his years is unsearchable.
B018C036V027	18	36	27	For he draws up the drops of water,which distill in rain from his vapor,
B018C036V028	18	36	28	Which the skies pour downand which drop on man abundantly.
B018C036V029	18	36	29	Yes, can any understand the spreading of the clouds,and the thunderings of his pavilion?
B018C036V030	18	36	30	Behold, he spreads his light around him.He covers the bottom of the sea.
B018C036V031	18	36	31	For by these he judges the people.He gives food in abundance.
B018C036V032	18	36	32	He covers his hands with the lightning,and commands it to strike the mark.
B018C036V033	18	36	33	Its noise tells about him,and the livestock also concerning the storm that comes up.
B018C037V001	18	37	1	"Yes, at this my heart trembles, and is moved out of its place.
B018C037V002	18	37	2	Hear, oh, hear the noise of his voice,the sound that goes out of his mouth.
B018C037V003	18	37	3	He sends it forth under the whole sky,and his lightning to the ends of the earth.
B018C037V004	18	37	4	After it a voice roars.He thunders with the voice of his majesty.He doesn't hold back anything when his voice is heard.
B018C037V005	18	37	5	God thunders marvelously with his voice.He does great things, which we can't comprehend.
B018C037V006	18	37	6	For he says to the snow, 'Fall on the earth;'likewise to the shower of rain,and to the showers of his mighty rain.
B018C037V007	18	37	7	He seals up the hand of every man,that all men whom he has made may know it.
B018C037V008	18	37	8	Then the animals take cover,and remain in their dens.
B018C037V009	18	37	9	Out of its chamber comes the storm,and cold out of the north.
B018C037V010	18	37	10	By the breath of God, ice is given,and the breadth of the waters is frozen.
B018C037V011	18	37	11	Yes, he loads the thick cloud with moisture.He spreads abroad the cloud of his lightning.
B018C037V012	18	37	12	It is turned around by his guidance,that they may do whatever he commands themon the surface of the habitable world,
B018C037V013	18	37	13	Whether it is for correction, or for his land,or for loving kindness, that he causes it to come.
B018C037V014	18	37	14	"Listen to this, Job.Stand still, and consider the wondrous works of God.
B018C037V015	18	37	15	Do you know how God controls them,and causes the lightning of his cloud to shine?
B018C037V016	18	37	16	Do you know the workings of the clouds,the wondrous works of him who is perfect in knowledge?
B018C037V017	18	37	17	You whose clothing is warm,when the earth is still by reason of the south wind?
B018C037V018	18	37	18	Can you, with him, spread out the sky,which is strong as a cast metal mirror?
B018C037V019	18	37	19	Teach us what we shall tell him,for we can't make our case by reason of darkness.
B018C037V020	18	37	20	Shall it be told him that I would speak?Or should a man wish that he were swallowed up?
B018C037V021	18	37	21	Now men do not see the light which is bright in the skies,but the wind passes, and clears them.
B018C037V022	18	37	22	Out of the north comes golden splendor.With God is awesome majesty.
B018C037V023	18	37	23	We can't reach the Almighty.He is exalted in power.In justice and great righteousness, he will not oppress.
B018C037V024	18	37	24	Therefore men revere him.He doesn't regard any who are wise of heart."
B018C038V001	18	38	1	Then 
B018C038V002	18	38	2	"Who is this who darkens counselby words without knowledge?
B018C038V003	18	38	3	Brace yourself like a man,for I will question you, then you answer me!
B018C038V004	18	38	4	"Where were you when I laid the foundations of the earth?Declare, if you have understanding.
B018C038V005	18	38	5	Who determined its measures, if you know?Or who stretched the line on it?
B018C038V006	18	38	6	Whereupon were its foundations fastened?Or who laid its cornerstone,
B018C038V007	18	38	7	when the morning stars sang together,and all the sons of God shouted for joy?
B018C038V008	18	38	8	"Or who shut up the sea with doors,when it broke forth from the womb,
B018C038V009	18	38	9	when I made clouds its garment,and wrapped it in thick darkness,
B018C038V010	18	38	10	marked out for it my bound,set bars and doors,
B018C038V011	18	38	11	and said, 'Here you may come, but no further.Here your proud waves shall be stayed?'
B018C038V012	18	38	12	"Have you commanded the morning in your days,and caused the dawn to know its place;
B018C038V013	18	38	13	that it might take hold of the ends of the earth,and shake the wicked out of it?
B018C038V014	18	38	14	It is changed as clay under the seal,and stands forth as a garment.
B018C038V015	18	38	15	From the wicked, their light is withheld.The high arm is broken.
B018C038V016	18	38	16	"Have you entered into the springs of the sea?Or have you walked in the recesses of the deep?
B018C038V017	18	38	17	Have the gates of death been revealed to you?Or have you seen the gates of the shadow of death?
B018C038V018	18	38	18	Have you comprehended the earth in its breadth?Declare, if you know it all.
B018C038V019	18	38	19	"What is the way to the dwelling of light?As for darkness, where is its place,
B018C038V020	18	38	20	that you should take it to its bound,that you should discern the paths to its house?
B018C038V021	18	38	21	Surely you know, for you were born then,and the number of your days is great!
B018C038V022	18	38	22	Have you entered the treasuries of the snow,or have you seen the treasures of the hail,
B018C038V023	18	38	23	which I have reserved against the time of trouble,against the day of battle and war?
B018C038V024	18	38	24	By what way is the lightning distributed,or the east wind scattered on the earth?
B018C038V025	18	38	25	Who has cut a channel for the flood water,or the path for the thunderstorm;
B018C038V026	18	38	26	To cause it to rain on a land where no man is;on the wilderness, in which there is no man;
B018C038V027	18	38	27	to satisfy the waste and desolate ground,to cause the tender grass to spring forth?
B018C038V028	18	38	28	Does the rain have a father?Or who fathers the drops of dew?
B018C038V029	18	38	29	Out of whose womb came the ice?The gray frost of the sky, who has given birth to it?
B018C038V030	18	38	30	The waters become hard like stone,when the surface of the deep is frozen.
B018C038V031	18	38	31	"Can you bind the cluster of the Pleiades,or loosen the cords of Orion?
B018C038V032	18	38	32	Can you lead forth the constellations in their season?Or can you guide the Bear with her cubs?
B018C038V033	18	38	33	Do you know the laws of the heavens?Can you establish its dominion over the earth?
B018C038V034	18	38	34	"Can you lift up your voice to the clouds,That abundance of waters may cover you?
B018C038V035	18	38	35	Can you send forth lightnings, that they may go?Do they report to you, 'Here we are?'
B018C038V036	18	38	36	Who has put wisdom in the inward parts?Or who has given understanding to the mind?
B018C038V037	18	38	37	Who can number the clouds by wisdom?Or who can pour out the bottles of the sky,
B018C038V038	18	38	38	when the dust runs into a mass,and the clods of earth stick together?
B018C038V039	18	38	39	"Can you hunt the prey for the lioness,or satisfy the appetite of the young lions,
B018C038V040	18	38	40	when they crouch in their dens,and lie in wait in the thicket?
B018C038V041	18	38	41	Who provides for the raven his prey,when his young ones cry to God,and wander for lack of food?
B018C039V001	18	39	1	"Do you know the time when the mountain goats give birth? Do you watch when the doe bears fawns?
B018C039V002	18	39	2	Can you number the months that they fulfill?Or do you know the time when they give birth?
B018C039V003	18	39	3	They bow themselves, they bring forth their young,they end their labor pains.
B018C039V004	18	39	4	Their young ones become strong.They grow up in the open field.They go forth, and do not return again.
B018C039V005	18	39	5	"Who has set the wild donkey free?Or who has loosened the bonds of the swift donkey,
B018C039V006	18	39	6	Whose home I have made the wilderness,and the salt land his dwelling place?
B018C039V007	18	39	7	He scorns the tumult of the city,neither does he hear the shouting of the driver.
B018C039V008	18	39	8	The range of the mountains is his pasture,He searches after every green thing.
B018C039V009	18	39	9	"Will the wild ox be content to serve you?Or will he stay by your feeding trough?
B018C039V010	18	39	10	Can you hold the wild ox in the furrow with his harness?Or will he till the valleys after you?
B018C039V011	18	39	11	Will you trust him, because his strength is great?Or will you leave to him your labor?
B018C039V012	18	39	12	Will you confide in him, that he will bring home your seed,and gather the grain of your threshing floor?
B018C039V013	18	39	13	"The wings of the ostrich wave proudly;but are they the feathers and plumage of love?
B018C039V014	18	39	14	For she leaves her eggs on the earth,warms them in the dust,
B018C039V015	18	39	15	and forgets that the foot may crush them,or that the wild animal may trample them.
B018C039V016	18	39	16	She deals harshly with her young ones, as if they were not hers.Though her labor is in vain, she is without fear,
B018C039V017	18	39	17	because God has deprived her of wisdom,neither has he imparted to her understanding.
B018C039V018	18	39	18	When she lifts up herself on high,she scorns the horse and his rider.
B018C039V019	18	39	19	"Have you given the horse might?Have you clothed his neck with a quivering mane?
B018C039V020	18	39	20	Have you made him to leap as a locust?The glory of his snorting is awesome.
B018C039V021	18	39	21	He paws in the valley, and rejoices in his strength.He goes out to meet the armed men.
B018C039V022	18	39	22	He mocks at fear, and is not dismayed,neither does he turn back from the sword.
B018C039V023	18	39	23	The quiver rattles against him,the flashing spear and the javelin.
B018C039V024	18	39	24	He eats up the ground with fierceness and rage,neither does he stand still at the sound of the trumpet.
B018C039V025	18	39	25	As often as the trumpet sounds he snorts, 'Aha!'He smells the battle afar off,the thunder of the captains, and the shouting.
B018C039V026	18	39	26	"Is it by your wisdom that the hawk soars,and stretches her wings toward the south?
B018C039V027	18	39	27	Is it at your command that the eagle mounts up,and makes his nest on high?
B018C039V028	18	39	28	On the cliff he dwells, and makes his home,on the point of the cliff, and the stronghold.
B018C039V029	18	39	29	From there he spies out the prey.His eyes see it afar off.
B018C039V030	18	39	30	His young ones also suck up blood.Where the slain are, there he is."
B018C040V001	18	40	1	Moreover 
B018C040V002	18	40	2	"Shall he who argues contend with the Almighty?He who argues with God, let him answer it." 
B018C040V003	18	40	3	Then Job answered 
B018C040V004	18	40	4	"Behold, I am of small account. What shall I answer you?I lay my hand on my mouth.
B018C040V005	18	40	5	I have spoken once, and I will not answer;Yes, twice, but I will proceed no further." 
B018C040V006	18	40	6	Then 
B018C040V007	18	40	7	"Now brace yourself like a man.I will question you, and you will answer me.
B018C040V008	18	40	8	Will you even annul my judgment?Will you condemn me, that you may be justified?
B018C040V009	18	40	9	Or do you have an arm like God?Can you thunder with a voice like him?
B018C040V010	18	40	10	"Now deck yourself with excellency and dignity.Array yourself with honor and majesty.
B018C040V011	18	40	11	Pour out the fury of your anger.Look at everyone who is proud, and bring him low.
B018C040V012	18	40	12	Look at everyone who is proud, and humble him.Crush the wicked in their place.
B018C040V013	18	40	13	Hide them in the dust together.Bind their faces in the hidden place.
B018C040V014	18	40	14	Then I will also admit to youthat your own right hand can save you.
B018C040V015	18	40	15	"See now, behemoth, which I made as well as you.He eats grass as an ox.
B018C040V016	18	40	16	Look now, his strength is in his thighs.His force is in the muscles of his belly.
B018C040V017	18	40	17	He moves his tail like a cedar.The sinews of his thighs are knit together.
B018C040V018	18	40	18	His bones are like tubes of brass.His limbs are like bars of iron.
B018C040V019	18	40	19	He is the chief of the ways of God.He who made him gives him his sword.
B018C040V020	18	40	20	Surely the mountains produce food for him,where all the animals of the field play.
B018C040V021	18	40	21	He lies under the lotus trees,in the covert of the reed, and the marsh.
B018C040V022	18	40	22	The lotuses cover him with their shade.The willows of the brook surround him.
B018C040V023	18	40	23	Behold, if a river overflows, he doesn't tremble.He is confident, though the Jordan swells even to his mouth.
B018C040V024	18	40	24	Shall any take him when he is on the watch,or pierce through his nose with a snare?
B018C041V001	18	41	1	"Can you draw out Leviathan with a fishhook, or press down his tongue with a cord?
B018C041V002	18	41	2	Can you put a rope into his nose,or pierce his jaw through with a hook?
B018C041V003	18	41	3	Will he make many petitions to you,or will he speak soft words to you?
B018C041V004	18	41	4	Will he make a covenant with you,that you should take him for a servant forever?
B018C041V005	18	41	5	Will you play with him as with a bird?Or will you bind him for your girls?
B018C041V006	18	41	6	Will traders barter for him?Will they part him among the merchants?
B018C041V007	18	41	7	Can you fill his skin with barbed irons,or his head with fish spears?
B018C041V008	18	41	8	Lay your hand on him.Remember the battle, and do so no more.
B018C041V009	18	41	9	Behold, the hope of him is in vain.Won't one be cast down even at the sight of him?
B018C041V010	18	41	10	None is so fierce that he dare stir him up.Who then is he who can stand before me?
B018C041V011	18	41	11	Who has first given to me, that I should repay him?Everything under the heavens is mine.
B018C041V012	18	41	12	"I will not keep silence concerning his limbs,nor his mighty strength, nor his goodly frame.
B018C041V013	18	41	13	Who can strip off his outer garment?Who shall come within his jaws?
B018C041V014	18	41	14	Who can open the doors of his face?Around his teeth is terror.
B018C041V015	18	41	15	Strong scales are his pride,shut up together with a close seal.
B018C041V016	18	41	16	One is so near to another,that no air can come between them.
B018C041V017	18	41	17	They are joined one to another.They stick together, so that they can't be pulled apart.
