B020C024V023	20	24	23	These also are sayings of the wise. To show partiality in judgment is not good.
B020C024V024	20	24	24	He who says to the wicked, "You are righteous;"peoples shall curse him, and nations shall abhor him-
B020C024V025	20	24	25	but it will go well with those who convict the guilty,and a rich blessing will come on them.
B020C024V026	20	24	26	An honest answeris like a kiss on the lips.
B020C024V027	20	24	27	Prepare your work outside,and get your fields ready.Afterwards, build your house.
B020C024V028	20	24	28	Do not be a witness against your neighbor without cause.Do not deceive with your lips.
B020C024V029	20	24	29	Do not say, "I will do to him as he has done to me;I will render to the man according to his work."
B020C024V030	20	24	30	I went by the field of the sluggard,by the vineyard of the man void of understanding;
B020C024V031	20	24	31	Behold, it was all grown over with thorns.Its surface was covered with nettles,and its stone wall was broken down.
B020C024V032	20	24	32	Then I saw, and considered well.I saw, and received instruction:
B020C024V033	20	24	33	a little sleep, a little slumber,a little folding of the hands to sleep;
B020C024V034	20	24	34	so your poverty will come as a robber,and your want as an armed man.
B020C025V001	20	25	1	These also are proverbs of Solomon, which the men of Hezekiah king of Judah copied out.
B020C025V002	20	25	2	It is the glory of God to conceal a thing,but the glory of kings is to search out a matter.
B020C025V003	20	25	3	As the heavens for height, and the earth for depth,so the hearts of kings are unsearchable.
B020C025V004	20	25	4	Take away the dross from the silver,and material comes out for the refiner;
B020C025V005	20	25	5	Take away the wicked from the king's presence,and his throne will be established in righteousness.
B020C025V006	20	25	6	Do not exalt yourself in the presence of the king,or claim a place among great men;
B020C025V007	20	25	7	for it is better that it be said to you, "Come up here,"than that you should be put lower in the presence of the prince,whom your eyes have seen.
B020C025V008	20	25	8	Do not be hasty in bringing charges to court.What will you do in the end when your neighbor shames you?
B020C025V009	20	25	9	Debate your case with your neighbor,and do not betray the confidence of another;
B020C025V010	20	25	10	lest one who hears it put you to shame,and your bad reputation never depart.
B020C025V011	20	25	11	A word fitly spokenis like apples of gold in settings of silver.
B020C025V012	20	25	12	As an earring of gold, and an ornament of fine gold,so is a wise reprover to an obedient ear.
B020C025V013	20	25	13	As the cold of snow in the time of harvest,so is a faithful messenger to those who send him;for he refreshes the soul of his masters.
B020C025V014	20	25	14	As clouds and wind without rain,so is he who boasts of gifts deceptively.
B020C025V015	20	25	15	By patience a ruler is persuaded.A soft tongue breaks the bone.
B020C025V016	20	25	16	Have you found honey?Eat as much as is sufficient for you,lest you eat too much, and vomit it.
B020C025V017	20	25	17	Let your foot be seldom in your neighbor's house,lest he be weary of you, and hate you.
B020C025V018	20	25	18	A man who gives false testimony against his neighboris like a club, a sword, or a sharp arrow.
B020C025V019	20	25	19	Confidence in someone unfaithful in time of troubleis like a bad tooth, or a lame foot.
B020C025V020	20	25	20	As one who takes away a garment in cold weather,or vinegar on soda,so is one who sings songs to a heavy heart.
B020C025V021	20	25	21	If your enemy is hungry, give him food to eat.If he is thirsty, give him water to drink:
B020C025V022	20	25	22	for you will heap coals of fire on his head,and 
B020C025V023	20	25	23	The north wind brings forth rain:so a backbiting tongue brings an angry face.
B020C025V024	20	25	24	It is better to dwell in the corner of the housetop,than to share a house with a contentious woman.
B020C025V025	20	25	25	Like cold water to a thirsty soul,so is good news from a far country.
B020C025V026	20	25	26	Like a muddied spring, and a polluted well,so is a righteous man who gives way before the wicked.
B020C025V027	20	25	27	It is not good to eat much honey;nor is it honorable to seek one's own honor.
B020C025V028	20	25	28	Like a city that is broken down and without wallsis a man whose spirit is without restraint.
B020C026V001	20	26	1	Like snow in summer, and as rain in harvest, so honor is not fitting for a fool.
B020C026V002	20	26	2	Like a fluttering sparrow,like a darting swallow,so the undeserved curse doesn't come to rest.
B020C026V003	20	26	3	A whip is for the horse,a bridle for the donkey,and a rod for the back of fools!
B020C026V004	20	26	4	Do not answer a fool according to his folly,lest you also be like him.
B020C026V005	20	26	5	Answer a fool according to his folly,lest he be wise in his own eyes.
B020C026V006	20	26	6	One who sends a message by the hand of a foolis cutting off feet and drinking violence.
B020C026V007	20	26	7	Like the legs of the lame that hang loose:so is a parable in the mouth of fools.
B020C026V008	20	26	8	As one who binds a stone in a sling,so is he who gives honor to a fool.
B020C026V009	20	26	9	Like a thornbush that goes into the hand of a drunkard,so is a parable in the mouth of fools.
B020C026V010	20	26	10	As an archer who wounds all,so is he who hires a foolor he who hires those who pass by.
B020C026V011	20	26	11	As a dog that returns to his vomit,so is a fool who repeats his folly.
B020C026V012	20	26	12	Do you see a man wise in his own eyes?There is more hope for a fool than for him.
B020C026V013	20	26	13	The sluggard says, "There is a lion in the road!A fierce lion roams the streets!"
B020C026V014	20	26	14	As the door turns on its hinges,so does the sluggard on his bed.
B020C026V015	20	26	15	The sluggard buries his hand in the dish.He is too lazy to bring it back to his mouth.
B020C026V016	20	26	16	The sluggard is wiser in his own eyesthan seven men who answer with discretion.
B020C026V017	20	26	17	Like one who grabs a dog's earsis one who passes by and meddles in a quarrel not his own.
B020C026V018	20	26	18	Like a madman who shoots firebrands, arrows, and death,
B020C026V019	20	26	19	is the man who deceives his neighbor and says, "Am I not joking?"
B020C026V020	20	26	20	For lack of wood a fire goes out.Without gossip, a quarrel dies down.
B020C026V021	20	26	21	As coals are to hot embers,and wood to fire,so is a contentious man to kindling strife.
B020C026V022	20	26	22	The words of a whisperer are as dainty morsels,they go down into the innermost parts.
B020C026V023	20	26	23	Like silver dross on an earthen vesselare the lips of a fervent one with an evil heart.
B020C026V024	20	26	24	A malicious man disguises himself with his lips,but he harbors evil in his heart.
B020C026V025	20	26	25	When his speech is charming, do not believe him;for there are seven abominations in his heart.
B020C026V026	20	26	26	His malice may be concealed by deception,but his wickedness will be exposed in the assembly.
B020C026V027	20	26	27	Whoever digs a pit shall fall into it.Whoever rolls a stone, it will come back on him.
B020C026V028	20	26	28	A lying tongue hates those it hurts;and a flattering mouth works ruin.
B020C027V001	20	27	1	Do not boast about tomorrow; for you do not know what a day may bring forth.
B020C027V002	20	27	2	Let another man praise you,and not your own mouth;a stranger, and not your own lips.
B020C027V003	20	27	3	A stone is heavy,and sand is a burden;but a fool's provocation is heavier than both.
B020C027V004	20	27	4	Wrath is cruel,and anger is overwhelming;but who is able to stand before jealousy?
B020C027V005	20	27	5	Better is open rebukethan hidden love.
B020C027V006	20	27	6	Faithful are the wounds of a friend;although the kisses of an enemy are profuse.
B020C027V007	20	27	7	A full soul loathes a honeycomb;but to a hungry soul, every bitter thing is sweet.
B020C027V008	20	27	8	As a bird that wanders from her nest,so is a man who wanders from his home.
B020C027V009	20	27	9	Perfume and incense bring joy to the heart;so does earnest counsel from a man's friend.
B020C027V010	20	27	10	Do not forsake your friend and your father's friend.Do not go to your brother's house in the day of your disaster:better is a neighbor who is near than a distant brother.
B020C027V011	20	27	11	Be wise, my son,and bring joy to my heart,then I can answer my tormentor.
B020C027V012	20	27	12	A prudent man sees danger and takes refuge;but the simple pass on, and suffer for it.
B020C027V013	20	27	13	Take his garment when he puts up collateral for a stranger.Hold it for a wayward woman!
B020C027V014	20	27	14	He who blesses his neighbor with a loud voice early in the morning,it will be taken as a curse by him.
B020C027V015	20	27	15	A continual dropping on a rainy dayand a contentious wife are alike:
B020C027V016	20	27	16	restraining her is like restraining the wind,or like grasping oil in his right hand.
B020C027V017	20	27	17	Iron sharpens iron;so a man sharpens his friend's countenance.
B020C027V018	20	27	18	Whoever tends the fig tree shall eat its fruit.He who looks after his master shall be honored.
B020C027V019	20	27	19	As water reflects a face,so a man's heart reflects the man.
B020C027V020	20	27	20	Sheol and Abaddon are never satisfied;and a man's eyes are never satisfied.
B020C027V021	20	27	21	The crucible is for silver,and the furnace for gold;but man is refined by his praise.
B020C027V022	20	27	22	Though you grind a fool in a mortar with a pestle along with grain,yet his foolishness will not be removed from him.
B020C027V023	20	27	23	Know well the state of your flocks,and pay attention to your herds:
B020C027V024	20	27	24	for riches are not forever,nor does even the crown endure to all generations.
B020C027V025	20	27	25	The hay is removed, and the new growth appears,the grasses of the hills are gathered in.
B020C027V026	20	27	26	The lambs are for your clothing,and the goats are the price of a field.
B020C027V027	20	27	27	There will be plenty of goats' milk for your food,for your family's food,and for the nourishment of your servant girls.
B020C028V001	20	28	1	The wicked flee when no one pursues; but the righteous are as bold as a lion.
B020C028V002	20	28	2	In rebellion, a land has many rulers,but order is maintained by a man of understanding and knowledge.
B020C028V003	20	28	3	A needy man who oppresses the pooris like a driving rain which leaves no crops.
B020C028V004	20	28	4	Those who forsake the Law praise the wicked;but those who keep the Law contend with them.
B020C028V005	20	28	5	Evil men do not understand justice;but those who seek 
B020C028V006	20	28	6	Better is the poor who walks in his integrity,than he who is perverse in his ways, and he is rich.
B020C028V007	20	28	7	Whoever keeps the Law is a wise son;but he who is a companion of gluttons shames his father.
B020C028V008	20	28	8	He who increases his wealth by excessive interestgathers it for one who has pity on the poor.
B020C028V009	20	28	9	He who turns away his ear from hearing the Law,even his prayer is an abomination.
B020C028V010	20	28	10	Whoever causes the upright to go astray in an evil way,he will fall into his own trap;but the blameless will inherit good.
B020C028V011	20	28	11	The rich man is wise in his own eyes;but the poor who has understanding sees through him.
B020C028V012	20	28	12	When the righteous triumph, there is great glory;but when the wicked rise, men hide themselves.
B020C028V013	20	28	13	He who conceals his sins doesn't prosper,but whoever confesses and renounces them finds mercy.
B020C028V014	20	28	14	Blessed is the man who always fears;but one who hardens his heart falls into trouble.
B020C028V015	20	28	15	As a roaring lion or a charging bear,so is a wicked ruler over helpless people.
B020C028V016	20	28	16	A tyrannical ruler lacks judgment.One who hates ill-gotten gain will have long days.
B020C028V017	20	28	17	A man who is tormented by life blood will be a fugitive until death;no one will support him.
B020C028V018	20	28	18	Whoever walks blamelessly is kept safe;but one with perverse ways will fall suddenly.
B020C028V019	20	28	19	One who works his land will have an abundance of food;but one who chases fantasies will have his fill of poverty.
B020C028V020	20	28	20	A faithful man is rich with blessings;but one who is eager to be rich will not go unpunished.
B020C028V021	20	28	21	To show partiality is not good;yet a man will do wrong for a piece of bread.
B020C028V022	20	28	22	A stingy man hurries after riches,and doesn't know that poverty waits for him.
B020C028V023	20	28	23	One who rebukes a man will afterward find more favorthan one who flatters with the tongue.
B020C028V024	20	28	24	Whoever robs his father or his mother, and says, "It's not wrong."He is a partner with a destroyer.
B020C028V025	20	28	25	One who is greedy stirs up strife;but one who trusts in 
B020C028V026	20	28	26	One who trusts in himself is a fool;but one who walks in wisdom is kept safe.
B020C028V027	20	28	27	One who gives to the poor has no lack;but one who closes his eyes will have many curses.
B020C028V028	20	28	28	When the wicked rise, men hide themselves;but when they perish, the righteous thrive.
B020C029V001	20	29	1	He who is often rebuked and stiffens his neck will be destroyed suddenly, with no remedy.
B020C029V002	20	29	2	When the righteous thrive, the people rejoice;but when the wicked rule, the people groan.
B020C029V003	20	29	3	Whoever loves wisdom brings joy to his father;but a companion of prostitutes squanders his wealth.
B020C029V004	20	29	4	The king by justice makes the land stable,but he who takes bribes tears it down.
B020C029V005	20	29	5	A man who flatters his neighborspreads a net for his feet.
B020C029V006	20	29	6	An evil man is snared by his sin,but the righteous can sing and be glad.
B020C029V007	20	29	7	The righteous care about justice for the poor.The wicked aren't concerned about knowledge.
B020C029V008	20	29	8	Mockers stir up a city,but wise men turn away anger.
B020C029V009	20	29	9	If a wise man goes to court with a foolish man,the fool rages or scoffs, and there is no peace.
B020C029V010	20	29	10	The bloodthirsty hate a man of integrity;and they seek the life of the upright.
B020C029V011	20	29	11	A fool vents all of his anger,but a wise man brings himself under control.
B020C029V012	20	29	12	If a ruler listens to lies,all of his officials are wicked.
B020C029V013	20	29	13	The poor man and the oppressor have this in common:
B020C029V014	20	29	14	The king who fairly judges the poor,his throne shall be established forever.
B020C029V015	20	29	15	The rod of correction gives wisdom,but a child left to himself causes shame to his mother.
B020C029V016	20	29	16	When the wicked increase, sin increases;but the righteous will see their downfall.
B020C029V017	20	29	17	Correct your son, and he will give you peace;yes, he will bring delight to your soul.
B020C029V018	20	29	18	Where there is no revelation, the people cast off restraint;but one who keeps the Law is blessed.
B020C029V019	20	29	19	A servant can't be corrected by words.Though he understands, yet he will not respond.
B020C029V020	20	29	20	Do you see a man who is hasty in his words?There is more hope for a fool than for him.
B020C029V021	20	29	21	He who pampers his servant from youthwill have him become a son in the end.
B020C029V022	20	29	22	An angry man stirs up strife,and a wrathful man abounds in sin.
B020C029V023	20	29	23	A man's pride brings him low,but one of lowly spirit gains honor.
B020C029V024	20	29	24	Whoever is an accomplice of a thief is an enemy of his own soul.He takes an oath, but dares not testify.
B020C029V025	20	29	25	The fear of man proves to be a snare,but whoever puts his trust in 
B020C029V026	20	29	26	Many seek the ruler's favor,but a man's justice comes from 
B020C029V027	20	29	27	A dishonest man detests the righteous,and the upright in their ways detest the wicked.
B020C030V001	20	30	1	The words of Agur the son of Jakeh, the oracle: the man says to Ithiel,to Ithiel and Ucal:
B020C030V002	20	30	2	"Surely I am the most ignorant man,and do not have a man's understanding.
B020C030V003	20	30	3	I have not learned wisdom,neither do I have the knowledge of the Holy One.
B020C030V004	20	30	4	Who has ascended up into heaven, and descended?Who has gathered the wind in his fists?Who has bound the waters in his garment?Who has established all the ends of the earth?What is his name, and what is his son's name, if you know?
B020C030V005	20	30	5	"Every word of God is flawless.He is a shield to those who take refuge in him.
B020C030V006	20	30	6	Do not add to his words,lest he reprove you, and you be found a liar.
B020C030V007	20	30	7	"Two things I have asked of you;do not deny me before I die:
B020C030V008	20	30	8	Remove far from me falsehood and lies.Give me neither poverty nor riches.Feed me with the food that is needful for me;
B020C030V009	20	30	9	lest I be full, deny you, and say, 'Who is 
B020C030V010	20	30	10	"Do not slander a servant to his master,lest he curse you, and you be held guilty.
B020C030V011	20	30	11	There is a generation that curses their father,and doesn't bless their mother.
B020C030V012	20	30	12	There is a generation that is pure in their own eyes,yet are not washed from their filthiness.
B020C030V013	20	30	13	There is a generation, oh how lofty are their eyes!Their eyelids are lifted up.
B020C030V014	20	30	14	There is a generation whose teeth are like swords,and their jaws like knives,to devour the poor from the earth, and the needy from among men.
B020C030V015	20	30	15	"The leach has two daughters:'Give, give.'"There are three things that are never satisfied;four that do not say, 'Enough:'
B020C030V016	20	30	16	Sheol,the barren womb;the earth that is not satisfied with water;and the fire that doesn't say, 'Enough.'
B020C030V017	20	30	17	"The eye that mocks at his father,and scorns obedience to his mother:the ravens of the valley shall pick it out,the young eagles shall eat it.
B020C030V018	20	30	18	"There are three things which are too amazing for me,four which I do not understand:
B020C030V019	20	30	19	The way of an eagle in the air;the way of a serpent on a rock;the way of a ship in the midst of the sea;and the way of a man with a maiden.
B020C030V020	20	30	20	"So is the way of an adulterous woman:she eats and wipes her mouth,and says, 'I have done nothing wrong.'
B020C030V021	20	30	21	"For three things the earth tremble,and under four, it can't bear up:
B020C030V022	20	30	22	For a servant when he is king;a fool when he is filled with food;
B020C030V023	20	30	23	for an unloved woman when she is married;and a handmaid who is heir to her mistress.
B020C030V024	20	30	24	"There are four things which are little on the earth,but they are exceedingly wise:
B020C030V025	20	30	25	the ants are not a strong people,yet they provide their food in the summer.
B020C030V026	20	30	26	The conies are but a feeble folk,yet make they their houses in the rocks.
B020C030V027	20	30	27	The locusts have no king,yet they advance in ranks.
B020C030V028	20	30	28	You can catch a lizard with your hands,yet it is in kings' palaces.
B020C030V029	20	30	29	"There are three things which are stately in their march,four which are stately in going:
B020C030V030	20	30	30	The lion, which is mightiest among animals,and doesn't turn away for any;
B020C030V031	20	30	31	the greyhound,the male goat also;and the king against whom there is no rising up.
B020C030V032	20	30	32	"If you have done foolishly in lifting up yourself,or if you have thought evil,put your hand over your mouth.
B020C030V033	20	30	33	For as the churning of milk brings forth butter,and the wringing of the nose brings forth blood;so the forcing of wrath brings forth strife."
B020C031V001	20	31	1	The words of king Lemuel; the oracle which his mother taught him.
B020C031V002	20	31	2	"Oh, my son!Oh, son of my womb!Oh, son of my vows!
B020C031V003	20	31	3	Do not give your strength to women,nor your ways to that which destroys kings.
B020C031V004	20	31	4	It is not for kings, Lemuel;it is not for kings to drink wine;nor for princes to say, 'Where is strong drink?'
B020C031V005	20	31	5	lest they drink, and forget the decree,and pervert the justice due to anyone who is afflicted.
B020C031V006	20	31	6	Give strong drink to him who is ready to perish;and wine to the bitter in soul:
B020C031V007	20	31	7	Let him drink, and forget his poverty,and remember his misery no more.
B020C031V008	20	31	8	Open your mouth for the mute,in the cause of all who are left desolate.
B020C031V009	20	31	9	Open your mouth, judge righteously,and serve justice to the poor and needy."  ALEPH
B020C031V010	20	31	10	Who can find a worthy woman?For her price is far above rubies.  BET
B020C031V011	20	31	11	The heart of her husband trusts in her.He shall have no lack of gain.  GIMEL
B020C031V012	20	31	12	She does him good, and not harm,all the days of her life.  DALET
B020C031V013	20	31	13	She seeks wool and flax,and works eagerly with her hands.  HEY
B020C031V014	20	31	14	She is like the merchant ships.She brings her bread from afar.  VAV
B020C031V015	20	31	15	She rises also while it is yet night,gives food to her household,and portions for her servant girls.  ZAYIN
B020C031V016	20	31	16	She considers a field, and buys it.With the fruit of her hands, she plants a vineyard.  HET
B020C031V017	20	31	17	She girds her waist with strength,and makes her arms strong.  TET
B020C031V018	20	31	18	She perceives that her merchandise is profitable.Her lamp doesn't go out by night.  YOD
B020C031V019	20	31	19	She lays her hands to the distaff,and her hands hold the spindle.  KAPH
B020C031V020	20	31	20	She opens her arms to the poor;yes, she extends her hands to the needy.  LAMED
B020C031V021	20	31	21	She is not afraid of the snow for her household;for all her household are clothed with scarlet.  MEM
B020C031V022	20	31	22	She makes for herself carpets of tapestry.Her clothing is fine linen and purple.  NUN
B020C031V023	20	31	23	Her husband is respected in the gates,when he sits among the elders of the land.  SAMEKH
B020C031V024	20	31	24	She makes linen garments and sells them,and delivers sashes to the merchant.  AYIN
B020C031V025	20	31	25	Strength and dignity are her clothing.She laughs at the time to come.  PEY
B020C031V026	20	31	26	She opens her mouth with wisdom.Faithful instruction is on her tongue.  TZADE
B020C031V027	20	31	27	She looks well to the ways of her household,and doesn't eat the bread of idleness.  QOPH
B020C031V028	20	31	28	Her children rise up and call her blessed.Her husband also praises her:  RESH
B020C031V029	20	31	29	"Many women do noble things,but you excel them all."  SHIN
B020C031V030	20	31	30	Charm is deceitful, and beauty is vain;but a woman who fears 
B020C031V031	20	31	31	Give her of the fruit of her hands!Let her works praise her in the gates!
B021C001V001	21	1	1	The words of the Preacher, the son of David, king in Jerusalem:
B021C001V002	21	1	2	"Vanity of vanities," says the Preacher; "Vanity of vanities, all is vanity."
B021C001V003	21	1	3	What does man gain from all his labor in which he labors under the sun?
B021C001V004	21	1	4	One generation goes, and another generation comes; but the earth remains forever.
B021C001V005	21	1	5	The sun also rises, and the sun goes down, and hurries to its place where it rises.
B021C001V006	21	1	6	The wind goes toward the south, and turns around to the north. It turns around continually as it goes, and the wind returns again to its courses.
B021C001V007	21	1	7	All the rivers run into the sea, yet the sea is not full. To the place where the rivers flow, there they flow again.
B021C001V008	21	1	8	All things are full of weariness beyond uttering. The eye is not satisfied with seeing, nor the ear filled with hearing.
B021C001V009	21	1	9	That which has been is that which shall be; and that which has been done is that which shall be done: and there is no new thing under the sun.
B021C001V010	21	1	10	Is there a thing of which it may be said, "Behold, this is new?" It has been long ago, in the ages which were before us.
B021C001V011	21	1	11	There is no memory of the former; neither shall there be any memory of the latter that are to come, among those that shall come after.
B021C001V012	21	1	12	I, the Preacher, was king over Israel in Jerusalem.
B021C001V013	21	1	13	I applied my heart to seek and to search out by wisdom concerning all that is done under the sky. It is a heavy burden that God has given to the sons of men to be afflicted with.
B021C001V014	21	1	14	I have seen all the works that are done under the sun; and behold, all is vanity and a chasing after wind.
B021C001V015	21	1	15	That which is crooked can't be made straight; and that which is lacking can't be counted.
B021C001V016	21	1	16	I said to myself, "Behold, I have obtained for myself great wisdom above all who were before me in Jerusalem. Yes, my heart has had great experience of wisdom and knowledge."
B021C001V017	21	1	17	I applied my heart to know wisdom, and to know madness and folly. I perceived that this also was a chasing after wind.
B021C001V018	21	1	18	For in much wisdom is much grief; and he who increases knowledge increases sorrow.
B021C002V001	21	2	1	I said in my heart, "Come now, I will test you with mirth: therefore enjoy pleasure;" and behold, this also was vanity.
B021C002V002	21	2	2	I said of laughter, "It is foolishness;" and of mirth, "What does it accomplish?"
B021C002V003	21	2	3	I searched in my heart how to cheer my flesh with wine, my heart yet guiding me with wisdom, and how to lay hold of folly, until I might see what it was good for the sons of men that they should do under heaven all the days of their lives.
B021C002V004	21	2	4	I made myself great works. I built myself houses. I planted myself vineyards.
B021C002V005	21	2	5	I made myself gardens and parks, and I planted trees in them of all kinds of fruit.
B021C002V006	21	2	6	I made myself pools of water, to water from it the forest where trees were reared.
B021C002V007	21	2	7	I bought male servants and female servants, and had servants born in my house. I also had great possessions of herds and flocks, above all who were before me in Jerusalem;
B021C002V008	21	2	8	I also gathered silver and gold for myself, and the treasure of kings and of the provinces. I got myself male and female singers, and the delights of the sons of men-musical instruments, and that of all sorts.
B021C002V009	21	2	9	So I was great, and increased more than all who were before me in Jerusalem. My wisdom also remained with me.
B021C002V010	21	2	10	Whatever my eyes desired, I did not keep from them. I did not withhold my heart from any joy, for my heart rejoiced because of all my labor, and this was my portion from all my labor.
B021C002V011	21	2	11	Then I looked at all the works that my hands had worked, and at the labor that I had labored to do; and behold, all was vanity and a chasing after wind, and there was no profit under the sun.
B021C002V012	21	2	12	I turned myself to consider wisdom, madness, and folly: for what can the king's successor do? Just that which has been done long ago.
B021C002V013	21	2	13	Then I saw that wisdom excels folly, as far as light excels darkness.
B021C002V014	21	2	14	The wise man's eyes are in his head, and the fool walks in darkness-and yet I perceived that one event happens to them all.
B021C002V015	21	2	15	Then said I in my heart, "As it happens to the fool, so will it happen even to me; and why was I then more wise?" Then said I in my heart that this also is vanity.
B021C002V016	21	2	16	For of the wise man, even as of the fool, there is no memory for ever, seeing that in the days to come all will have been long forgotten. Indeed, the wise man must die just like the fool!
B021C002V017	21	2	17	So I hated life, because the work that is worked under the sun was grievous to me; for all is vanity and a chasing after wind.
B021C002V018	21	2	18	I hated all my labor in which I labored under the sun, seeing that I must leave it to the man who comes after me.
B021C002V019	21	2	19	Who knows whether he will be a wise man or a fool? Yet he will have rule over all of my labor in which I have labored, and in which I have shown myself wise under the sun. This also is vanity.
B021C002V020	21	2	20	Therefore I began to cause my heart to despair concerning all the labor in which I had labored under the sun.
B021C002V021	21	2	21	For there is a man whose labor is with wisdom, with knowledge, and with skillfulness; yet he shall leave it for his portion to a man who has not labored for it. This also is vanity and a great evil.
B021C002V022	21	2	22	For what has a man of all his labor, and of the striving of his heart, in which he labors under the sun?
B021C002V023	21	2	23	For all his days are sorrows, and his travail is grief; yes, even in the night his heart takes no rest. This also is vanity.
B021C002V024	21	2	24	There is nothing better for a man than that he should eat and drink, and make his soul enjoy good in his labor. This also I saw, that it is from the hand of God.
B021C002V025	21	2	25	For who can eat, or who can have enjoyment, more than I?
B021C002V026	21	2	26	For to the man who pleases him, God gives wisdom, knowledge, and joy; but to the sinner he gives travail, to gather and to heap up, that he may give to him who pleases God. This also is vanity and a chasing after wind.
B021C003V001	21	3	1	For everything there is a season, and a time for every purpose under heaven:
B021C003V002	21	3	2	a time to be born,and a time to die;a time to plant,and a time to pluck up that which is planted;
B021C003V003	21	3	3	a time to kill,and a time to heal;a time to break down,and a time to build up;
B021C003V004	21	3	4	a time to weep,and a time to laugh;a time to mourn,and a time to dance;
B021C003V005	21	3	5	a time to cast away stones,and a time to gather stones together;a time to embrace,and a time to refrain from embracing;
B021C003V006	21	3	6	a time to seek,and a time to lose;a time to keep,and a time to cast away;
B021C003V007	21	3	7	a time to tear,and a time to sew;a time to keep silence,and a time to speak;
B021C003V008	21	3	8	a time to love,and a time to hate;a time for war,and a time for peace. 
B021C003V009	21	3	9	What profit has he who works in that in which he labors?
B021C003V010	21	3	10	I have seen the burden which God has given to the sons of men to be afflicted with.
B021C003V011	21	3	11	He has made everything beautiful in its time. He has also set eternity in their hearts, yet so that man can't find out the work that God has done from the beginning even to the end.
B021C003V012	21	3	12	I know that there is nothing better for them than to rejoice, and to do good as long as they live.
B021C003V013	21	3	13	Also that every man should eat and drink, and enjoy good in all his labor, is the gift of God.
B021C003V014	21	3	14	I know that whatever God does, it shall be forever. Nothing can be added to it, nor anything taken from it; and God has done it, that men should fear before him.
B021C003V015	21	3	15	That which is has been long ago, and that which is to be has been long ago: and God seeks again that which is passed away.
B021C003V016	21	3	16	Moreover I saw under the sun, in the place of justice, that wickedness was there; and in the place of righteousness, that wickedness was there.
B021C003V017	21	3	17	I said in my heart, "God will judge the righteous and the wicked; for there is a time there for every purpose and for every work."
B021C003V018	21	3	18	I said in my heart, "As for the sons of men, God tests them, so that they may see that they themselves are like animals.
B021C003V019	21	3	19	For that which happens to the sons of men happens to animals. Even one thing happens to them. As the one dies, so the other dies. Yes, they have all one breath; and man has no advantage over the animals: for all is vanity.
B021C003V020	21	3	20	All go to one place. All are from the dust, and all turn to dust again.
B021C003V021	21	3	21	Who knows the spirit of man, whether it goes upward, and the spirit of the animal, whether it goes downward to the earth?"
B021C003V022	21	3	22	Therefore I saw that there is nothing better, than that a man should rejoice in his works; for that is his portion: for who can bring him to see what will be after him?
B021C004V001	21	4	1	Then I returned and saw all the oppressions that are done under the sun: and behold, the tears of those who were oppressed, and they had no comforter; and on the side of their oppressors there was power; but they had no comforter.
B021C004V002	21	4	2	Therefore I praised the dead who have been long dead more than the living who are yet alive.
B021C004V003	21	4	3	Yes, better than them both is him who has not yet been, who has not seen the evil work that is done under the sun.
B021C004V004	21	4	4	Then I saw all the labor and achievement that is the envy of a man's neighbor. This also is vanity and a striving after wind.
B021C004V005	21	4	5	The fool folds his hands together and ruins himself.
B021C004V006	21	4	6	Better is a handful, with quietness, than two handfuls with labor and chasing after wind.
B021C004V007	21	4	7	Then I returned and saw vanity under the sun.
B021C004V008	21	4	8	There is one who is alone, and he has neither son nor brother. There is no end to all of his labor, neither are his eyes satisfied with wealth. For whom then, do I labor, and deprive my soul of enjoyment? This also is vanity, yes, it is a miserable business.
B021C004V009	21	4	9	Two are better than one, because they have a good reward for their labor.
B021C004V010	21	4	10	For if they fall, the one will lift up his fellow; but woe to him who is alone when he falls, and doesn't have another to lift him up.
B021C004V011	21	4	11	Again, if two lie together, then they have warmth; but how can one keep warm alone?
B021C004V012	21	4	12	If a man prevails against one who is alone, two shall withstand him; and a threefold cord is not quickly broken.
B021C004V013	21	4	13	Better is a poor and wise youth than an old and foolish king who doesn't know how to receive admonition any more.
B021C004V014	21	4	14	For out of prison he came forth to be king; yes, even in his kingdom he was born poor.
B021C004V015	21	4	15	I saw all the living who walk under the sun, that they were with the youth, the other, who succeeded him.
B021C004V016	21	4	16	There was no end of all the people, even of all them over whom he was-yet those who come after shall not rejoice in him. Surely this also is vanity and a chasing after wind.
B021C005V001	21	5	1	Guard your steps when you go to God's house; for to draw near to listen is better than to give the sacrifice of fools, for they do not know that they do evil.
B021C005V002	21	5	2	Do not be rash with your mouth, and do not let your heart be hasty to utter anything before God; for God is in heaven, and you on earth. Therefore let your words be few.
B021C005V003	21	5	3	For as a dream comes with a multitude of cares, so a fool's speech with a multitude of words.
B021C005V004	21	5	4	When you vow a vow to God, do not defer to pay it; for he has no pleasure in fools. Pay that which you vow.
B021C005V005	21	5	5	It is better that you should not vow, than that you should vow and not pay.
B021C005V006	21	5	6	Do not allow your mouth to lead you into sin. Do not protest before the messenger that this was a mistake. Why should God be angry at your voice, and destroy the work of your hands?
B021C005V007	21	5	7	For in the multitude of dreams there are vanities, as well as in many words: but you must fear God.
B021C005V008	21	5	8	If you see the oppression of the poor, and the violent taking away of justice and righteousness in a district, do not marvel at the matter: for one official is eyed by a higher one; and there are officials over them.
B021C005V009	21	5	9	Moreover the profit of the earth is for all. The king profits from the field.
B021C005V010	21	5	10	He who loves silver shall not be satisfied with silver; nor he who loves abundance, with increase: this also is vanity.
B021C005V011	21	5	11	When goods increase, those who eat them are increased; and what advantage is there to its owner, except to feast on them with his eyes?
B021C005V012	21	5	12	The sleep of a laboring man is sweet, whether he eats little or much; but the abundance of the rich will not allow him to sleep.
B021C005V013	21	5	13	There is a grievous evil which I have seen under the sun: wealth kept by its owner to his harm.
B021C005V014	21	5	14	Those riches perish by misfortune, and if he has fathered a son, there is nothing in his hand.
B021C005V015	21	5	15	As he came forth from his mother's womb, naked shall he go again as he came, and shall take nothing for his labor, which he may carry away in his hand.
B021C005V016	21	5	16	This also is a grievous evil, that in all points as he came, so shall he go. And what profit does he have who labors for the wind?
B021C005V017	21	5	17	All his days he also eats in darkness, he is frustrated, and has sickness and wrath.
B021C005V018	21	5	18	Behold, that which I have seen to be good and proper is for one to eat and to drink, and to enjoy good in all his labor, in which he labors under the sun, all the days of his life which God has given him; for this is his portion.
B021C005V019	21	5	19	Every man also to whom God has given riches and wealth, and has given him power to eat of it, and to take his portion, and to rejoice in his labor-this is the gift of God.
B021C005V020	21	5	20	For he shall not often reflect on the days of his life; because God occupies him with the joy of his heart.
B021C006V001	21	6	1	There is an evil which I have seen under the sun, and it is heavy on men:
B021C006V002	21	6	2	a man to whom God gives riches, wealth, and honor, so that he lacks nothing for his soul of all that he desires, yet God gives him no power to eat of it, but a foreigner eats it. This is vanity, and it is an evil disease.
B021C006V003	21	6	3	If a man fathers a hundred children, and lives many years, so that the days of his years are many, but his soul is not filled with good, and moreover he has no burial; I say, that a stillborn child is better than he:
B021C006V004	21	6	4	for it comes in vanity, and departs in darkness, and its name is covered with darkness.
B021C006V005	21	6	5	Moreover it has not seen the sun nor known it. This has rest rather than the other.
B021C006V006	21	6	6	Yes, though he live a thousand years twice told, and yet fails to enjoy good, do not all go to one place?
B021C006V007	21	6	7	All the labor of man is for his mouth, and yet the appetite is not filled.
B021C006V008	21	6	8	For what advantage has the wise more than the fool? What has the poor man, that knows how to walk before the living?
B021C006V009	21	6	9	Better is the sight of the eyes than the wandering of the desire. This also is vanity and a chasing after wind.
B021C006V010	21	6	10	Whatever has been, its name was given long ago; and it is known what man is; neither can he contend with him who is mightier than he.
B021C006V011	21	6	11	For there are many words that create vanity. What does that profit man?
B021C006V012	21	6	12	For who knows what is good for man in life, all the days of his vain life which he spends like a shadow? For who can tell a man what will be after him under the sun?
B021C007V001	21	7	1	A good name is better than fine perfume; and the day of death better than the day of one's birth.
B021C007V002	21	7	2	It is better to go to the house of mourning than to go to the house of feasting: for that is the end of all men, and the living should take this to heart.
B021C007V003	21	7	3	Sorrow is better than laughter; for by the sadness of the face the heart is made good.
B021C007V004	21	7	4	The heart of the wise is in the house of mourning; but the heart of fools is in the house of mirth.
B021C007V005	21	7	5	It is better to hear the rebuke of the wise, than for a man to hear the song of fools.
B021C007V006	21	7	6	For as the crackling of thorns under a pot, so is the laughter of the fool. This also is vanity.
B021C007V007	21	7	7	Surely extortion makes the wise man foolish; and a bribe destroys the understanding.
B021C007V008	21	7	8	Better is the end of a thing than its beginning.The patient in spirit is better than the proud in spirit.
B021C007V009	21	7	9	Do not be hasty in your spirit to be angry, for anger rests in the bosom of fools.
B021C007V010	21	7	10	Do not say, "Why were the former days better than these?" For you do not ask wisely about this.
B021C007V011	21	7	11	Wisdom is as good as an inheritance. Yes, it is more excellent for those who see the sun.
B021C007V012	21	7	12	For wisdom is a defense, even as money is a defense; but the excellency of knowledge is that wisdom preserves the life of him who has it.
B021C007V013	21	7	13	Consider the work of God, for who can make that straight, which he has made crooked?
B021C007V014	21	7	14	In the day of prosperity be joyful, and in the day of adversity consider; yes, God has made the one side by side with the other, to the end that man should not find out anything after him.
B021C007V015	21	7	15	All this have I seen in my days of vanity: there is a righteous man who perishes in his righteousness, and there is a wicked man who lives long in his evildoing.
B021C007V016	21	7	16	Do not be overly righteous, neither make yourself overly wise. Why should you destroy yourself?
B021C007V017	21	7	17	Do not be too wicked, neither be foolish. Why should you die before your time?
B021C007V018	21	7	18	It is good that you should take hold of this. Yes, also from that do not withdraw your hand; for he who fears God will come forth from them all.
B021C007V019	21	7	19	Wisdom is a strength to the wise man more than ten rulers who are in a city.
B021C007V020	21	7	20	Surely there is not a righteous man on earth, who does good and doesn't sin.
B021C007V021	21	7	21	Also do not take heed to all words that are spoken, lest you hear your servant curse you;
B021C007V022	21	7	22	for often your own heart knows that you yourself have likewise cursed others.
B021C007V023	21	7	23	All this have I proved in wisdom. I said, "I will be wise;" but it was far from me.
B021C007V024	21	7	24	That which is, is far off and exceedingly deep. Who can find it out?
B021C007V025	21	7	25	I turned around, and my heart sought to know and to search out, and to seek wisdom and the scheme of things, and to know that wickedness is stupidity, and that foolishness is madness.
B021C007V026	21	7	26	I find more bitter than death the woman whose heart is snares and traps, whose hands are chains. Whoever pleases God shall escape from her; but the sinner will be ensnared by her.
B021C007V027	21	7	27	Behold, this have I found, says the Preacher, one to another, to find out the scheme;
B021C007V028	21	7	28	which my soul still seeks; but I have not found: one man among a thousand have I found; but a woman among all those have I not found.
B021C007V029	21	7	29	Behold, this only have I found: that God made man upright; but they search for many schemes.
B021C008V001	21	8	1	Who is like the wise man? And who knows the interpretation of a thing? A man's wisdom makes his face shine, and the hardness of his face is changed.
B021C008V002	21	8	2	I say, "Keep the king's command!" because of the oath to God.
B021C008V003	21	8	3	Do not be hasty to go out of his presence. Do not persist in an evil thing, for he does whatever pleases him,
B021C008V004	21	8	4	for the king's word is supreme. Who can say to him, "What are you doing?"
B021C008V005	21	8	5	Whoever keeps the commandment shall not come to harm, and his wise heart will know the time and procedure.
B021C008V006	21	8	6	For there is a time and procedure for every purpose, although the misery of man is heavy on him.
B021C008V007	21	8	7	For he doesn't know that which will be; for who can tell him how it will be?
B021C008V008	21	8	8	There is no man who has power over the spirit to contain the spirit; neither does he have power over the day of death. There is no discharge in war; neither shall wickedness deliver those who practice it.
B021C008V009	21	8	9	All this have I seen, and applied my mind to every work that is done under the sun. There is a time in which one man has power over another to his hurt.
B021C008V010	21	8	10	So I saw the wicked buried. Indeed they came also from holiness. They went and were forgotten in the city where they did this. This also is vanity.
B021C008V011	21	8	11	Because sentence against an evil work is not executed speedily, therefore the heart of the sons of men is fully set in them to do evil.
B021C008V012	21	8	12	Though a sinner commits crimes a hundred times, and lives long, yet surely I know that it will be better with those who fear God, who are reverent before him.
B021C008V013	21	8	13	But it shall not be well with the wicked, neither shall he lengthen days like a shadow; because he doesn't fear God.
B021C008V014	21	8	14	There is a vanity which is done on the earth, that there are righteous men to whom it happens according to the work of the wicked. Again, there are wicked men to whom it happens according to the work of the righteous. I said that this also is vanity.
B021C008V015	21	8	15	Then I commended mirth, because a man has no better thing under the sun, than to eat, and to drink, and to be joyful: for that will accompany him in his labor all the days of his life which God has given him under the sun.
B021C008V016	21	8	16	When I applied my heart to know wisdom, and to see the business that is done on the earth (for also there is that neither day nor night sees sleep with his eyes),
B021C008V017	21	8	17	then I saw all the work of God, that man can't find out the work that is done under the sun, because however much a man labors to seek it out, yet he won't find it. Yes even though a wise man thinks he can comprehend it, he won't be able to find it.
B021C009V001	21	9	1	For all this I laid to my heart, even to explore all this: that the righteous, and the wise, and their works, are in the hand of God; whether it is love or hatred, man doesn't know it; all is before them.
B021C009V002	21	9	2	All things come alike to all. There is one event to the righteous and to the wicked; to the good, to the clean, to the unclean, to him who sacrifices, and to him who doesn't sacrifice. As is the good, so is the sinner; he who takes an oath, as he who fears an oath.
B021C009V003	21	9	3	This is an evil in all that is done under the sun, that there is one event to all: yes also, the heart of the sons of men is full of evil, and madness is in their heart while they live, and after that they go to the dead.
B021C009V004	21	9	4	For to him who is joined with all the living there is hope; for a living dog is better than a dead lion.
B021C009V005	21	9	5	For the living know that they will die, but the dead do not know anything, neither do they have any more a reward; for the memory of them is forgotten.
B021C009V006	21	9	6	Also their love, their hatred, and their envy has perished long ago; neither have they any more a portion forever in anything that is done under the sun.
B021C009V007	21	9	7	Go your way-eat your bread with joy, and drink your wine with a merry heart; for God has already accepted your works.
B021C009V008	21	9	8	Let your garments be always white, and do not let your head lack oil.
B021C009V009	21	9	9	Live joyfully with the wife whom you love all the days of your life of vanity, which he has given you under the sun, all your days of vanity: for that is your portion in life, and in your labor in which you labor under the sun.
B021C009V010	21	9	10	Whatever your hand finds to do, do it with your might; for there is no work, nor device, nor knowledge, nor wisdom, in Sheol, where you are going.
B021C009V011	21	9	11	I returned, and saw under the sun, that the race is not to the swift, nor the battle to the strong, neither yet bread to the wise, nor yet riches to men of understanding, nor yet favor to men of skill; but time and chance happen to them all.
B021C009V012	21	9	12	For man also doesn't know his time. As the fish that are taken in an evil net, and as the birds that are caught in the snare, even so are the sons of men snared in an evil time, when it falls suddenly on them.
B021C009V013	21	9	13	I have also seen wisdom under the sun in this way, and it seemed great to me.
B021C009V014	21	9	14	There was a little city, and few men within it; and a great king came against it, besieged it, and built great siege works against it.
B021C009V015	21	9	15	Now a poor wise man was found in it, and he by his wisdom delivered the city; yet no man remembered that same poor man.
B021C009V016	21	9	16	Then said I, Wisdom is better than strength. Nevertheless the poor man's wisdom is despised, and his words are not heard.
B021C009V017	21	9	17	The words of the wise heard in quiet are better than the cry of him who rules among fools.
B021C009V018	21	9	18	Wisdom is better than weapons of war; but one sinner destroys much good.
B021C010V001	21	10	1	Dead flies cause the oil of the perfumer to send forth an evil odor; so does a little folly outweigh wisdom and honor.
B021C010V002	21	10	2	A wise man's heart is at his right hand, but a fool's heart at his left.
B021C010V003	21	10	3	Yes also, when the fool walks by the way, his understanding fails him, and he says to everyone that he is a fool.
B021C010V004	21	10	4	If the spirit of the ruler rises up against you, do not leave your place; for gentleness lays great offenses to rest.
B021C010V005	21	10	5	There is an evil which I have seen under the sun, the sort of error which proceeds from the ruler.
B021C010V006	21	10	6	Folly is set in great dignity, and the rich sit in a low place.
B021C010V007	21	10	7	I have seen servants on horses, and princes walking like servants on the earth.
B021C010V008	21	10	8	He who digs a pit may fall into it; and whoever breaks through a wall may be bitten by a snake.
B021C010V009	21	10	9	Whoever carves out stones may be injured by them. Whoever splits wood may be endangered thereby.
B021C010V010	21	10	10	If the axe is blunt, and one doesn't sharpen the edge, then he must use more strength; but skill brings success.
B021C010V011	21	10	11	If the snake bites before it is charmed, then is there no profit for the charmer's tongue.
B021C010V012	21	10	12	The words of a wise man's mouth are gracious; but a fool is swallowed by his own lips.
B021C010V013	21	10	13	The beginning of the words of his mouth is foolishness; and the end of his talk is mischievous madness.
B021C010V014	21	10	14	A fool also multiplies words.Man doesn't know what will be; and that which will be after him, who can tell him?
B021C010V015	21	10	15	The labor of fools wearies every one of them; for he doesn't know how to go to the city.
B021C010V016	21	10	16	Woe to you, land, when your king is a child,and your princes eat in the morning!
B021C010V017	21	10	17	Happy are you, land, when your king is the son of nobles,and your princes eat in due season,for strength, and not for drunkenness!
B021C010V018	21	10	18	By slothfulness the roof sinks in;and through idleness of the hands the house leaks.
B021C010V019	21	10	19	A feast is made for laughter,and wine makes the life glad;and money is the answer for all things.
B021C010V020	21	10	20	Do not curse the king, no, not in your thoughts;and do not curse the rich in your bedchamber:for a bird of the sky may carry your voice,and that which has wings may tell the matter.
B021C011V001	21	11	1	Cast your bread on the waters; for you shall find it after many days.
B021C011V002	21	11	2	Give a portion to seven, yes, even to eight;for you do not know what evil will be on the earth.
B021C011V003	21	11	3	If the clouds are full of rain, they empty themselves on the earth;and if a tree falls toward the south, or toward the north,in the place where the tree falls, there shall it be.
B021C011V004	21	11	4	He who observes the wind won't sow;and he who regards the clouds won't reap.
B021C011V005	21	11	5	As you do not know what is the way of the wind,nor how the bones grow in the womb of her who is with child;even so you do not know the work of God who does all.
B021C011V006	21	11	6	In the morning sow your seed,and in the evening do not withhold your hand;for you do not know which will prosper, whether this or that,or whether they both will be equally good.
B021C011V007	21	11	7	Truly the light is sweet,and a pleasant thing it is for the eyes to see the sun.
B021C011V008	21	11	8	Yes, if a man lives many years, let him rejoice in them all;but let him remember the days of darkness, for they shall be many.All that comes is vanity.
B021C011V009	21	11	9	Rejoice, young man, in your youth,and let your heart cheer you in the days of your youth,and walk in the ways of your heart,and in the sight of your eyes;but know that for all these things God will bring you into judgment.
B021C011V010	21	11	10	Therefore remove sorrow from your heart,and put away evil from your flesh;for youth and the dawn of life are vanity.
B021C012V001	21	12	1	Remember also your Creator in the days of your youth, before the evil days come, and the years draw near,when you will say, "I have no pleasure in them;"
B021C012V002	21	12	2	Before the sun, the light, the moon, and the stars are darkened,and the clouds return after the rain;
B021C012V003	21	12	3	in the day when the keepers of the house shall tremble,and the strong men shall bow themselves,and the grinders cease because they are few,and those who look out of the windows are darkened,
B021C012V004	21	12	4	and the doors shall be shut in the street;when the sound of the grinding is low,and one shall rise up at the voice of a bird,and all the daughters of music shall be brought low;
B021C012V005	21	12	5	yes, they shall be afraid of heights,and terrors will be in the way;and the almond tree shall blossom,and the grasshopper shall be a burden,and desire shall fail;because man goes to his everlasting home,and the mourners go about the streets:
B021C012V006	21	12	6	before the silver cord is severed,or the golden bowl is broken,or the pitcher is broken at the spring,or the wheel broken at the cistern,
B021C012V007	21	12	7	and the dust returns to the earth as it was,and the spirit returns to God who gave it.
B021C012V008	21	12	8	Vanity of vanities, says the Preacher.All is vanity! 
B021C012V009	21	12	9	Further, because the Preacher was wise, he still taught the people knowledge. Yes, he pondered, sought out, and set in order many proverbs.
B021C012V010	21	12	10	The Preacher sought to find out acceptable words, and that which was written blamelessly, words of truth.
B021C012V011	21	12	11	The words of the wise are like goads; and like nails well fastened are words from the masters of assemblies, which are given from one shepherd.
B021C012V012	21	12	12	Furthermore, my son, be admonished: of making many books there is no end; and much study is a weariness of the flesh.
B021C012V013	21	12	13	This is the end of the matter. All has been heard. Fear God, and keep his commandments; for this is the whole duty of man.
B021C012V014	21	12	14	For God will bring every work into judgment, with every hidden thing, whether it is good, or whether it is evil.
B022C001V001	22	1	1	The Song of songs, which is Solomon's. Beloved
B022C001V002	22	1	2	Let him kiss me with the kisses of his mouth;for your love is better than wine.
B022C001V003	22	1	3	Your oils have a pleasing fragrance.Your name is oil poured forth,therefore the virgins love you.
B022C001V004	22	1	4	Take me away with you.Let us hurry.The king has brought me into his chambers.FriendsWe will be glad and rejoice in you.We will praise your love more than wine!BelovedThey are right to love you.
B022C001V005	22	1	5	I am dark, but lovely,you daughters of Jerusalem,like Kedar's tents,like Solomon's curtains.
B022C001V006	22	1	6	Do not stare at me because I am dark,because the sun has scorched me.My mother's sons were angry with me.They made me keeper of the vineyards.I haven't kept my own vineyard.
B022C001V007	22	1	7	Tell me, you whom my soul loves,where you graze your flock,where you rest them at noon;For why should I be as one who is veiledbeside the flocks of your companions?Lover
B022C001V008	22	1	8	If you do not know, most beautiful among women,follow the tracks of the sheep.Graze your young goats beside the shepherds' tents.
B022C001V009	22	1	9	I have compared you, my love,to a steed in Pharaoh's chariots.
B022C001V010	22	1	10	Your cheeks are beautiful with earrings,your neck with strings of jewels.
B022C001V011	22	1	11	We will make you earrings of gold,with studs of silver.Beloved
B022C001V012	22	1	12	While the king sat at his table,my perfume spread its fragrance.
B022C001V013	22	1	13	My beloved is to me a sachet of myrrh,that lies between my breasts.
B022C001V014	22	1	14	My beloved is to me a cluster of henna blossomsfrom the vineyards of En Gedi.Lover
B022C001V015	22	1	15	Behold, you are beautiful, my love.Behold, you are beautiful.Your eyes are doves.Beloved
B022C001V016	22	1	16	Behold, you are beautiful, my beloved, yes, pleasant;and our couch is verdant.Lover
B022C001V017	22	1	17	The beams of our house are cedars.Our rafters are firs.Beloved
B022C002V001	22	2	1	I am a rose of Sharon, a lily of the valleys.Lover
B022C002V002	22	2	2	As a lily among thorns,so is my love among the daughters.Beloved
B022C002V003	22	2	3	As the apple tree among the trees of the wood,so is my beloved among the sons.I sat down under his shadow with great delight,his fruit was sweet to my taste.
B022C002V004	22	2	4	He brought me to the banquet hall.His banner over me is love.
B022C002V005	22	2	5	Strengthen me with raisins,refresh me with apples;For I am faint with love.
B022C002V006	22	2	6	His left hand is under my head.His right hand embraces me.
B022C002V007	22	2	7	I adjure you, daughters of Jerusalem,by the roes, or by the hinds of the field,that you not stir up, nor awaken love,until it so desires.
B022C002V008	22	2	8	The voice of my beloved!Behold, he comes,leaping on the mountains,skipping on the hills.
B022C002V009	22	2	9	My beloved is like a roe or a young hart.Behold, he stands behind our wall!He looks in at the windows.He glances through the lattice.
B022C002V010	22	2	10	My beloved spoke, and said to me,"Rise up, my love, my beautiful one, and come away.
B022C002V011	22	2	11	For, behold, the winter is past.The rain is over and gone.
B022C002V012	22	2	12	The flowers appear on the earth.The time of the singing has come,and the voice of the turtledove is heard in our land.
B022C002V013	22	2	13	The fig tree ripens her green figs.The vines are in blossom.They give forth their fragrance.Arise, my love, my beautiful one,and come away."Lover
B022C002V014	22	2	14	My dove in the clefts of the rock,In the hiding places of the mountainside,Let me see your face.Let me hear your voice;for your voice is sweet, and your face is lovely.
B022C002V015	22	2	15	Catch for us the foxes,the little foxes that spoil the vineyards;for our vineyards are in blossom.Beloved
B022C002V016	22	2	16	My beloved is mine, and I am his.He browses among the lilies.
B022C002V017	22	2	17	Until the day is cool, and the shadows flee away,turn, my beloved,and be like a roe or a young hart on the mountains of Bether.
B022C003V001	22	3	1	By night on my bed, I sought him whom my soul loves.I sought him, but I did not find him.
B022C003V002	22	3	2	I will get up now, and go about the city;in the streets and in the squares I will seek him whom my soul loves.I sought him, but I did not find him.
B022C003V003	22	3	3	The watchmen who go about the city found me;"Have you seen him whom my soul loves?"
B022C003V004	22	3	4	I had scarcely passed from them,when I found him whom my soul loves.I held him, and would not let him go,until I had brought him into my mother's house,into the chamber of her who conceived me.
B022C003V005	22	3	5	I adjure you, daughters of Jerusalem,by the roes, or by the hinds of the field,that you not stir up, nor awaken love,until it so desires.
B022C003V006	22	3	6	Who is this who comes up from the wilderness like pillars of smoke,perfumed with myrrh and frankincense,with all spices of the merchant?
B022C003V007	22	3	7	Behold, it is Solomon's carriage!Sixty mighty men are around it,of the mighty men of Israel.
B022C003V008	22	3	8	They all handle the sword, and are expert in war.Every man has his sword on his thigh,because of fear in the night.
B022C003V009	22	3	9	King Solomon made himself a carriageof the wood of Lebanon.
B022C003V010	22	3	10	He made its pillars of silver,its bottom of gold, its seat of purple,its midst being paved with love,from the daughters of Jerusalem.
B022C003V011	22	3	11	Go forth, you daughters of Zion, and see king Solomon,with the crown with which his mother has crowned him,in the day of his weddings,in the day of the gladness of his heart.Lover
B022C004V001	22	4	1	Behold, you are beautiful, my love. Behold, you are beautiful.Your eyes are doves behind your veil.Your hair is as a flock of goats,that descend from Mount Gilead.
B022C004V002	22	4	2	Your teeth are like a newly shorn flock,which have come up from the washing,where every one of them has twins.None is bereaved among them.
B022C004V003	22	4	3	Your lips are like scarlet thread.Your mouth is lovely.Your temples are like a piece of a pomegranate behind your veil.
B022C004V004	22	4	4	Your neck is like David's tower built for an armory,whereon a thousand shields hang,all the shields of the mighty men.
B022C004V005	22	4	5	Your two breasts are like two fawnsthat are twins of a roe,which feed among the lilies.
B022C004V006	22	4	6	Until the day is cool, and the shadows flee away,I will go to the mountain of myrrh,to the hill of frankincense.
B022C004V007	22	4	7	You are all beautiful, my love.There is no spot in you.
B022C004V008	22	4	8	Come with me from Lebanon, my bride,with me from Lebanon.Look from the top of Amana,from the top of Senir and Hermon,from the lions' dens,from the mountains of the leopards.
B022C004V009	22	4	9	You have ravished my heart, my sister, my bride.You have ravished my heart with one of your eyes,with one chain of your neck.
B022C004V010	22	4	10	How beautiful is your love, my sister, my bride!How much better is your love than wine!The fragrance of your perfumes than all manner of spices!
B022C004V011	22	4	11	Your lips, my bride, drip like the honeycomb.Honey and milk are under your tongue.The smell of your garments is like the smell of Lebanon.
B022C004V012	22	4	12	A locked up garden is my sister, my bride;a locked up spring,a sealed fountain.
B022C004V013	22	4	13	Your shoots are an orchard of pomegranates, with precious fruits:henna with spikenard plants,
B022C004V014	22	4	14	spikenard and saffron,calamus and cinnamon, with every kind of incense tree;myrrh and aloes, with all the best spices,
B022C004V015	22	4	15	a fountain of gardens,a well of living waters,flowing streams from Lebanon.Beloved
B022C004V016	22	4	16	Awake, north wind; and come, you south!Blow on my garden, that its spices may flow out.Let my beloved come into his garden,and taste his precious fruits.Lover
B022C005V001	22	5	1	I have come into my garden, my sister, my bride. I have gathered my myrrh with my spice;I have eaten my honeycomb with my honey;I have drunk my wine with my milk.FriendsEat, friends!Drink, yes, drink abundantly, beloved.Beloved
B022C005V002	22	5	2	I was asleep, but my heart was awake.It is the voice of my beloved who knocks:"Open to me, my sister, my love, my dove, my undefiled;for my head is filled with dew,and my hair with the dampness of the night."
B022C005V003	22	5	3	I have taken off my robe. Indeed, must I put it on?I have washed my feet. Indeed, must I soil them?
B022C005V004	22	5	4	My beloved thrust his hand in through the latch opening.My heart pounded for him.
B022C005V005	22	5	5	I rose up to open for my beloved.My hands dripped with myrrh,my fingers with liquid myrrh,on the handles of the lock.
B022C005V006	22	5	6	I opened to my beloved;but my beloved left; and had gone away.My heart went out when he spoke.I looked for him, but I did not find him.I called him, but he did not answer.
B022C005V007	22	5	7	The watchmen who go about the city found me.They beat me.They bruised me.The keepers of the walls took my cloak away from me.
B022C005V008	22	5	8	I adjure you, daughters of Jerusalem,If you find my beloved,that you tell him that I am faint with love.Friends
B022C005V009	22	5	9	How is your beloved better than another beloved,you fairest among women?How is your beloved better than another beloved,that you do so adjure us?Beloved
B022C005V010	22	5	10	My beloved is white and ruddy.The best among ten thousand.
B022C005V011	22	5	11	His head is like the purest gold.His hair is bushy, black as a raven.
B022C005V012	22	5	12	His eyes are like doves beside the water brooks,washed with milk, mounted like jewels.
B022C005V013	22	5	13	His cheeks are like a bed of spices with towers of perfumes.His lips are like lilies, dropping liquid myrrh.
B022C005V014	22	5	14	His hands are like rings of gold set with beryl.His body is like ivory work overlaid with sapphires.
B022C005V015	22	5	15	His legs are like pillars of marble set on sockets of fine gold.His appearance is like Lebanon, excellent as the cedars.
B022C005V016	22	5	16	His mouth is sweetness;yes, he is altogether lovely.This is my beloved, and this is my friend,daughters of Jerusalem.Friends
B022C006V001	22	6	1	Where has your beloved gone, you fairest among women? Where has your beloved turned, that we may seek him with you?Beloved
B022C006V002	22	6	2	My beloved has gone down to his garden,to the beds of spices,to feed in the gardens, and to gather lilies.
B022C006V003	22	6	3	I am my beloved's, and my beloved is mine.He browses among the lilies,
B022C006V004	22	6	4	You are beautiful, my love, as Tirzah,lovely as Jerusalem,awesome as an army with banners.
B022C006V005	22	6	5	Turn away your eyes from me,for they have overcome me.Your hair is like a flock of goats,that lie along the side of Gilead.
B022C006V006	22	6	6	Your teeth are like a flock of ewes,which have come up from the washing;of which every one has twins;none is bereaved among them.
B022C006V007	22	6	7	Your temples are like a piece of a pomegranate behind your veil.
B022C006V008	22	6	8	There are sixty queens, eighty concubines,and virgins without number.
B022C006V009	22	6	9	My dove, my perfect one, is unique.She is her mother's only daughter.She is the favorite one of her who bore her.The daughters saw her, and called her blessed;the queens and the concubines, and they praised her.
B022C006V010	22	6	10	Who is she who looks forth as the morning,beautiful as the moon,clear as the sun,and awesome as an army with banners?
B022C006V011	22	6	11	I went down into the nut tree grove,to see the green plants of the valley,to see whether the vine budded,and the pomegranates were in flower.
B022C006V012	22	6	12	Without realizing it,my desire set me with my royal people's chariots.Friends
B022C006V013	22	6	13	Return, return, Shulammite!Return, return, that we may gaze at you.LoverWhy do you desire to gaze at the Shulammite,as at the dance of Mahanaim?
B022C007V001	22	7	1	How beautiful are your feet in sandals, prince's daughter! Your rounded thighs are like jewels,the work of the hands of a skillful workman.
B022C007V002	22	7	2	Your body is like a round goblet,no mixed wine is wanting.Your waist is like a heap of wheat,set about with lilies.
B022C007V003	22	7	3	Your two breasts are like two fawns,that are twins of a roe.
B022C007V004	22	7	4	Your neck is like an ivory tower.Your eyes are like the pools in Heshbon by the gate of Bathrabbim.Your nose is like the tower of Lebanon which looks toward Damascus.
B022C007V005	22	7	5	Your head on you is like Carmel.The hair of your head like purple.The king is held captive in its tresses.
B022C007V006	22	7	6	How beautiful and how pleasant you are,love, for delights!
B022C007V007	22	7	7	This, your stature, is like a palm tree,your breasts like its fruit.
B022C007V008	22	7	8	I said, "I will climb up into the palm tree.I will take hold of its fruit."Let your breasts be like clusters of the vine,the smell of your breath like apples,Beloved
B022C007V009	22	7	9	Your mouth like the best wine,that goes down smoothly for my beloved,gliding through the lips of those who are asleep.
B022C007V010	22	7	10	I am my beloved's.His desire is toward me.
B022C007V011	22	7	11	Come, my beloved, let us go forth into the field.Let us lodge in the villages.
B022C007V012	22	7	12	Let's go early up to the vineyards.Let's see whether the vine has budded,its blossom is open,and the pomegranates are in flower.There I will give you my love.
B022C007V013	22	7	13	The mandrakes give forth fragrance.At our doors are all kinds of precious fruits, new and old,which I have stored up for you, my beloved.
B022C008V001	22	8	1	Oh that you were like my brother, who sucked the breasts of my mother!If I found you outside, I would kiss you;yes, and no one would despise me.
B022C008V002	22	8	2	I would lead you, bringing you into my mother's house,who would instruct me.I would have you drink spiced wine,of the juice of my pomegranate.
B022C008V003	22	8	3	His left hand would be under my head.His right hand would embrace me.
B022C008V004	22	8	4	I adjure you, daughters of Jerusalem,that you not stir up, nor awaken love,until it so desires.Friends
B022C008V005	22	8	5	Who is this who comes up from the wilderness,leaning on her beloved?Under the apple tree I aroused you.There your mother conceived you.There she was in labor and bore you.
B022C008V006	22	8	6	Set me as a seal on your heart,as a seal on your arm;for love is strong as death.Jealousy is as cruel as Sheol.Its flashes are flashes of fire,a very flame of Yah.
B022C008V007	22	8	7	Many waters can't quench love,neither can floods drown it.If a man would give all the wealth of his house for love,he would be utterly scorned.Friends
B022C008V008	22	8	8	We have a little sister.She has no breasts.What shall we do for our sisterin the day when she is to be spoken for?
B022C008V009	22	8	9	If she is a wall,we will build on her a turret of silver.If she is a door,we will enclose her with boards of cedar.Beloved
B022C008V010	22	8	10	I am a wall, and my breasts like towers,then I was in his eyes like one who found peace.
B022C008V011	22	8	11	Solomon had a vineyard at Baal Hamon.He leased out the vineyard to keepers.Each was to bring a thousand shekels of silver for its fruit.
B022C008V012	22	8	12	My own vineyard is before me.The thousand are for you, Solomon;two hundred for those who tend its fruit.Lover
B022C008V013	22	8	13	You who dwell in the gardens, with friends in attendance,let me hear your voice!Beloved
B022C008V014	22	8	14	Come away, my beloved!Be like a gazelle or a young stag on the mountains of spices!
B023C001V001	23	1	1	The vision of Isaiah the son of Amoz, which he saw concerning Judah and Jerusalem, in the days of Uzziah, Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah, kings of Judah.
