B044C018V010	44	18	10	for I am with you, and no one will attack you to harm you, for I have many people in this city."
B044C018V011	44	18	11	He lived there a year and six months, teaching the word of God among them.
B044C018V012	44	18	12	But when Gallio was proconsul of Achaia, the Jews with one accord rose up against Paul and brought him before the judgment seat,
B044C018V013	44	18	13	saying, "This man persuades men to worship God contrary to the law."
B044C018V014	44	18	14	But when Paul was about to open his mouth, Gallio said to the Jews, "If indeed it were a matter of wrong or of wicked crime, you Jews, it would be reasonable that I should bear with you;
B044C018V015	44	18	15	but if they are questions about words and names and your own law, look to it yourselves. For I do not want to be a judge of these matters."
B044C018V016	44	18	16	He drove them from the judgment seat.
B044C018V017	44	18	17	Then all laid hold on Sosthenes, the ruler of the synagogue, and beat him before the judgment seat. Gallio did not care about any of these things.
B044C018V018	44	18	18	Paul, having stayed after this many more days, took his leave of the brothers, and sailed from there for Syria, together with Priscilla and Aquila. He shaved his head in Cenchreae, for he had a vow.
B044C018V019	44	18	19	They came to Ephesus, and he left them there; but he himself entered into the synagogue, and reasoned with the Jews.
