B044C022V021	44	22	21	"He said to me, 'Depart, for I will send you out far from here to the Gentiles.'"
B044C022V022	44	22	22	They listened to him until he said that; then they lifted up their voice, and said, "Rid the earth of this fellow, for he is not fit to live!"
B044C022V023	44	22	23	As they yelled, and threw off their cloaks, and threw dust into the air,
B044C022V024	44	22	24	the commanding officer commanded him to be brought into the barracks, ordering him to be examined by scourging, that he might know for what crime they yelled at him like that.
B044C022V025	44	22	25	When they had tied him up with thongs, Paul asked the centurion who stood by, "Is it lawful for you to scourge a man who is a Roman, and not found guilty?"
B044C022V026	44	22	26	When the centurion heard it, he went to the commanding officer and told him, "What are you about to do? For this man is a Roman!"
B044C022V027	44	22	27	The commanding officer came and asked him, "Tell me, are you a Roman?"
B044C022V028	44	22	28	The commanding officer answered, "I bought my citizenship for a great price."
B044C022V029	44	22	29	Immediately those who were about to examine him departed from him, and the commanding officer also was afraid when he realized that he was a Roman, because he had bound him.
B044C022V030	44	22	30	But on the next day, desiring to know the truth about why he was accused by the Judeans, he freed him, and commanded the chief priests and all the council to come together, and brought Paul down and set him before them.
B044C023V001	44	23	1	Paul, looking steadfastly at the council, said, "Brothers, I have lived before God in all good conscience until this day."
B044C023V002	44	23	2	The high priest, Ananias, commanded those who stood by him to strike him on the mouth.
B044C023V003	44	23	3	Then Paul said to him, "God will strike you, you whitewashed wall! Do you sit to judge me according to the Law, and command me to be struck contrary to the law?"
B044C023V004	44	23	4	Those who stood by said, "Do you malign God's high priest?"
B044C023V005	44	23	5	Paul said, "I did not know, brothers, that he was high priest. For it is written, 'You shall not speak evil of a ruler of your people.'"
B044C023V006	44	23	6	But when Paul perceived that the one part were Sadducees and the other Pharisees, he shouted in the council, "Men and brothers, I am a Pharisee, a son of Pharisees. Concerning the hope and resurrection of the dead I am being judged!"
B044C023V007	44	23	7	When he had said this, an argument arose between the Pharisees and Sadducees, and the assembly was divided.
B044C023V008	44	23	8	For the Sadducees say that there is no resurrection, nor angel, nor spirit; but the Pharisees confess all of these.
B044C023V009	44	23	9	A great clamor arose, and some of the scribes of the Pharisees part stood up, and contended, saying, "We find no evil in this man. What if a spirit spoke to him, or an angel?"
B044C023V010	44	23	10	When a great argument arose, the commanding officer, fearing that Paul would be torn in pieces by them, commanded the soldiers to go down and take him by force from among them, and bring him into the barracks.
B044C023V011	44	23	11	The following night, the Lord stood by him, and said, "Cheer up, for as you have testified about me at Jerusalem, so you must testify also at Rome."
B044C023V012	44	23	12	When it was day, the Judeans banded together, and bound themselves under a curse, saying that they would neither eat nor drink until they had killed Paul.
B044C023V013	44	23	13	There were more than forty people who had made this conspiracy.
B044C023V014	44	23	14	They came to the chief priests and the elders, and said, "We have bound ourselves under a great curse, to taste nothing until we have killed Paul.
B044C023V015	44	23	15	Now therefore, you with the council inform the commanding officer that he should bring him down to you, as though you were going to judge his case more exactly. We are ready to kill him before he comes near."
B044C023V016	44	23	16	But Paul's sister's son heard of their lying in wait, and he came and entered into the barracks and told Paul.
B044C023V017	44	23	17	Paul summoned one of the centurions, and said, "Bring this young man to the commanding officer, for he has something to tell him."
B044C023V018	44	23	18	So he took him, and brought him to the commanding officer, and said, "Paul, the prisoner, summoned me and asked me to bring this young man to you, who has something to tell you."
B044C023V019	44	23	19	The commanding officer took him by the hand, and going aside, asked him privately, "What is it that you have to tell me?"
B044C023V020	44	23	20	He said, "The Judeans have agreed to ask you to bring Paul down to the council tomorrow, as though intending to inquire somewhat more accurately concerning him.
B044C023V021	44	23	21	Therefore do not yield to them, for more than forty men lie in wait for him, who have bound themselves under a curse neither to eat nor to drink until they have killed him. Now they are ready, looking for the promise from you."
B044C023V022	44	23	22	So the commanding officer let the young man go, charging him, "Tell no one that you have revealed these things to me."
B044C023V023	44	23	23	He called to himself two of the centurions, and said, "Prepare two hundred soldiers to go as far as Caesarea, with seventy horsemen, and two hundred men armed with spears, at the third hour of the night."
B044C023V024	44	23	24	He asked them to provide animals, that they might set Paul on one, and bring him safely to Felix the governor.
B044C023V025	44	23	25	He wrote a letter like this:
B044C023V026	44	23	26	"Claudius Lysias to the most excellent governor Felix: Greetings.
B044C023V027	44	23	27	"This man was seized by the Judeans, and was about to be killed by them, when I came with the soldiers and rescued him, having learned that he was a Roman.
B044C023V028	44	23	28	Desiring to know the cause why they accused him, I brought him down to their council.
B044C023V029	44	23	29	I found him to be accused about questions of their law, but not to be charged with anything worthy of death or of imprisonment.
B044C023V030	44	23	30	When I was told that there would be a plot against the man, I sent him to you immediately, charging his accusers also to bring their accusations against him before you."
B044C023V031	44	23	31	So the soldiers, carrying out their orders, took Paul and brought him by night to Antipatris.
B044C023V032	44	23	32	But on the next day they left the horsemen to go with him, and returned to the barracks.
B044C023V033	44	23	33	When they came to Caesarea and delivered the letter to the governor, they also presented Paul to him.
B044C023V034	44	23	34	When the governor had read it, he asked what province he was from. When he understood that he was from Cilicia, he said,
B044C023V035	44	23	35	"I will hear you fully when your accusers also arrive." He commanded that he be kept in Herod's palace.
B044C024V001	44	24	1	After five days, the high priest, Ananias, came down with certain elders and an orator, one Tertullus. They informed the governor against Paul.
B044C024V002	44	24	2	When he was called, Tertullus began to accuse him, saying, "Seeing that by you we enjoy much peace, and that by your foresight reforms are coming to this nation,
B044C024V003	44	24	3	we accept it in all ways and in all places, most excellent Felix, with all thankfulness.
B044C024V004	44	24	4	But, that I do not delay you, I entreat you to bear with us and hear a few words.
B044C024V005	44	24	5	For we have found this man to be a plague, an instigator of insurrections among all the Jews throughout the world, and a ringleader of the sect of the Nazarenes.
B044C024V006	44	24	6	He even tried to profane the temple, and we arrested him.
B044C024V008	44	24	8	By examining him yourself you may ascertain all these things of which we accuse him."
B044C024V009	44	24	9	The Judeans also joined in the attack, affirming that these things were so.
B044C024V010	44	24	10	When the governor had beckoned to him to speak, Paul answered, "Because I know that you have been a judge of this nation for many years, I cheerfully make my defense,
B044C024V011	44	24	11	seeing that you can recognize that it is not more than twelve days since I went up to worship at Jerusalem.
B044C024V012	44	24	12	In the temple they did not find me disputing with anyone or stirring up a crowd, either in the synagogues, or in the city.
B044C024V013	44	24	13	Nor can they prove to you the things of which they now accuse me.
B044C024V014	44	24	14	But this I confess to you, that after the Way, which they call a sect, so I serve the God of our fathers, believing all things which are according to the Law, and which are written in the Prophets;
B044C024V015	44	24	15	having hope toward God, which these also themselves look for, that there will be a resurrection, both of the just and unjust.
B044C024V016	44	24	16	Herein I also practice always having a conscience void of offense toward God and men.
B044C024V017	44	24	17	Now after some years, I came to bring gifts for the needy to my nation, and offerings;
B044C024V018	44	24	18	amid which certain Jews from Asia found me purified in the temple, not with a mob, nor with turmoil.
B044C024V019	44	24	19	They ought to have been here before you, and to make accusation, if they had anything against me.
B044C024V020	44	24	20	Or else let these men themselves say what injustice they found in me when I stood before the council,
B044C024V021	44	24	21	unless it is for this one thing that I shouted out standing among them, 'Concerning the resurrection of the dead I am being judged before you today!'"
B044C024V022	44	24	22	But Felix, having more exact knowledge concerning the Way, deferred them, saying, "When Lysias, the commanding officer, comes down, I will decide your case."
B044C024V023	44	24	23	He ordered the centurion that he should be kept in custody, and should have some privileges, and not to forbid any of his friends to serve him or to visit him.
B044C024V024	44	24	24	But after some days, Felix came with Drusilla, his wife, who was a Jewess, and sent for Paul, and heard him concerning the faith in Christ Jesus.
B044C024V025	44	24	25	As he reasoned about righteousness, self-control, and the judgment to come, Felix was terrified, and answered, "Go your way for this time, and when it is convenient for me, I will summon you."
B044C024V026	44	24	26	Meanwhile, he also hoped that money would be given to him by Paul. Therefore also he sent for him more often, and talked with him.
B044C024V027	44	24	27	But when two years were fulfilled, Felix was succeeded by Porcius Festus, and desiring to gain favor with the Judeans, Felix left Paul in bonds.
B044C025V001	44	25	1	Festus therefore, having come into the province, after three days went up to Jerusalem from Caesarea.
B044C025V002	44	25	2	Then the high priest and the principal men of the Judeans informed him against Paul, and they begged him,
B044C025V003	44	25	3	asking a favor against him, that he would summon him to Jerusalem; plotting to kill him on the way.
B044C025V004	44	25	4	However Festus answered that Paul should be kept in custody at Caesarea, and that he himself was about to depart shortly.
B044C025V005	44	25	5	"Let them therefore," said he, "that are in power among you go down with me, and if there is anything wrong in the man, let them accuse him."
B044C025V006	44	25	6	When he had stayed among them more than eight or ten days, he went down to Caesarea, and on the next day he sat on the judgment seat, and commanded Paul to be brought.
B044C025V007	44	25	7	When he had come, the Judeans who had come down from Jerusalem stood around him, bringing against him many and grievous charges which they could not prove,
B044C025V008	44	25	8	while he said in his defense, "Neither against the law of the Jews, nor against the temple, nor against Caesar, have I sinned at all."
B044C025V009	44	25	9	But Festus, desiring to gain favor with the Judeans, answered Paul and said, "Are you willing to go up to Jerusalem, and be judged by me there concerning these things?"
B044C025V010	44	25	10	But Paul said, "I am standing before Caesar's judgment seat, where I ought to be tried. I have done no wrong to the Judeans, as you also know very well.
B044C025V011	44	25	11	For if I have done wrong, and have committed anything worthy of death, I do not refuse to die; but if none of those things is true that they accuse me of, no one can give me up to them. I appeal to Caesar!"
B044C025V012	44	25	12	Then Festus, when he had conferred with the council, answered, "You have appealed to Caesar. To Caesar you shall go."
B044C025V013	44	25	13	Now when some days had passed, Agrippa the King and Bernice arrived at Caesarea, and greeted Festus.
B044C025V014	44	25	14	As they stayed there many days, Festus laid Paul's case before the king, saying, "There is a certain man left a prisoner by Felix;
B044C025V015	44	25	15	about whom, when I was at Jerusalem, the chief priests and the Jewish elders informed me, asking for a sentence against him.
B044C025V016	44	25	16	To whom I answered that it is not the custom of the Romans to give up any man, before the accused has met the accusers face to face, and has had opportunity to make his defense concerning the matter laid against him.
B044C025V017	44	25	17	When therefore they had come together here, I did not delay, but on the next day sat on the judgment seat, and commanded the man to be brought.
B044C025V018	44	25	18	Concerning whom, when the accusers stood up, they brought no charge of such things as I supposed;
B044C025V019	44	25	19	but had certain questions against him about their own religion, and about one Jesus, who was dead, whom Paul affirmed to be alive.
B044C025V020	44	25	20	Being perplexed how to inquire concerning these things, I asked whether he was willing to go to Jerusalem and there be judged concerning these matters.
B044C025V021	44	25	21	But when Paul had appealed to be kept for the decision of the emperor, I commanded him to be kept until I could send him to Caesar."
B044C025V022	44	25	22	Agrippa said to Festus, "I also would like to hear the man myself."
B044C025V023	44	25	23	So on the next day, when Agrippa and Bernice had come with great pomp, and they had entered into the place of hearing with the commanding officers and principal men of the city, at the command of Festus, Paul was brought in.
B044C025V024	44	25	24	Festus said, "King Agrippa, and all men who are here present with us, you see this man, about whom all the multitude of the Judeans petitioned me, both at Jerusalem and here, crying that he ought not to live any longer.
B044C025V025	44	25	25	But when I found that he had committed nothing worthy of death, and as he himself appealed to the emperor I determined to send him.
B044C025V026	44	25	26	Of whom I have no certain thing to write to my lord. Therefore I have brought him forth before you, and especially before you, King Agrippa, that, after examination, I may have something to write.
B044C025V027	44	25	27	For it seems to me unreasonable, in sending a prisoner, not to also specify the charges against him."
B044C026V001	44	26	1	Agrippa said to Paul, "You may speak for yourself."Then Paul stretched out his hand, and made his defense.
B044C026V002	44	26	2	"I think myself happy, King Agrippa, that I am to make my defense before you this day concerning all the things that I am accused by the Judeans,
B044C026V003	44	26	3	especially because you are expert in all customs and questions which are among Jews. Therefore I beg you to hear me patiently.
B044C026V004	44	26	4	"Indeed, all Jews know my way of life from my youth up, which was from the beginning among my own nation and at Jerusalem;
B044C026V005	44	26	5	having known me from the first, if they are willing to testify, that after the strictest sect of our religion I lived a Pharisee.
B044C026V006	44	26	6	Now I stand here to be judged for the hope of the promise made by God to our fathers,
B044C026V007	44	26	7	which our twelve tribes, earnestly serving night and day, hope to attain. Concerning this hope I am accused by the Judeans, O King!
B044C026V008	44	26	8	Why is it judged incredible with you, if God does raise the dead?
B044C026V009	44	26	9	"I myself most certainly thought that I ought to do many things contrary to the name of Jesus of Nazareth.
B044C026V010	44	26	10	This I also did in Jerusalem. I both shut up many of the saints in prisons, having received authority from the chief priests, and when they were put to death I gave my vote against them.
B044C026V011	44	26	11	Punishing them often in all the synagogues, I tried to make them blaspheme. Being exceedingly enraged against them, I persecuted them even to foreign cities.
B044C026V012	44	26	12	"Whereupon as I traveled to Damascus with the authority and commission from the chief priests,
B044C026V013	44	26	13	at noon, O King, I saw on the way a light from the sky, brighter than the sun, shining around me and those who traveled with me.
B044C026V014	44	26	14	When we had all fallen to the earth, I heard a voice saying to me in the Hebrew language, 'Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me? It is hard for you to kick against the goads.'
B044C026V015	44	26	15	"I said, 'Who are you, Lord?'"He said, 'I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting.
B044C026V016	44	26	16	But arise, and stand on your feet, for I have appeared to you for this purpose: to appoint you a servant and a witness both of the things which you have seen, and of the things which I will reveal to you;
B044C026V017	44	26	17	delivering you from the people, and from the Gentiles, to whom I send you,
B044C026V018	44	26	18	to open their eyes, that they may turn from darkness to light and from the power of Satan to God, that they may receive remission of sins and an inheritance among those who are sanctified by faith in me.'
B044C026V019	44	26	19	"Therefore, King Agrippa, I was not disobedient to the heavenly vision,
B044C026V020	44	26	20	but declared first to them of Damascus, at Jerusalem, and throughout all the country of Judea, and also to the Gentiles, that they should repent and turn to God, doing works worthy of repentance.
B044C026V021	44	26	21	For this reason Jews seized me in the temple, and tried to kill me.
B044C026V022	44	26	22	Having therefore obtained the help that is from God, I stand to this day testifying both to small and great, saying nothing but what the Prophets and Moses said would happen,
B044C026V023	44	26	23	how the Messiah must suffer, and how, by the resurrection of the dead, he would be first to proclaim light both to these people and to the Gentiles."
B044C026V024	44	26	24	As he thus made his defense, Festus said with a loud voice, "Paul, you are crazy! Your great learning is driving you insane!"
B044C026V025	44	26	25	But he said, "I am not crazy, most excellent Festus, but boldly declare words of truth and reasonableness.
B044C026V026	44	26	26	For the king knows of these things, to whom also I speak freely. For I am persuaded that none of these things is hidden from him, for this has not been done in a corner.
B044C026V027	44	26	27	King Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know that you believe."
B044C026V028	44	26	28	Agrippa said to Paul, "With a little persuasion are you trying to make me a Christian?"
B044C026V029	44	26	29	Paul said, "I pray to God, that whether with little or with much, not only you, but also all that hear me this day, might become such as I am, except for these bonds."
B044C026V030	44	26	30	The king rose up with the governor, and Bernice, and those who sat with them.
B044C026V031	44	26	31	When they had withdrawn, they spoke one to another, saying, "This man does nothing worthy of death or of bonds."
B044C026V032	44	26	32	Agrippa said to Festus, "This man might have been set free if he had not appealed to Caesar."
B044C027V001	44	27	1	When it was determined that we should sail for Italy, they delivered Paul and certain other prisoners to a centurion named Julius, of the Augustan band.
B044C027V002	44	27	2	Embarking in a ship of Adramyttium, which was about to sail to places on the coast of Asia, we put to sea; Aristarchus, a Macedonian of Thessalonica, being with us.
B044C027V003	44	27	3	The next day, we landed at Sidon. Julius treated Paul kindly, and gave him permission to go to his friends and refresh himself.
B044C027V004	44	27	4	Putting to sea from there, we sailed under the lee of Cyprus, because the winds were contrary.
B044C027V005	44	27	5	When we had sailed across the sea which is off Cilicia and Pamphylia, we came to Myra, a city of Lycia.
B044C027V006	44	27	6	There the centurion found a ship of Alexandria sailing for Italy, and he put us on board.
B044C027V007	44	27	7	When we had sailed slowly many days, and had come with difficulty opposite Cnidus, the wind not allowing us further, we sailed under the lee of Crete, opposite Salmone.
B044C027V008	44	27	8	With difficulty sailing along it we came to a certain place called Fair Havens, near the city of Lasea.
B044C027V009	44	27	9	When much time had passed and the voyage was now dangerous, because the Fast had now already gone by, Paul admonished them,
B044C027V010	44	27	10	and said to them, "Sirs, I perceive that the voyage will be with injury and much loss, not only of the cargo and the ship, but also of our lives."
B044C027V011	44	27	11	But the centurion gave more heed to the master and to the owner of the ship than to those things which were spoken by Paul.
B044C027V012	44	27	12	Because the haven was not suitable to winter in, the majority advised going to sea from there, if by any means they could reach Phoenix, and winter there, which is a port of Crete, looking northeast and southeast.
B044C027V013	44	27	13	When the south wind blew softly, supposing that they had obtained their purpose, they weighed anchor and sailed along Crete, close to shore.
B044C027V014	44	27	14	But before long, a stormy wind beat down from shore, which is called Euraquilo.
B044C027V015	44	27	15	When the ship was caught, and could not face the wind, we gave way to it, and were driven along.
B044C027V016	44	27	16	Running under the lee of a small island called Cauda, we were able, with difficulty, to secure the boat.
B044C027V017	44	27	17	After they had hoisted it up, they used cables to help reinforce the ship. Fearing that they would run aground on the Syrtis sand bars, they lowered the sea anchor, and so were driven along.
B044C027V018	44	27	18	As we labored exceedingly with the storm, the next day they began to throw things overboard.
B044C027V019	44	27	19	On the third day, they threw out the ship's tackle with their own hands.
B044C027V020	44	27	20	When neither sun nor stars shone on us for many days, and no small storm pressed on us, all hope that we would be saved was now taken away.
B044C027V021	44	27	21	When they had been long without food, Paul stood up in the middle of them, and said, "Sirs, you should have listened to me, and not have set sail from Crete, and have gotten this injury and loss.
B044C027V022	44	27	22	Now I exhort you to cheer up, for there will be no loss of life among you, but only of the ship.
B044C027V023	44	27	23	For there stood by me this night an angel, belonging to the God whose I am and whom I serve,
B044C027V024	44	27	24	saying, 'Do not be afraid, Paul. You must stand before Caesar. Behold, God has granted you all those who sail with you.'
B044C027V025	44	27	25	Therefore, sirs, cheer up! For I believe God, that it will be just as it has been spoken to me.
B044C027V026	44	27	26	But we must run aground on a certain island."
B044C027V027	44	27	27	But when the fourteenth night had come, as we were driven back and forth in the Adriatic Sea, about midnight the sailors surmised that they were drawing near to some land.
B044C027V028	44	27	28	They took soundings, and found twenty fathoms. After a little while, they took soundings again, and found fifteen fathoms.
B044C027V029	44	27	29	Fearing that we would run aground on rocky ground, they let go four anchors from the stern, and wished for daylight.
B044C027V030	44	27	30	As the sailors were trying to flee out of the ship, and had lowered the boat into the sea, pretending that they would lay out anchors from the bow,
B044C027V031	44	27	31	Paul said to the centurion and to the soldiers, "Unless these stay in the ship, you cannot be saved."
B044C027V032	44	27	32	Then the soldiers cut away the ropes of the boat, and let it fall off.
B044C027V033	44	27	33	While the day was coming on, Paul begged them all to take some food, saying, "This day is the fourteenth day that you wait and continue fasting, having taken nothing.
B044C027V034	44	27	34	Therefore I beg you to take some food, for this is for your safety; for not a hair will perish from any of your heads."
B044C027V035	44	27	35	When he had said this, and had taken bread, he gave thanks to God in the presence of all, and he broke it, and began to eat.
B044C027V036	44	27	36	Then they all cheered up, and they also took food.
B044C027V037	44	27	37	In all, we were two hundred seventy-six souls on the ship.
B044C027V038	44	27	38	When they had eaten enough, they lightened the ship, throwing out the wheat into the sea.
B044C027V039	44	27	39	When it was day, they did not recognize the land, but they noticed a certain bay with a beach, and they decided to try to drive the ship onto it.
B044C027V040	44	27	40	Casting off the anchors, they left them in the sea, at the same time untying the rudder ropes. Hoisting up the foresail to the wind, they made for the beach.
B044C027V041	44	27	41	But coming to a place where two seas met, they ran the vessel aground. The bow struck and remained immovable, but the stern began to break up by the violence of the waves.
B044C027V042	44	27	42	The soldiers' counsel was to kill the prisoners, so that none of them would swim out and escape.
B044C027V043	44	27	43	But the centurion, desiring to save Paul, stopped them from their purpose, and commanded that those who could swim should throw themselves overboard first to go toward the land;
B044C027V044	44	27	44	and the rest should follow, some on planks, and some on other things from the ship. So it happened that they all escaped safely to the land.
B044C028V001	44	28	1	When we had escaped, then we learned that the island was called Malta.
B044C028V002	44	28	2	The natives showed us uncommon kindness; for they kindled a fire, and received us all, because of the present rain, and because of the cold.
B044C028V003	44	28	3	But when Paul had gathered a bundle of sticks and placed them on the fire, a viper came out because of the heat, and fastened on his hand.
B044C028V004	44	28	4	When the natives saw the creature hanging from his hand, they said one to another, "No doubt this man is a murderer, whom, though he has escaped from the sea, yet Justice has not allowed to live."
B044C028V005	44	28	5	However he shook off the creature into the fire, and was not harmed.
B044C028V006	44	28	6	But they expected that he would have swollen or fallen down dead suddenly, but when they watched for a long time and saw nothing bad happen to him, they changed their minds, and said that he was a god.
B044C028V007	44	28	7	Now in the neighborhood of that place were lands belonging to the chief man of the island, named Publius, who received us, and courteously entertained us for three days.
B044C028V008	44	28	8	It happened that the father of Publius lay sick of fever and dysentery. Paul entered in to him, prayed, and laying his hands on him, healed him.
B044C028V009	44	28	9	Then when this was done, the rest also who had diseases in the island came, and were cured.
B044C028V010	44	28	10	They also honored us with many honors, and when we sailed, they put on board the things that we needed.
B044C028V011	44	28	11	After three months, we set sail in a ship of Alexandria which had wintered in the island, whose sign was "The Twin Brothers."
B044C028V012	44	28	12	Touching at Syracuse, we stayed there three days.
B044C028V013	44	28	13	From there we weighed anchor and arrived at Rhegium. After one day, a south wind sprang up, and on the second day we came to Puteoli,
B044C028V014	44	28	14	where we found brothers, and were entreated to stay with them for seven days. So we came to Rome.
B044C028V015	44	28	15	From there the brothers, when they heard of us, came to meet us as far as The Market of Appius and The Three Taverns. When Paul saw them, he thanked God, and took courage.
B044C028V016	44	28	16	When we entered into Rome, Paul was allowed to stay by himself with the soldier who guarded him.
B044C028V017	44	28	17	It happened that after three days Paul called together those who were the Jewish leaders. When they had come together, he said to them, "I, brothers, though I had done nothing against the people, or the customs of our fathers, still was delivered prisoner from Jerusalem into the hands of the Romans,
B044C028V018	44	28	18	who, when they had examined me, desired to set me free, because there was no cause of death in me.
B044C028V019	44	28	19	But when the Judeans spoke against it, I was constrained to appeal to Caesar, not that I had anything about which to accuse my nation.
B044C028V020	44	28	20	For this cause therefore I asked to see you and to speak with you. For because of the hope of Israel I am bound with this chain."
B044C028V021	44	28	21	They said to him, "We neither received letters from Judea concerning you, nor did any of the brothers come here and report or speak any evil of you.
B044C028V022	44	28	22	But we desire to hear from you what you think. For, as concerning this sect, it is known to us that everywhere it is spoken against."
B044C028V023	44	28	23	When they had appointed him a day, many people came to him at his lodging. He explained to them, testifying about the Kingdom of God, and persuading them concerning Jesus, both from the Law of Moses and from the Prophets, from morning until evening.
B044C028V024	44	28	24	Some believed the things which were spoken, and some disbelieved.
B044C028V025	44	28	25	When they did not agree among themselves, they departed after Paul had spoken one word, "The Holy Spirit spoke rightly through Isaiah, the prophet, to your fathers,
B044C028V026	44	28	26	saying, 'Go to this people, and say,in hearing, you will hear,but will in no way understand.In seeing, you will see,but will in no way perceive.
B044C028V027	44	28	27	For this people's heart has grown callous.Their ears are dull of hearing.Their eyes they have closed.Lest they should see with their eyes,hear with their ears,understand with their heart,and would turn again,and I would heal them.' 
B044C028V028	44	28	28	"Be it known therefore to you, that the salvation of God is sent to the nations. They will also listen." [
B044C028V029	44	28	29	When he had said these words, the Jews departed, having a great dispute among themselves.]
B044C028V030	44	28	30	Paul stayed two whole years in his own rented house, and received all who were coming to him,
B044C028V031	44	28	31	proclaiming the Kingdom of God, and teaching the things concerning the Lord Jesus Christ with all boldness, without hindrance.
B045C001V001	45	1	1	Paul, a servant of Jesus Christ, called to be an apostle, set apart for the Good News of God,
B045C001V002	45	1	2	which he promised before through his prophets in the holy Scriptures,
B045C001V003	45	1	3	concerning his Son, who was born of the seed of David according to the flesh,
B045C001V004	45	1	4	who was declared to be the Son of God with power, according to the Spirit of holiness, by the resurrection from the dead, Jesus Christ our Lord,
B045C001V005	45	1	5	through whom we received grace and the office of apostle, for obedience of faith among all the nations, for his name's sake;
B045C001V006	45	1	6	among whom you are also called to belong to Jesus Christ;
B045C001V007	45	1	7	to all who are in Rome, beloved of God, called to be saints: Grace to you and peace from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B045C001V008	45	1	8	First, I thank my God through Jesus Christ for all of you, that your faith is proclaimed throughout the whole world.
B045C001V009	45	1	9	For God is my witness, whom I serve in my spirit in the Good News of his Son, how unceasingly I make mention of you always in my prayers,
B045C001V010	45	1	10	requesting, if by any means now at last I may be prospered by the will of God to come to you.
B045C001V011	45	1	11	For I long to see you, that I may impart to you some spiritual gift, to the end that you may be established;
B045C001V012	45	1	12	that is, that I with you may be encouraged in you, each of us by the other's faith, both yours and mine.
B045C001V013	45	1	13	Now I do not desire to have you unaware, brothers, that I often planned to come to you, and was hindered so far, that I might have some fruit among you also, even as among the rest of the Gentiles.
B045C001V014	45	1	14	I am debtor both to Greeks and to foreigners, both to the wise and to the foolish.
B045C001V015	45	1	15	So, as much as is in me, I am eager to proclaim the Good News to you also who are in Rome.
B045C001V016	45	1	16	For I am not ashamed of the Good News, for it is the power of God for salvation for everyone who believes; for the Jew first, and also for the Greek.
B045C001V017	45	1	17	For in it is revealed God's righteousness from faith to faith. As it is written, "But the righteous shall live by faith."
B045C001V018	45	1	18	For the wrath of God is revealed from heaven against all ungodliness and unrighteousness of men, who suppress the truth in unrighteousness,
B045C001V019	45	1	19	because that which is known of God is revealed in them, for God revealed it to them.
B045C001V020	45	1	20	For the invisible things of him since the creation of the world are clearly seen, being perceived through the things that are made, even his everlasting power and divine nature; that they may be without excuse.
B045C001V021	45	1	21	Because, knowing God, they did not glorify him as God, neither gave thanks, but became vain in their reasoning, and their senseless heart was darkened.
B045C001V022	45	1	22	Professing themselves to be wise, they became fools,
B045C001V023	45	1	23	and traded the glory of the incorruptible God for the likeness of an image of corruptible man, and of birds, and four-footed animals, and creeping things.
B045C001V024	45	1	24	Therefore God also abandoned them in the lusts of their hearts to uncleanness, that their bodies should be dishonored among themselves,
B045C001V025	45	1	25	who exchanged the truth of God for a lie, and worshiped and served the creature rather than the Creator, who is blessed forever. Amen.
B045C001V026	45	1	26	For this reason, God abandoned them to their degrading passions. For their women changed the natural function into that which is against nature.
B045C001V027	45	1	27	Likewise also the men, leaving the natural function of the woman, burned in their lust toward one another, men doing what is inappropriate with men, and receiving in themselves the due penalty of their error.
B045C001V028	45	1	28	Even as they refused to have God in their knowledge, God abandoned them to a reprobate mind, to do those things which are not fitting;
B045C001V029	45	1	29	being filled with all unrighteousness, sexual immorality, wickedness, covetousness, maliciousness; full of envy, murder, strife, deceit, evil habits, secret slanderers,
B045C001V030	45	1	30	backbiters, hateful to God, insolent, haughty, boastful, inventors of evil things, disobedient to parents,
B045C001V031	45	1	31	without understanding, covenant breakers, without natural affection, unmerciful;
B045C001V032	45	1	32	who, knowing the ordinance of God, that those who practice such things are worthy of death, not only do the same, but also approve of those who practice them.
B045C002V001	45	2	1	Therefore you are without excuse, O man, whoever you are who judge. For in that which you judge another, you condemn yourself. For you who judge practice the same things.
B045C002V002	45	2	2	We know that the judgment of God is according to truth against those who practice such things.
B045C002V003	45	2	3	Do you think this, O man who judges those who practice such things, and do the same, that you will escape the judgment of God?
B045C002V004	45	2	4	Or do you despise the riches of his goodness, forbearance, and patience, not knowing that the goodness of God leads you to repentance?
B045C002V005	45	2	5	But according to your hardness and unrepentant heart you are treasuring up for yourself wrath in the day of wrath, revelation, and of the righteous judgment of God;
B045C002V006	45	2	6	who "will pay back to everyone according to their works:"
B045C002V007	45	2	7	to those who by patience in well-doing seek for glory, honor, and incorruptibility, eternal life;
B045C002V008	45	2	8	but to those who are self-seeking, and do not obey the truth, but obey unrighteousness, will be wrath and indignation,
B045C002V009	45	2	9	oppression and anguish, on every soul of man who works evil, to the Jew first, and also to the Greek.
B045C002V010	45	2	10	But glory, honor, and peace go to every man who works good, to the Jew first, and also to the Greek.
B045C002V011	45	2	11	For there is no partiality with God.
B045C002V012	45	2	12	For as many as have sinned without law will also perish without the law. As many as have sinned under the law will be judged by the law.
B045C002V013	45	2	13	For it is not the hearers of the law who are righteous before God, but the doers of the law will be justified
B045C002V014	45	2	14	(for when Gentiles who do not have the law do by nature the things of the law, these, not having the law, are a law to themselves,
B045C002V015	45	2	15	in that they show the work of the law written in their hearts, their conscience testifying with them, and their thoughts among themselves accusing or else excusing them)
B045C002V016	45	2	16	in the day when God will judge the secrets of men, according to my Good News, by Christ Jesus.
B045C002V017	45	2	17	But if you call yourself a Jew, and rest on the law, and glory in God,
B045C002V018	45	2	18	and know his will, and approve the things that are excellent, being instructed out of the law,
B045C002V019	45	2	19	and are confident that you yourself are a guide of the blind, a light to those who are in darkness,
B045C002V020	45	2	20	a corrector of the foolish, a teacher of children, having in the law the form of knowledge and of the truth.
B045C002V021	45	2	21	You therefore who teach another, do you not teach yourself? You who proclaim that a man should not steal, do you steal?
B045C002V022	45	2	22	You who say a man should not commit adultery. Do you commit adultery? You who abhor idols, do you rob temples?
B045C002V023	45	2	23	You who glory in the law, through your disobedience of the law do you dishonor God?
B045C002V024	45	2	24	For "the name of God is blasphemed among the Gentiles because of you," just as it is written.
B045C002V025	45	2	25	For circumcision indeed profits, if you are a doer of the law, but if you are a transgressor of the law, your circumcision has become uncircumcision.
B045C002V026	45	2	26	If therefore the uncircumcised keep the ordinances of the law, won't his uncircumcision be accounted as circumcision?
B045C002V027	45	2	27	Won't the uncircumcision which is by nature, if it fulfills the law, judge you, who with the letter and circumcision are a transgressor of the law?
B045C002V028	45	2	28	For he is not a Jew who is one outwardly, neither is that circumcision which is outward in the flesh;
B045C002V029	45	2	29	but he is a Jew who is one inwardly, and circumcision is that of the heart, in the spirit not in the letter; whose praise is not from men, but from God.
B045C003V001	45	3	1	Then what advantage does the Jew have? Or what is the profit of circumcision?
B045C003V002	45	3	2	Much in every way! Because first of all, they were entrusted with the oracles of God.
B045C003V003	45	3	3	For what if some were without faith? Will their lack of faith nullify the faithfulness of God?
B045C003V004	45	3	4	May it never be! Yes, let God be found true, but every man a liar. As it is written,
B045C003V005	45	3	5	But if our unrighteousness commends the righteousness of God, what will we say? Is God unrighteous who inflicts wrath? I speak like men do.
B045C003V006	45	3	6	May it never be! For then how will God judge the world?
B045C003V007	45	3	7	For if the truth of God through my lie abounded to his glory, why am I also still judged as a sinner?
B045C003V008	45	3	8	Why not (as we are slanderously reported, and as some affirm that we say), "Let us do evil, that good may come?" Those who say so are justly condemned.
B045C003V009	45	3	9	What then? Are we better than they? No, in no way. For we previously warned both Jews and Greeks, that they are all under sin.
B045C003V010	45	3	10	As it is written, "There is no one righteous;no, not one.
B045C003V011	45	3	11	There is no one who understands.There is no one who seeks after God.
B045C003V012	45	3	12	They have all turned aside.They have together become unprofitable.There is no one who does good,no, not, so much as one."
B045C003V013	45	3	13	"Their throat is an open tomb.With their tongues they have used deceit.""The poison of vipers is under their lips;"
B045C003V014	45	3	14	"Whose mouth is full of cursing and bitterness."
B045C003V015	45	3	15	"Their feet are swift to shed blood.
B045C003V016	45	3	16	Destruction and misery are in their ways.
B045C003V017	45	3	17	The way of peace, they have not known."
B045C003V018	45	3	18	"There is no fear of God before their eyes." 
B045C003V019	45	3	19	Now we know that whatever things the law says, it speaks to those who are under the law, that every mouth may be closed, and all the world may be brought under the judgment of God.
B045C003V020	45	3	20	Because by the works of the law, no flesh will be justified in his sight. For through the law comes the knowledge of sin.
B045C003V021	45	3	21	But now apart from the law, a righteousness of God has been revealed, being testified by the Law and the Prophets;
B045C003V022	45	3	22	even the righteousness of God through faith in Jesus Christ to all those who believe. For there is no distinction,
B045C003V023	45	3	23	for all have sinned, and fall short of the glory of God;
B045C003V024	45	3	24	being justified freely by his grace through the redemption that is in Christ Jesus;
B045C003V025	45	3	25	whom God set forth to be an atoning sacrifice, through faith in his blood, for a demonstration of his righteousness through the passing over of prior sins, in God's forbearance;
B045C003V026	45	3	26	to demonstrate his righteousness at this present time; that he might himself be just, and the justifier of him who has faith in Jesus.
B045C003V027	45	3	27	Where then is the boasting? It is excluded. By what manner of law? Of works? No, but by a law of faith.
B045C003V028	45	3	28	We maintain therefore that a man is justified by faith apart from the works of the law.
B045C003V029	45	3	29	Or is God the God of Jews only? Is not he the God of Gentiles also? Yes, of Gentiles also,
B045C003V030	45	3	30	since indeed there is one God who will justify the circumcised by faith, and the uncircumcised through faith.
B045C003V031	45	3	31	Do we then nullify the law through faith? May it never be! No, we establish the law.
B045C004V001	45	4	1	What then will we say that Abraham, our forefather, has found according to the flesh?
B045C004V002	45	4	2	For if Abraham was justified by works, he has something to boast about, but not toward God.
B045C004V003	45	4	3	For what does the Scripture say? "Abraham believed God, and it was accounted to him for righteousness."
B045C004V004	45	4	4	Now to him who works, the reward is not counted as grace, but as debt.
B045C004V005	45	4	5	But to him who does not work, but believes in him who justifies the ungodly, his faith is accounted for righteousness.
B045C004V006	45	4	6	Even as David also pronounces blessing on the man to whom God counts righteousness apart from works,
B045C004V007	45	4	7	"Blessed are they whose iniquities are forgiven,whose sins are covered.
B045C004V008	45	4	8	Blessed is the man whom 
B045C004V009	45	4	9	Is this blessing then pronounced on the circumcised, or on the uncircumcised also? For we say that faith was accounted to Abraham for righteousness.
B045C004V010	45	4	10	How then was it counted? When he was in circumcision, or in uncircumcision? Not in circumcision, but in uncircumcision.
B045C004V011	45	4	11	He received the sign of circumcision, a seal of the righteousness of the faith which he had while he was in uncircumcision, that he might be the father of all those who believe, though they be in uncircumcision, that righteousness might also be accounted to them.
B045C004V012	45	4	12	The father of circumcision to those who not only are of the circumcision, but who also walk in the steps of that faith of our father Abraham, which he had in uncircumcision.
B045C004V013	45	4	13	For the promise to Abraham and to his seed that he should be heir of the world was not through the law, but through the righteousness of faith.
B045C004V014	45	4	14	For if those who are of the law are heirs, faith is made void, and the promise is made of no effect.
B045C004V015	45	4	15	For the law works wrath, for where there is no law, neither is there disobedience.
B045C004V016	45	4	16	For this cause it is of faith, that it may be according to grace, to the end that the promise may be sure to all the seed, not to that only which is of the law, but to that also which is of the faith of Abraham, who is the father of us all.
B045C004V017	45	4	17	As it is written, "I have made you a father of many nations." This is in the presence of him whom he believed: God, who gives life to the dead, and calls the things that are not, as though they were.
B045C004V018	45	4	18	Who in hope believed against hope, to the end that he might become a father of many nations, according to that which had been spoken, "So will your seed be."
B045C004V019	45	4	19	Without being weakened in faith, he considered his own body, already having been worn out, (he being about a hundred years old), and the deadness of Sarah's womb.
B045C004V020	45	4	20	Yet, looking to the promise of God, he did not waver through unbelief, but grew strong through faith, giving glory to God,
B045C004V021	45	4	21	and being fully assured that what he had promised, he was able also to perform.
B045C004V022	45	4	22	Therefore it also was "reckoned to him for righteousness."
B045C004V023	45	4	23	Now it was not written that it was accounted to him for his sake alone,
B045C004V024	45	4	24	but for our sake also, to whom it will be accounted, who believe in him who raised Jesus, our Lord, from the dead,
B045C004V025	45	4	25	who was delivered up for our trespasses, and was raised for our justification.
B045C005V001	45	5	1	Being therefore justified by faith, we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ;
B045C005V002	45	5	2	through whom we also have our access by faith into this grace in which we stand. We rejoice in hope of the glory of God.
B045C005V003	45	5	3	Not only this, but we also rejoice in our sufferings, knowing that suffering works perseverance;
B045C005V004	45	5	4	and perseverance, proven character; and proven character, hope:
B045C005V005	45	5	5	and hope does not disappoint us, because God's love has been poured out into our hearts through the Holy Spirit who was given to us.
B045C005V006	45	5	6	For while we were yet weak, at the right time Christ died for the ungodly.
B045C005V007	45	5	7	For rarely does one die for the righteous. Yet perhaps for a good person someone might dare to die.
B045C005V008	45	5	8	But God commends his own love toward us, in that while we were yet sinners, Christ died for us.
B045C005V009	45	5	9	Much more then, being now justified by his blood, we will be saved from God's wrath through him.
B045C005V010	45	5	10	For if, while we were enemies, we were reconciled to God through the death of his Son, much more, being reconciled, we will be saved by his life.
B045C005V011	45	5	11	Not only so, but we also rejoice in God through our Lord Jesus Christ, through whom we have now received the reconciliation.
B045C005V012	45	5	12	Therefore, as sin entered into the world through one man, and death through sin; and so death passed to all men, because all sinned.
B045C005V013	45	5	13	For until the law, sin was in the world; but sin is not charged when there is no law.
B045C005V014	45	5	14	Nevertheless death reigned from Adam until Moses, even over those whose sins weren't like Adam's disobedience, who is a foreshadowing of him who was to come.
B045C005V015	45	5	15	But the free gift is not like the trespass. For if by the trespass of the one the many died, much more did the grace of God, and the gift by the grace of the one man, Jesus Christ, abound to the many.
B045C005V016	45	5	16	The gift is not as through one who sinned: for the judgment came by one to condemnation, but the free gift came of many trespasses to justification.
B045C005V017	45	5	17	For if by the trespass of the one, death reigned through the one; so much more will those who receive the abundance of grace and of the gift of righteousness reign in life through the one, Jesus Christ.
B045C005V018	45	5	18	So then as through one trespass, all men were condemned; even so through one act of righteousness, all men were justified to life.
B045C005V019	45	5	19	For as through the one man's disobedience many were made sinners, even so through the obedience of the one, many will be made righteous.
B045C005V020	45	5	20	The law came in besides, that the trespass might abound; but where sin abounded, grace abounded more exceedingly;
B045C005V021	45	5	21	that as sin reigned in death, even so grace might reign through righteousness to eternal life through Jesus Christ our Lord.
B045C006V001	45	6	1	What shall we say then? Shall we continue in sin, that grace may abound?
B045C006V002	45	6	2	May it never be! We who died to sin, how could we live in it any longer?
B045C006V003	45	6	3	Or do you not know that all we who were baptized into Christ Jesus were baptized into his death?
B045C006V004	45	6	4	We were buried therefore with him through baptism to death, that just like Christ was raised from the dead through the glory of the Father, so we also might walk in newness of life.
B045C006V005	45	6	5	For if we have become united with him in the likeness of his death, we will also be part of his resurrection;
B045C006V006	45	6	6	knowing this, that our old man was crucified with him, that the body of sin might be done away with, so that we would no longer be in bondage to sin.
B045C006V007	45	6	7	For he who has died has been freed from sin.
B045C006V008	45	6	8	But if we died with Christ, we believe that we will also live with him;
B045C006V009	45	6	9	knowing that Christ, being raised from the dead, dies no more. Death no more has dominion over him!
B045C006V010	45	6	10	For the death that he died, he died to sin one time; but the life that he lives, he lives to God.
B045C006V011	45	6	11	Thus consider yourselves also to be dead to sin, but alive to God in Christ Jesus.
B045C006V012	45	6	12	Therefore do not let sin reign in your mortal body, that you should obey it in its lusts.
B045C006V013	45	6	13	Neither present your members to sin as instruments of unrighteousness, but present yourselves to God, as alive from the dead, and your members as instruments of righteousness to God.
B045C006V014	45	6	14	For sin will not have dominion over you. For you are not under law, but under grace.
B045C006V015	45	6	15	What then? Shall we sin, because we are not under law, but under grace? May it never be!
B045C006V016	45	6	16	Do you not know that to whom you present yourselves as servants to obedience, his servants you are whom you obey; whether of sin to death, or of obedience to righteousness?
B045C006V017	45	6	17	But thanks be to God, that, whereas you were bondservants of sin, you became obedient from the heart to that form of teaching whereunto you were delivered.
B045C006V018	45	6	18	Being made free from sin, you became bondservants of righteousness.
B045C006V019	45	6	19	I speak in human terms because of the weakness of your flesh, for as you presented your members as servants to uncleanness and to wickedness upon wickedness, even so now present your members as servants to righteousness for sanctification.
B045C006V020	45	6	20	For when you were servants of sin, you were free in regard to righteousness.
B045C006V021	45	6	21	What fruit then did you have at that time in the things of which you are now ashamed? For the end of those things is death.
B045C006V022	45	6	22	But now, being made free from sin, and having become servants of God, you have your fruit of sanctification, and the result of eternal life.
B045C006V023	45	6	23	For the wages of sin is death, but the free gift of God is eternal life in Christ Jesus our Lord.
B045C007V001	45	7	1	Or do you not know, brothers (for I speak to men who know the law), that the law has dominion over a man for as long as he lives?
B045C007V002	45	7	2	For the woman that has a husband is bound by law to the husband while he lives, but if the husband dies, she is discharged from the law of the husband.
B045C007V003	45	7	3	So then if, while the husband lives, she is joined to another man, she would be called an adulteress. But if the husband dies, she is free from the law, so that she is no adulteress, though she is joined to another man.
B045C007V004	45	7	4	Therefore, my brothers, you also were made dead to the law through the body of Christ, that you would be joined to another, to him who was raised from the dead, that we might bring forth fruit to God.
B045C007V005	45	7	5	For when we were in the flesh, the sinful passions which were through the law, worked in our members to bring forth fruit to death.
B045C007V006	45	7	6	But now we have been discharged from the law, having died to that in which we were held; so that we serve in newness of the spirit, and not in oldness of the letter.
B045C007V007	45	7	7	What shall we say then? Is the law sin? May it never be! However, I would not have known sin, except through the law. For I would not have known coveting, unless the law had said, "You shall not covet."
B045C007V008	45	7	8	But sin, finding occasion through the commandment, produced in me all kinds of coveting. For apart from the law, sin is dead.
B045C007V009	45	7	9	I was alive apart from the law once, but when the commandment came, sin revived, and I died.
B045C007V010	45	7	10	The commandment, which was for life, this I found to be for death;
B045C007V011	45	7	11	for sin, finding occasion through the commandment, deceived me, and through it killed me.
B045C007V012	45	7	12	Therefore the law indeed is holy, and the commandment holy, and righteous, and good.
B045C007V013	45	7	13	Did then that which is good become death to me? May it never be! But sin, that it might be shown to be sin, by working death to me through that which is good; that through the commandment sin might become exceeding sinful.
B045C007V014	45	7	14	For we know that the law is spiritual, but I am fleshly, sold under sin.
B045C007V015	45	7	15	For I do not know what I am doing. For I do not practice what I desire to do; but what I hate, that I do.
B045C007V016	45	7	16	But if what I do not desire, that I do, I consent to the law that it is good.
B045C007V017	45	7	17	So now it is no more I that do it, but sin which dwells in me.
B045C007V018	45	7	18	For I know that in me, that is, in my flesh, dwells no good thing. For desire is present with me, but to do that which is good is not.
B045C007V019	45	7	19	For the good which I desire, I do not do; but the evil which I do not desire, that I practice.
B045C007V020	45	7	20	But if what I do not desire, that I do, it is no more I that do it, but sin which dwells in me.
B045C007V021	45	7	21	I find then the law, that, to me, while I desire to do good, evil is present.
B045C007V022	45	7	22	For I delight in God's law after the inward man,
B045C007V023	45	7	23	but I see a different law in my members, warring against the law of my mind, and bringing me into captivity under the law of sin which is in my members.
B045C007V024	45	7	24	What a wretched man I am! Who will deliver me out of the body of this death?
B045C007V025	45	7	25	Thanks be to God through Jesus Christ, our Lord! So then with the mind, I myself serve God's law, but with the flesh, the sin's law.
B045C008V001	45	8	1	There is therefore now no condemnation to those who are in Christ Jesus.
B045C008V002	45	8	2	For the law of the Spirit of life in Christ Jesus made you free from the law of sin and of death.
B045C008V003	45	8	3	For what the law could not do, in that it was weak through the flesh, God did, sending his own Son in the likeness of sinful flesh and for sin, he condemned sin in the flesh;
B045C008V004	45	8	4	that the ordinance of the law might be fulfilled in us, who walk not after the flesh, but after the Spirit.
B045C008V005	45	8	5	For those who live according to the flesh set their minds on the things of the flesh, but those who live according to the Spirit, the things of the Spirit.
B045C008V006	45	8	6	For the mind of the flesh is death, but the mind of the Spirit is life and peace;
B045C008V007	45	8	7	because the mind of the flesh is hostile towards God; for it is not subject to God's law, neither indeed can it be.
B045C008V008	45	8	8	Those who are in the flesh cannot please God.
B045C008V009	45	8	9	But you are not in the flesh but in the Spirit, if it is so that the Spirit of God dwells in you. But if any man does not have the Spirit of Christ, he is not his.
B045C008V010	45	8	10	If Christ is in you, the body is dead because of sin, but the spirit is alive because of righteousness.
B045C008V011	45	8	11	But if the Spirit of him who raised up Jesus from the dead dwells in you, he who raised up Christ Jesus from the dead will also give life to your mortal bodies through his Spirit who dwells in you.
